aS'Diane Craglow was caring for a 14-year-old autistic boy named Connor Leibel in Buckeye, Ariz., one day in July.'
p2242
aS'They took a walk to one of his favorite places, a park in an upscale community called Verrado.'
p2243
aS'She was not hesitant to leave Connor alone for a few minutes while she booked a piano lesson for his sister nearby, because he usually feels safe and comfortable in places that are familiar to him, and he learns to be more independent that way.'
p2244
aS'When Ms. Craglow returned, she couldn\xe2\x80\x99t believe what she saw: a police officer looming over the boy with his handcuffs at the ready, pinning him to the ground against a tree.'
p2245
aS'Connor was screaming, and the police officer, David Grossman, seemed extremely agitated.'
p2246
aS'As Ms. Craglow tried to piece together what had happened, more officers arrived, spilling out of eight patrol cars in response to Officer Grossman\xe2\x80\x99s frantic call for backup.'
p2247
aS'Soon it became clear to Ms. Craglow that the policeman was unaware that Connor has autism, and had interpreted the boy\xe2\x80\x99s rigid, unfamiliar movements \xe2\x80\x94 which included raising a piece of yarn to his nose to sniff it repeatedly \xe2\x80\x94 as a sign of drug intoxication.'
p2248
aS'As a graduate of Arizona\xe2\x80\x99s Drug Evaluation and Classification program, Officer Grossman is certified as a "drug recognition expert".'
p2249
aS'But no one had trained him to recognize one of the classic signs of autism: the repetitive movements that autistic people rely on to manage their anxiety in stressful situations, known as self-stimulation or "stimming".'
p2250
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s what Connor was doing with the string when Officer Grossman noticed him while he was on patrol.'
p2251
aS'Images from Officer Grossman\xe2\x80\x99s body camera show how the encounter turned into a situation that rapidly escalated beyond Connor\xe2\x80\x99s ability to make sense of what was happening to him.'
p2252
aS'When an unfamiliar policeman rushed up to Connor and asked, "What are you doing"?'
p2253
aS'he was honest, as autistic people usually are.'
p2254
aS'"I\xe2\x80\x99m stimming," the boy said brightly.'
p2255
aS'But Officer Grossman was unfamiliar with the word.'
p2256
aS'On the body-cam audio, you can hear the officer\xe2\x80\x99s uncomprehending response: "What"?'
p2257
aS'You can also hear Connor try to calm himself down by saying "I\xe2\x80\x99m O.K., I\xe2\x80\x99m O.K.," as he sustains abrasions on his back, arm and cheek by being held on the ground by the officer.'
p2258
aS'This is basically a   for anyone who cares for someone with a developmental disability, as well as for disabled people themselves, who live every day in fear that their behavior will be misconstrued as suspicious, intoxicated or hostile by law enforcement.'
p2259
aS'And the encounter could have ended up a lot more tragic.'
p2260
aS'Imagine if instead of being fair-haired and rail-thin, Connor had been powerfully built and black or Hispanic.'
p2261
aS'A tense police officer, approaching a young man he thought was a threat to himself or others, might have been tempted to reach for his Taser or service weapon instead of his handcuffs.'
p2262
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s precisely what happened last year in North Miami, Fla., when a young autistic man named Arnaldo Rios briefly wandered from a group home to play with his toy truck on the street, and a passer-by called the police to report an "armed and suicidal" man sitting in the road.'
p2263
aS'When Officer Jonathan Aledda arrived, he had no idea that Mr. Rios had autism; no idea that the black man trying to calm him down, Charles Kinsey, was his behavioral therapist; and no idea that the flashing silver object in Mr. Rios\xe2\x80\x99s hands was a toy, not a weapon.'
p2264
aS'Officer Aledda fired at Mr. Rios.'
p2265
aS'The bullet missed him, but struck Mr. Kinsey in the leg.'
p2266
aS'The therapist survived, but the trauma of the incident resulted in Mr. Rios\xe2\x80\x99s being placed into more  .'
p2267
aS'He was unable to eat, suffered from night terrors and said to himself over and over, " ".'
p2268
aS'In April, state prosecutors   with attempted manslaughter and culpable negligence.'
p2269
aS'Studies show that these kinds of interactions between disabled people and law enforcement are terrifyingly common, and often go unreported.'
p2270
aS'A   published last year by the Ruderman Family Foundation reported, "Disabled individuals make up a third to half of all people killed by law enforcement officers".'
p2271
aS'Connor Leibel\xe2\x80\x99s mother filed a complaint about her son\xe2\x80\x99s treatment that resulted in an internal investigation by the Buckeye Police Department.'
p2272
aS'It not only cleared Officer Grossman but also came to the unsatisfying conclusion that because the autism label covers a large spectrum of symptoms and behaviors it "would be very difficult to teach officers to recognize them all".'
p2273
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s certainly true: Another way to frame the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention\xe2\x80\x99s estimate that   American schoolchildren is on the spectrum is that autistic people make up a large and extremely diverse minority population.'
p2274
aS'But police officers do not have to become experts in every aspect of autism to learn how to recognize people on the spectrum and treat them with respect.'
p2275
aS'Last year I attended a presentation by Rob Zink, an officer from the St. Paul Police Department in Minnesota,   the Cop Autism Response Education Project to train his fellow officers how to interact with autistic people, inspired by his experience of having two sons on the spectrum.'
p2276
aS'Officer Zink pointed out that sirens and flashing lights alone can be catastrophic sensory overload for people with autism, while a calm voice and a reassuring demeanor can go a long way toward de-escalating a tense confrontation.'
p2277
aS'He also stressed that law enforcement personnel should not expect autistic people to behave in the ways that non-autistic people do.'
p2278
aS'For example, officers should not regard a refusal to look them in the eyes as a sign of guilt, as Officer Grossman did with Connor Leibel.'
p2279
aS'In fact, many autistic people find it easier to interpret spoken instructions if they\xe2\x80\x99re   compelled to simultaneously look the speaker in the eyes.'
p2280
aS'Similar programs are underway in several police departments across the country and around the world, but they are still too few and far between.'
p2281
aS'The scarcity of these programs is a sad legacy of the decades when autism was mistakenly believed to be a rare condition, and many autistic people lived out their lives in state-run institutions.'
p2282
aS'Now that we know that autism is common, and comes in all the hues and shades of a broad human spectrum, we need to give law enforcement officers the knowledge that they need to avoid turning a routine call into a life-altering calamity.'
