aS'The U.S. Supreme Court on Tuesday allowed President Donald Trump to broadly implement a ban on refugees entering the country from around the world.'
p2284
aS'The justices granted a request from the Trump administration to block a federal appeals court decision that, according to the Justice Department, would have allowed up to 24,000 additional refugees to enter the United States than would otherwise have been eligible.'
p2285
aS'The Supreme Court ruling gives Trump a partial victory as the high court prepares for a key October hearing on the constitutionality of Trump\xe2\x80\x99s controversial executive order, which banned travelers from six Muslim-majority countries and limited refugee admissions.'
p2286
aS'The March 6 order suspended travel for people from Iran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen for 90 days and locked out most aspiring refugees for 120 days in a move the Republican president argued was needed to prevent terrorist attacks and allow the government to put in place more stringent vetting procedures.'
p2287
aS'The order took effect in late June, following a Supreme Court ruling that narrowed the scope of lower court rulings.'
p2288
aS'In a ruling last week, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said grandparents, aunts, uncles and cousins of legal U.S. residents would be exempt from the travel ban.'
p2289
aS'The Justice Department opted not to appeal that part of the 9th Circuit decision.'
p2290
aS'However, the 9th Circuit also ruled that Trump\xe2\x80\x99s refugee policy was too broad, and the court allowed entry to refugees from around the world if they had a formal offer from a resettlement agency.'
p2291
aS'The Justice Department appealed, and the full Supreme Court on Tuesday sided with the administration in a one-sentence order.'
p2292
aS'Naureen Shah, Amnesty International USA\xe2\x80\x99s senior director of campaigns, said the refugee ban is inherently cruel.'
p2293
aS'"The Supreme Court today has dealt yet another devastating blow to vulnerable people who were on the cusp of obtaining safety for themselves and their families," she said.'
p2294
aS'"They continue to be subjected to unimaginable violence and fear while their lives are in limbo".'
p2295
aS'Earlier on Tuesday the state of Hawaii, which challenged the policy, said in a court filing that the U.S. government could still "bar tens of thousands of refugees from entering the country".'
p2296
aS'All the 9th Circuit ruling did is "protect vulnerable refugees and the American entities that have been eagerly preparing to welcome them to our shores," Hawaii\xe2\x80\x99s lawyers added.'
p2297
aS'Hawaii Attorney General Doug Chin said he respected the Supreme Court\xe2\x80\x99s decision and is preparing for the hearing there on Oct. 10.'
