aS'The U.S. State Department on Wednesday will stop issuing certain kinds of visas to some citizens of Cambodia, Eritrea, Guinea and Sierra Leone because the nations are not taking back their citizens the United States wants to deport.'
p3133
aS'The new policies, laid out in State Department cables reviewed by Reuters on Tuesday and described in a department news briefing, are the latest example of U.S. President Donald Trump\xe2\x80\x99s effort to crack down on immigrants who are in the United States illegally.'
p3134
aS'The cables, sent by Secretary of State Rex Tillerson to consular officials around the world, said the four countries were "denying or unreasonably delaying" the return of their citizens, and that visa restrictions would be lifted in a country if it accepted its deportees.'
p3135
aS'"The Secretary determines the categories of applicants subject to the visa restrictions, and the categories differ slightly country by country," State Department spokeswoman Heather Nauert said in the news briefing on Tuesday.'
p3136
aS'The visa sanctions vary in severity, with Eritrea facing the harshest ones.'
p3137
aS'Any Eritreans who apply in their own country for most U.S. business or tourist visas will be rejected, according to one of the cables.'
p3138
aS'( )  In Guinea, the United States will no longer issue a range of tourist, business and student visas to government officials and their immediate family members who apply from inside the country, another cable said.'
p3139
aS'( )  "We are all surprised by the American authorities\xe2\x80\x99 decision but the foreign minister is at this moment working so that the situation returns to normal," Guinea government spokesman Damantang Albert Camara told Reuters.'
p3140
aS'"It must be understood that Guinea has never wanted to prevent the repatriation of its nationals who are in conflict with American law".'
p3141
aS'In Cambodia, the sanction is tailored.'
p3142
aS'Only Foreign Ministry employees at or above the rank of director general, and their families, who apply inside the country will be barred from getting some visas for personal travel, a third cable said.'
p3143
aS'( )  For Sierra Leone, only Foreign Ministry and immigration officials will be denied tourist and business visas at the U.S. Embassy in Freetown, according to a fourth cable.'
p3144
aS'( )  "American citizens have been harmed because foreign governments refuse to take back their citizens," Thomas Homan, acting director of U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, said in a Department of Homeland Security statement.'
p3145
aS'In each case, there are exceptions for citizens of the four nations who apply for visas from outside their countries, as well as exceptions on humanitarian grounds or for travel "deemed in the interest of the United States".'
p3146
aS'The new rules, which go into effect on Wednesday, do not affect visas that already have been granted.'
p3147
aS'Visa sanctions are allowed by U.S. immigration law to punish countries that refuse to accept their citizens back from the United States.'
p3148
aS'In practice, the United States has rarely taken that step - just twice in the past decade and a half, according to a Department of Homeland Security spokesman.'
p3149
aS'The most recent instance was in October 2016 when the Obama administration stopped issuing visas\xc2\xa0to Gambian government officials and their families because the government was not taking back U.S. deportees from Gambia.'
p3150
aS'\xc2\xa0  Three of the four countries included in the current visa restrictions - Cambodia, Guinea, and Eritrea - were on a July list of nations deemed "recalcitrant" by U.S. immigration authorities.'
p3151
aS'It was unclear immediately why Sierra Leone was included in Tuesday\xe2\x80\x99s action even though it was not on the "recalcitrant" list in July.'
p3152
aS'ICE has had to release roughly 2,137 Guineans and 831 Sierra Leone nationals, many with "serious criminal convictions," the DHS statement said.'
p3153
aS'In addition, around 700 Eritreans and more than 1,900 Cambodians are living in the United States who have been ordered removed, DHS said.'
p3154
aS'DHS officials say in some cases, the agency has had no choice but to release convicted criminals who served prison time but could not be returned to their home country because it refused to take them back.'
p3155
aS'The Trump administration has made it a priority to pressure reluctant countries to take back their citizens.'
p3156
aS'As of July, the 12 nations deemed "recalcitrant" were China, Cuba, Vietnam, Laos, Iran, Cambodia, Burma, Morocco, Hong Kong, South Sudan, Guinea and Eritrea.'
