aS'Last September, Patrik Hermansson, a 25-year-old graduate student from Sweden, went undercover in the world of the extreme right.'
p3290
aS'Posing as a student writing a thesis about the suppression of right-wing speech, he traveled from London to New York to Charlottesville, Va.'
p3291
aS'\xe2\x80\x94 and into the heart of a dangerous movement that is experiencing a profound rejuvenation.'
p3292
aS'Mr. Hermansson, who was sent undercover by the British anti-racist watchdog group  , spent months insinuating himself into the alt-right, using his Swedish nationality (many neo-Nazis are obsessed with Sweden because of its "Nordic" heritage) as a way in.'
p3293
aS'It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t always easy.'
p3294
aS'"You want to punch them in the face," he told me of the people he met undercover.'
p3295
aS'But you can\xe2\x80\x99t do any of those things.'
p3296
aS'"You want to scream and do whatever \xe2\x80\x94 leave. You have to sit and smile".'
p3297
aS'What he learned while undercover is one part of a shocking, comprehensive new   that sheds light on the strange landscape of the alt-right, the much discussed, little understood and largely anonymous far-right movement that exists mostly online and that has come to national attention in part because of its support for Donald Trump.'
p3298
aS'As a result of the growing influence of the far-right social-media ecosystem, once-moribund hate groups in both the United States and Europe \xe2\x80\x94 groups that mostly existed long before "alt-right" entered the vernacular \xe2\x80\x94 are enjoying a striking uptick in recruitment.'
p3299
aS'This latest wave of potential members is young \xe2\x80\x94 teenage and 20-something men (they\xe2\x80\x99re mostly men) appear to be exhibiting interest in far-right ideas in numbers that would have been unthinkable just a few years ago.'
p3300
aS'These young men are being radicalized largely through the work of a popular group of new far-right internet personalities whose videos, blog posts and tweets have been consistently nudging the boundaries of acceptable conversation to the right \xe2\x80\x94 one of the explicit goals of racist extremists everywhere.'
p3301
aS'And while "globalist" may be one of the alt-right\xe2\x80\x99s favorite slurs, Hope Not Hate conclusively shows that the alt-right is itself now a global movement with regular interaction among far-right figures from Scotland to Sweden to Seattle.'
p3302
aS'Mr. Hermansson\xe2\x80\x99s story offers vital insights into these groups\xe2\x80\x99 tactics and their sometimes bizarre practices.'
p3303
aS'During his time undercover, he hung out with heavily armed Holocaust deniers and attended gatherings where extremists drank mead from a traditional Viking horn and prayed to the Norse god Odin.'
p3304
aS'In Charlottesville, he marched alongside hundreds of young neo-Nazis and white supremacists before he was sprayed with Mace by a counterprotester and witnessed  .'
p3305
aS'In Britain, Mr. Hermansson attended a private dinner of extremists where Greg Johnson, a reclusive leading American far-right figure who is editor in chief of Counter-Currents Publishing, explained the need to "mainstream this stuff \xe2\x80\x94 or, more precisely, we need to bring the mainstream towards us".'
p3306
aS'Mr. Johnson later expressed confidence that this process is working.'
p3307
aS'"I see the upward curve in web traffic, and the upward trend in quality and quantity of younger people getting involved," he told Mr. Hermansson in conversation captured on hidden-camera footage.'
p3308
aS'(During that same chat, he said he believed in ethnic homelands and favored telling Jews, "You need to go to Israel or we\xe2\x80\x99re going to freeze you out of our society".'
p3309
aS') This goal of mainstreaming is an abiding fixation of the far right, whose members are well aware of the problems their movement has had with attracting young people in recent decades.'
p3310
aS'At one point in Mr. Hermansson\xe2\x80\x99s footage, Colin Robertson, a far-right YouTube personality who goes by the name Millennial Woes, explained to an older extremist the importance of putting forward a friendly, accessible face: "If we don\xe2\x80\x99t appear like angry misfits, then we will end up making friendships with people who don\xe2\x80\x99t agree with us," he said.'
p3311
aS'Some of Mr. Hermansson\xe2\x80\x99s most arresting footage comes from a June meeting with Jason Reza Jorjani, a founder, along with the American white nationalist Richard Spencer and others, of the AltRight Corporation, an organization established to foster cooperation and coordination among alt-right groups in Europe and North America.'
p3312
aS'Mr. Hermansson and Mr. Jorjani met at an Irish pub near the Empire State Building, where the baby-faced Mr. Jorjani imagined a near future in which, thanks to liberal complacency over the migration crisis, Europe re-embraces fascism: "We will have a Europe, in 2050, where the bank notes have Adolf Hitler, Napoleon Bonaparte, Alexander the Great. And Hitler will be seen like that: like Napoleon, like Alexander, not like some weird monster who is unique in his own category \xe2\x80\x94 no, he is just going to be seen as a great European leader".'
p3313
aS'More shockingly, Mr. Jorjani bragged about his contacts in the American government.'
p3314
aS'"We had connections in the Trump administration \xe2\x80\x94 we were going to do things"!'
p3315
aS'he said at one point.'
p3316
aS'"I had contacts with the Trump administration," he said at another.'
p3317
aS'"Our original vision was the alt-right would become like a policy group for the Trump administration," he explained, and the administration figure "who was the interface was Steve Bannon".'
p3318
aS'Unfortunately, he told Mr. Hermansson, the political establishment was "disconnecting us from the Trump administration, almost completely".'
p3319
aS'(In June, Mr. Bannon hadn\xe2\x80\x99t yet left the White House and returned to Breitbart, the popular and ardently pro-Trump far-right outlet he had led before his time working for Mr. Trump.'
p3320
aS') When I called Mr. Jorjani, he was cagier about his "connections" and "contacts" in the White House.'
p3321
aS'All he meant, he said, was that he had been in touch with people who had a direct line to President Trump, though he wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t say who.'
p3322
aS'Asked to comment, a White House spokeswoman said, "We have no knowledge of any conversations or contact with this person".'
p3323
aS'Either way, Mr. Jorjani said, with the ousters of Michael Flynn in February and then Mr. Bannon in August, he now views the alt-right\xe2\x80\x99s efforts to carve out a place in the White House as having failed.'
p3324
aS'(Mr. Jorjani resigned from the AltRight Corporation in August.'
p3325
aS') If Mr. Jorjani wasn\xe2\x80\x99t exaggerating to Mr. Hermansson, and he did have a relationship with White House officials, that would certainly be alarming.'
p3326
aS'But even if he was exaggerating, it\xe2\x80\x99s still important to understand how messages like his could travel from the far reaches of the right-wing internet and all the way into \xe2\x80\x94 or close to, at least \xe2\x80\x94 the White House.'
p3327
aS'The extreme alt-right are benefiting immensely from the energy being produced by a more moderate \xe2\x80\x94 but still far-right \xe2\x80\x94 faction known as the "alt-light".'
p3328
aS'The alt-light promotes a slightly softer set of messages.'
p3329
aS'Its figures \xe2\x80\x94 such as Milo Yiannopoulos, Paul Joseph Watson and Mike Cernovich \xe2\x80\x94 generally frame their work as part of an effort to defend "the West" or "Western culture" against supposed left-liberal dominance, rather than making explicitly racist appeals.'
p3330
aS'Many of them, in fact, have renounced explicit racism and anti-Semitism, though they will creep up to the line of explicitly racist speech, especially when Islam and immigration are concerned.'
p3331
aS'This apparent moderation partly explains why they tend to have much bigger online audiences than even the most important alt-right figures \xe2\x80\x94 and why Hope Not Hate describes them as "less extreme, more dangerous".'
p3332
aS'Alt-light sites like Breitbart, formerly home to Mr. Yiannopoulos, as well as Prison Planet, where Mr. Watson is editor at large, draw millions of readers and are key nodes in a hyperkinetic network that is endlessly broadcasting viral-friendly far-right news, rumors and incitement.'
p3333
aS'Fluent in the language of online irony and absurdism, and adept at producing successful memes, alt-lighters have pulled off something remarkable: They\xe2\x80\x99ve made far-right ideas hip to a subset of young people, and framed themselves as society\xe2\x80\x99s forgotten underdogs.'
p3334
aS'The alt-light provides its audience easy scapegoats for their social, economic and sexual frustrations: liberals and feminists and migrants and, of course, globalists.'
p3335
aS'The alt-light\xe2\x80\x99s dedicated fan base runs into the millions.'
p3336
aS'Mr. Watson has  , for example, while Mr. Yiannopoulos has more than  .'
p3337
aS'If even a tiny fraction of this base is drafted toward more extreme far-right politics, that would represent a significant influx into hate groups.'
p3338
aS'According to researchers, the key to hooking new recruits into any movement, and to getting them increasingly involved over time, is to simply give them activities to participate in.'
p3339
aS'This often precedes any deep ideological commitment on the recruits\xe2\x80\x99 part and, especially early on, is more about offering them a sense of meaning and community than anything else.'
p3340
aS'Intentionally or not, the far right has deftly applied these insights to the online world.'
p3341
aS'Viewed through the filters of alt-light outlets like Breitbart and Prison Planet, or through Twitter feeds like Mr. Watson\xe2\x80\x99s, the world is a horror show of crimes by migrants, leftist censorship and attacks on common sense.'
p3342
aS'And the best, easiest way to fight back is through social media.'
p3343
aS'The newly initiated are offered many opportunities to participate directly.'
p3344
aS'A teenager in a suburban basement can join a coordinated global effort to spread misinformation about Emmanuel Macron, France\xe2\x80\x99s centrist president, in the hopes of helping far-right leader Marine Le Pen.'
p3345
aS'Anyone who wants to do so can help spread the word about supposed mainstream media censorship of the Muslim "crime wave" the far right says is ravaging Europe.'
p3346
aS'These efforts \xe2\x80\x94 a click, a retweet, a YouTube comment \xe2\x80\x94 come to feel like important parts of an epochal struggle.'
p3347
aS'The far right, once hemmed in by its own parochialism, has manufactured a worldwide online battlefield anyone with internet access can step into.'
p3348
aS'And if you\xe2\x80\x99re one of those newcomers happily playing the part of infantryman in the "meme wars" that rage daily, maybe, along the way, one of your new online Twitter buddies will say to you, "Milo\xe2\x80\x99s O.K., but have you checked out this guy Greg Johnson"?'
p3349
aS'Or maybe they\xe2\x80\x99ll invite you to a closed online forum where ideas about how to protect Europe from Muslim migrants are discussed a bit more, well, frankly.'
p3350
aS'Maybe, if you\xe2\x80\x99re really lucky, you\xe2\x80\x99ll eventually discover a whole new political movement to join.'
p3351
aS'All of which can explain why members of the hard-core alt-right are watching the explosive success of their more moderate counterparts with open glee, unable to believe their good luck.'
p3352
aS'"I\xe2\x80\x99m just fighting less and less opposition to our sorts of ideas when they\xe2\x80\x99re spoken," Mr. Johnson, the Counter-Currents editor, told Mr. Hermansson.'
p3353
aS'His optimism, unfortunately, appears to be well founded.'
p3354
aS'For all of Sunset Park\xe2\x80\x99s celebrated taquerias, dim sum parlors and picturesque piers, the most popular destination in that neighborhood might just be the local branch of the Brooklyn Public Library.'
p3355
aS'Despite its squat concrete frame and fluorescent lights \xe2\x80\x94 a far cry from the neighboring brownstones \xe2\x80\x94 the library draws a capacity crowd most days.'
p3356
aS'On a recent afternoon, students from down the block and around the world scribbled out homework, studied with tutors, practiced English and honed their chess skills.'
p3357
aS'On the walls, posters promoted not just reading but citizenship services and business-planning classes.'
p3358
aS'Parents and children alike sat at banks of computers, indulging in a world of knowledge that many New Yorkers take for granted.'
p3359
aS'It was a hive of activity, one that actually buzzed.'
p3360
aS'Four portable air-conditioners the size of refrigerators blasted air through coiled ducts.'
p3361
aS'One could be forgiven for thinking the place was being fumigated, but really, the central air was broken and has been for years.'
p3362
aS'The patrons of the Sunset Park library, one of the 20 busiest in the city, are hardly alone in their love for, and frustration with, their local branch.'
p3363
aS'Demand for libraries reaches new highs with each passing year (nearly 34 million visits in 2016), while many of New York\xe2\x80\x99s branches are woefully outmoded (the average library is 62 years old).'
p3364
aS'New York, graced with  , was foundational in the library movement.'
p3365
aS'Today, those foundations are crumbling.'
p3366
aS'Despite their popularity, and because of it, the city\xe2\x80\x99s 212 branches face nearly $1.5 billion in capital needs.'
p3367
aS'And that is simply to reach a state of good repair.'
p3368
aS'Chipping away at these needs can seem overwhelming.'
p3369
aS'But New York has an opportunity, one shared by cities across the country, to improve library infrastructure while creating badly needed housing.'
p3370
aS'By using aging branches as sites for development, new libraries may rise with affordable apartments on top.'
p3371
aS'The administration of Mayor Bill de Blasio should seize the chance at sites citywide to link these crucial needs.'
p3372
aS'Michelle de la Uz has made a career of tackling complicated affordable housing projects.'
p3373
aS'As the executive director of the Fifth Avenue Committee, she has helped build hundreds of units inside developments that include community spaces, medical offices and prekindergartens.'
p3374
aS'"It shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t just be the communities that can support these projects \xe2\x80\x94 every neighborhood, and every community, deserves great civic spaces," said Ms. de la Uz, who is also a city planning commissioner.'
p3375
aS'In 2014, the city selected the Fifth Avenue Committee to undertake the novel task of redeveloping the Sunset Park branch.'
p3376
aS'There, an eight-story building will rise, with the first two floors dedicated to a library 75 percent larger than the one there now.'
p3377
aS'The floors above will have 49 apartments, all of which will be rented to low- and middle-income families in perpetuity.'
p3378
aS'Imagine if the city did the same at the branch in Corona, Queens, where cramped quarters force study groups to huddle on the floor; or Red Hook, Brooklyn, where families from the nearby housing projects are eager for more job training; or Brighton Beach, Brooklyn, where rising sea levels and storms like Sandy threaten its very operations.'
p3379
aS'Some might complain that such public-private partnerships do not earn the libraries enough space or money, or that the resulting buildings are too big.'
p3380
aS'Such criticism ignores the complexities of building in the country\xe2\x80\x99s oldest and largest metropolis.'
p3381
aS'These deals do not undermine the libraries within \xe2\x80\x94 they underpin their futures.'
p3382
aS'When cities lack housing, new libraries and capital dollars, here is a way to get all three for the nominal public investment of an underused property, one the public continues to own once it is built.'
p3383
aS'Indeed, New York has already undertaken a number of library partnerships that underscore their promise.'
p3384
aS'Across from the Museum of Modern Art, a new 53rd Street branch has opened beneath a luxury hotel to   positive  .'
p3385
aS'New residential towers, from Battery Park City to the BAM Cultural District in Fort Greene, have incorporated libraries.'
p3386
aS'A similar development underway in Brooklyn Heights has drawn criticism for having only market-rate apartments; this overlooks the $52 million earned in the deal, which is underwriting the Sunset Park project, among others.'
p3387
aS'Admirable as these are, New York has fallen well short of its potential.'
p3388
aS'The city has built only 16 branches the past two decades, a paltry 8 percent increase, and nothing compared with rival metropolitan areas.'
p3389
aS'Other cities are much further ahead.'
p3390
aS'Starting in 1995, Chicago created a master plan tying libraries to community development and has replaced more than three-quarters of its branches.'
p3391
aS'In 1998, Seattle issued the largest library bond in history, allowing for the construction or replacement of all 27 branches.'
p3392
aS'And Columbus, Ohio, unveiled a plan to double, and possibly triple, its system\xe2\x80\x99s square footage over two decades.'
p3393
aS'New York ought to take such an integrated approach to the billion-dollar needs of its libraries.'
p3394
aS'At the very least, it should embrace the partnerships already flourishing here and foster even more.'
p3395
aS'My organization, the Center for an Urban Future, working with the architecture firm Marble Fairbanks, has identified  .'
p3396
aS'These could easily be redeveloped into libraries beneath housing, or even offices or manufacturing centers, depending on a community\xe2\x80\x99s needs.'
p3397
aS'Factoring in some smart rezonings, dozens more libraries could be upgraded in this fashion.'
p3398
aS'The Robin Hood Foundation is seeking to nurture this model.'
p3399
aS'In 2015, the foundation offered the de Blasio administration a challenge grant of $25 million, to be divided among five libraries, one in each borough.'
p3400
aS'A $5 million match from the city effectively covers the cost of building out a library, which would be in a new affordable housing complex.'
p3401
aS'It is akin to the venture in Sunset Park.'
p3402
aS'"The city has used up most of its vacant land, so we really have to get creative about our existing resources," said Beatriz De La Torre, Robin Hood\xe2\x80\x99s managing director of housing.'
p3403
aS'So far, the administration is piloting this effort in only one location,   on the upper reaches of Broadway.'
p3404
aS'But many neighborhoods are clamoring for both affordable housing and expanded library services.'
p3405
aS'Libraries have become 21st-century settlement houses, providing a world of resources under one roof.'
p3406
aS'They help bridge the digital divide, invest in early literacy and lifelong learning, increase language skills and serve as civic hubs.'
p3407
aS'Let\xe2\x80\x99s add affordable housing to the list.'
