aS'ZAGREB, Croatia \xe2\x80\x94 In Sarajevo, Yugoslavia, during the 1984 Winter Olympics, Elvis J. Kurtovic and his Meteors were performing   in a stifling little basement hall before 300 wild punk rock fans.'
p3409
aS'But it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t Dylan\xe2\x80\x99s rendition they were playing, it was their own, a deliberate extension that ostensibly was about the Margaret Thatcher, the prime minister of Britain.'
p3410
aS'But  Elvis J. Kurtovic and his Meteors were singing about \xe2\x80\x94 in an extremely brutal way that should have been unacceptable to the Communist authorities \xe2\x80\x94 Yugoslavia\xe2\x80\x99s own prime minister,  .'
p3411
aS'It was a brilliant trading of identities that mocked the Yugoslav regime and its ideology while playing with the form and content of a three-minute punk song.'
p3412
aS'It could be included in any global anthology of protest punk, though the editors would have to have heard of this strange Sarajevo group, which was led by Mirko Srdic, a 22-year-old engineering student and one of the cleverest and most lucid authors on the Yugoslav rock scene.'
p3413
aS'In their version of the song, Elvis J. Kurtovic and his Meteors accused Planinc \xe2\x80\x94 all while calling her Margaret Thatcher \xe2\x80\x94 of ineptitude and corruption in Kosovo, then a rebellious Yugoslav province.'
p3414
aS'If a journalist had tried to publish anything of the sort, she would have ended up in prison and been banned forever from working for Yugoslav papers.'
p3415
aS'If an ordinary citizen had talked like this in a cafe or on a tram, he would at the very least have been investigated by the police for "spreading false reports and alarming the public".'
p3416
aS'But this was a song that referred to Margaret Thatcher.'
p3417
aS'The police and the Communist Party pretended that it really was about Thatcher, and nothing happened.'
p3418
aS'Punk rock appeared early in Yugoslavia.'
p3419
aS'Yugoslav punk bands already existed by 1977, the year the Clash released its first album in Britain.'
p3420
aS'The first major punk concert, at least that I remember, took place in Pula, a town on the Croatian coast, on March 22, 1978.'
p3421
aS'Soon after, the first LPs came out from bands like Pankrti, from Ljubljana, whose name in Slovene means "illegitimate" or "bastard children".'
p3422
aS'These records were released through state-run record companies, which were under a kind of informal but ever-present party censorship.'
p3423
aS'From the standpoint of the regime these groups had extremely problematic lyrics.'
p3424
aS'They attacked the police, the authorities and the tenets of Communist ideology.'
p3425
aS'But still, they were sung and published with virtually no interference.'
p3426
aS'The reason was simple: It is less dangerous for something to exist in the shop windows of record stores and on the stages of Party-sponsored "houses of culture" than for it to live underground, conspiring against the system.'
p3427
aS'Such was the strategy of the leaders at the time, a group that would be further liberalized after the death of Yugoslavia\xe2\x80\x99s lifelong president, Marshal Josip Broz Tito, in the spring of 1980.'
p3428
aS'Like its British and American counterparts, Yugoslav punk rock was steeped in social scandal and radical political engagement.'
p3429
aS'It was a time when people were able to make a good living, and young people could find regular paid work through youth services (a Party invention that allowed high school and college students to work for money in their spare time), and with their earnings they would go to the Italian border city of Trieste or to Vienna or even to London to witness the new subcultural trends and buy records.'
p3430
aS'Because of this, the music of punk classics like the Clash, the Sex Pistols, the Buzzcocks and the Damned found its way to Yugoslavia, along with that of Patti Smith, the Stooges and New York Dolls.'
p3431
aS'Not everything was the same for us in Yugoslavia as it was in New York or London, though.'
p3432
aS'Yugoslav punk was based on rebellion, with the youth escapism that characterized some parts of the punk scene in the West almost completely absent.'
p3433
aS'Punk rock in Yugoslavia emerged and developed as a way to blaspheme the government and everything \xe2\x80\x94 or almost everything \xe2\x80\x94 that our parents\xe2\x80\x99 generation believed in.'
p3434
aS'The artistry consisted in writing songs that would be more anti-establishment than any before but would not be censored.'
p3435
aS'There was just one topic that was untouchable: Tito.'
p3436
aS'Everything else was allowed.'
p3437
aS'One could sing more or less openly against everything.'
p3438
aS'Even against Communism.'
p3439
aS'Some of these songs sounded like everyday political commentary.'
p3440
aS'During the great strike in the shipyards in Gdansk, Poland, when the labor movement Solidarity, led by the electrician Lech Walesa, had just been formed and was gaining support, the band Azra, from Zagreb, performed   all around Yugoslavia.'
p3441
aS'The song described actual events, railed against the Soviet Union and even mentioned Pope John Paul II.'
p3442
aS'The Soviet Embassy in Belgrade sent an official note to object to the song, but it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t banned The recording of "Poland in My Heart" was actually issued by Jugoton, then the largest and most influential record label in the country.'
p3443
aS'The ideology of Yugoslav punk boiled down to anti-Communism, conscious or unconscious.'
p3444
aS'And here again is the intriguing paradox: Why did the Communist authorities allow an anti-Communist youth subculture to flourish?'
p3445
aS'Yes, it was a useful outlet for youth rebellion.'
p3446
aS'But the other answer to this question became clearer a decade later.'
p3447
aS'In 1990 and \xe2\x80\x9991, Yugoslavia collapsed and Communism was replaced by ethno-nationalism.'
p3448
aS'That was when the old world would destroy itself from within, and yesterday\xe2\x80\x99s Communists, the heads of secret agencies and central committees, would seize power in the Yugoslav republics with lightning speed, transforming themselves into nationalists and right-wingers.'
p3449
aS'The people who at the beginning of the \xe2\x80\x9980s were convening Party conferences to discuss anti-Communist excesses and in the 1990s would take control of the newly established countries never cared much about anti-Communism; they cared about power.'
p3450
aS'Punk and New Wave music in Yugoslavia in the early \xe2\x80\x9980s was a unique phenomenon in the Communist world.'
p3451
aS'In the other countries of Eastern Europe \xe2\x80\x94 with the partial exception of Poland \xe2\x80\x94 punk rock truly appeared only once Communism had practically ceased to be.'
p3452
aS'Russian punk rockers, notably the women from Pussy Riot, revolted against a conservative, Vladimir Putin, at a time when Communism had faded into the past.'
p3453
aS'Punk rock arrived in Russia \xe2\x80\x94 as it had somewhat earlier in Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia \xe2\x80\x94 as a tardy echo of something that had taken place long before in the West, and usually it was merely an imitation of American and British models.'
p3454
aS'For many years, this was how popular and youth culture developed in Yugoslavia, too.'
p3455
aS'But with the liberalization of the political regime, and with the material enrichment of society and the expansion of the middle class, things had begun to change radically by the end of the \xe2\x80\x9970s.'
p3456
aS'In 1968, just a year after it was produced in New York, the Broadway musical "Hair" was staged in Belgrade, a landmark event in Yugoslav popular culture.'
p3457
aS'From Belgrade\xe2\x80\x99s "Hair" to Yugoslav punk rock, and then until the fall of Yugoslavia, things played out largely in synchronicity with the West.'
p3458
aS'In contrast to the Soviet Union and most other Eastern European Communist Parties, whose leaders and commissars saw control of culture, particularly popular and youth culture, as a means of safeguarding their power, the Yugoslav Communists offered culture to their citizens, especially the young, as an outlet to safely relieve social trauma, one that would also present the illusion of freedom.'
p3459
aS'Simply put, in contrast to the Leonid Brezhnev of the Soviet Union, Tito did not think that young people with drums and guitars would bring down the state.'
p3460
aS'And in the end, he was right.'
