aS'Because of the precise nature of Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s business, and the scarcity of competitors, its role censoring internet speech is not just new, it\xe2\x80\x99s  What makes Cloudflare an essential part of the internet is   from barraging clients\xe2\x80\x99 websites with requests that take them offline.'
p4005
aS'Cloudflare is one of the few companies in the world that provide this kind of reliable protection.'
p4006
aS'If you don\xe2\x80\x99t want your website to get taken down by extortionists, jokers, political opposition or hackers, you have to hire Cloudflare or one of its very few competitors.'
p4007
aS'Generally speaking, there are two kinds of corporate players on the internet: companies that build infrastructure through which content flows, and companies that seek to curate content and create a community.'
p4008
aS'Internet service providers like Verizon and Comcast, domain name servers, web hosts and security services providers like Cloudflare are all the former \xe2\x80\x94 or the "pipe".'
p4009
aS'They typically don\xe2\x80\x99t look at the content their clients and customers are putting up, they just give them the means to do it and let it flow.'
p4010
aS'Social media platforms like Facebook are the latter.'
p4011
aS'They encourage their users to create, share and engage with content \xe2\x80\x94 so they look at content all the time and decide whether they want to allow hateful material like that of neo-Nazis to stay up.'
p4012
aS'While there have long been worries about internet service providers favoring access to some content over others, there has been less concern about companies further along the pipeline holding an internet on/off switch.'
p4013
aS'In large part, this is because at other points in the pipeline, users have choice.'
p4014
aS'Private companies can make their own rules, and consumers can choose among them.'
p4015
aS'If GoDaddy won\xe2\x80\x99t register your domain, you can go to Bluehost or thousands of other companies.'
p4016
aS'But the fewer choices you have for the infrastructure you need to stay online, the more serious the consequences when companies refuse service.'
p4017
aS'This is why Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s decision to drop The Daily Stormer is so significant.'
p4018
aS'Denying security service to one Nazi website seems fine now, but what if Cloudflare started suspending service for a political candidate that its chief executive didn\xe2\x80\x99t like?'
p4019
aS'With this move, Cloudflare is wading into the business of evaluating the content of its clients \xe2\x80\x94 something sites like Facebook and Twitter have been wrestling with for years, leading them to develop complex rules and procedures that govern what users are and are not allowed to post.'
p4020
aS'Most agree that it\xe2\x80\x99s appropriate for social media companies to take down certain kinds of content \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s how they ensure our newsfeeds aren\xe2\x80\x99t full of pornography or violence.'
p4021
aS'But that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean we don\xe2\x80\x99t want that type of content to be able to exist   on the internet.'
p4022
aS'Ensuring that sites like Cloudflare remain content-neutral might be necessary to guarantee that.'
p4023
aS'One of the additional difficulties with Cloudflare is that it is not so much a piece of pipe as it is a service.'
p4024
aS'Specifically, it is a paid-for-protection service.'
p4025
aS'Having to hire Cloudflare to protect your website is like having to hire security to protect you from attackers when you speak in the public square.'
p4026
aS'If that security service is the only one in town, and you\xe2\x80\x99ll be silenced if you try to speak without it, maybe that security service shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t pick and choose whom it protects.'
p4027
aS'While regulation should not be done lightly or broadly, there\xe2\x80\x99s a case to be made that we should treat Cloudflare more like the police, who are supposed to equally protect all members of the public.'
p4028
aS'Last week, Matthew Prince, Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s chief executive, acknowledged how much power his company has, and what\xe2\x80\x99s at stake.'
p4029
aS'"The internet is a really important resource for everyone," he said in an interview with  , "but there\xe2\x80\x99s a very limited set of companies that control it and there\xe2\x80\x99s such little accountability to us that it really is quite a dangerous thing".'
p4030
aS'This is the most terrifying realization surrounding Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s removal of a site from the internet: There\xe2\x80\x99s a lack of accountability present at every part of the pipeline and on platforms.'
p4031
aS'The people who run these companies are not elected officials, yet we still expect them to safeguard our basic liberties while also meeting our cultural expectations.'
p4032
aS'For the most part they do: both because it\xe2\x80\x99s good business to meet the expectations of their users, and because most have praiseworthy goals of corporate responsibility.'
p4033
aS'Beyond these minor checks on these companies\xe2\x80\x99 power, we as users have no way to ensure they meet our needs \xe2\x80\x94 and we have no idea what site they\xe2\x80\x99ll take down next.'
p4034
aS'This is a pivotal moment in American history.'
p4035
aS'Do we, as a nation, join the rest of the industrialized world and guarantee comprehensive health care to every person as a human right?'
p4036
aS'Or do we maintain a system that is enormously expensive, wasteful and bureaucratic, and is designed to maximize profits for big insurance companies, the pharmaceutical industry, Wall Street and medical equipment suppliers?'
p4037
aS'We remain the only major country on earth that allows chief executives and stockholders in the health care industry to get incredibly rich, while tens of millions of people suffer because they can\xe2\x80\x99t get the health care they need.'
p4038
aS'This is not what the United States should be about.'
p4039
aS'All over this country, I have heard from Americans who have shared heartbreaking stories about our dysfunctional system.'
p4040
aS'Doctors have told me about patients who died because they put off their medical visits until it was too late.'
p4041
aS'These were people who had no insurance or could not afford out-of-pocket costs imposed by their insurance plans.'
p4042
aS'I have heard from older people who have been forced to split their pills in half because they couldn\xe2\x80\x99t pay the outrageously high price of prescription drugs.'
p4043
aS'Oncologists have told me about cancer patients who have been unable to acquire lifesaving treatments because they could not afford them.'
p4044
aS'This should not be happening in the world\xe2\x80\x99s wealthiest country.'
p4045
aS'Americans should not hesitate about going to the doctor because they do not have enough money.'
p4046
aS'They should not worry that a hospital stay will bankrupt them or leave them deeply in debt.'
p4047
aS'They should be able to go to the doctor they want, not just one in a particular network.'
p4048
aS'They should not have to spend huge amounts of time filling out complicated forms and arguing with insurance companies as to whether or not they have the coverage they expected.'
p4049
aS'Even though 28 million Americans remain uninsured and even more are underinsured, we spend far more per capita on health care than any other industrialized nation.'
p4050
aS'In 2015, the United States spent almost $10,000 per person for health care; the Canadians, Germans, French and British spent less than half of that, while guaranteeing health care to everyone.'
p4051
aS'Further, these countries have higher life expectancy rates and lower infant mortality rates than we do.'
p4052
aS'The reason that our health care system is so outrageously expensive is that it is not designed to provide quality care to all in a cost-effective way, but to provide huge profits to the medical-industrial complex.'
p4053
aS'Layers of bureaucracy associated with the administration of hundreds of individual and complicated insurance plans is stunningly wasteful, costing us hundreds of billions of dollars a year.'
p4054
aS'As the only major country not to negotiate drug prices with the pharmaceutical industry, we spend tens of billions more than we should.'
p4055
aS'The solution to this crisis is not hard to understand.'
p4056
aS'A half-century ago, the United States established Medicare.'
p4057
aS'Guaranteeing comprehensive health benefits to Americans over 65 has proved to be enormously successful, cost-effective and popular.'
p4058
aS'Now is the time to expand and improve Medicare to cover all Americans.'
p4059
aS'This is not a radical idea.'
p4060
aS'I live 50 miles south of the Canadian border.'
p4061
aS'For decades, every man, woman and child in Canada has been guaranteed health care through a single-payer, publicly funded health care program.'
p4062
aS'This system has not only improved the lives of the Canadian people but has also saved families and businesses an immense amount of money.'
p4063
aS'On Wednesday I will introduce the Medicare for All Act in the Senate with 15 co-sponsors and support from dozens of grass-roots organizations.'
p4064
aS'Under this legislation, every family in America would receive comprehensive coverage, and middle-class families would save thousands of dollars a year by eliminating their private insurance costs as we move to a publicly funded program.'
p4065
aS'The transition to the Medicare for All program would take place over four years.'
p4066
aS'In the first year, benefits to older people would be expanded to include dental care, vision coverage and hearing aids, and the eligibility age for Medicare would be lowered to 55.'
p4067
aS'All children under the age of 18 would also be covered.'
p4068
aS'In the second year, the eligibility age would be lowered to 45 and in the third year to 35.'
p4069
aS'By the fourth year, every man, woman and child in the country would be covered by Medicare for All.'
p4070
aS'Needless to say, there will be huge opposition to this legislation from the powerful special interests that profit from the current wasteful system.'
p4071
aS'The insurance companies, the drug companies and Wall Street will undoubtedly devote a lot of money to lobbying, campaign contributions and television ads to defeat this proposal.'
p4072
aS'But they are on the wrong side of history.'
p4073
aS'Guaranteeing health care as a right is important to the American people not just from a moral and financial perspective; it also happens to be what the majority of the American people want.'
p4074
aS'According to an   by The Economist/YouGov, 60 percent of the American people want to "expand Medicare to provide health insurance to every American," including 75 percent of Democrats, 58 percent of independents and 46 percent of Republicans.'
p4075
aS'Now is the time for Congress to stand with the American people and take on the special interests that dominate health care in the United States.'
p4076
aS'Now is the time to extend Medicare to everyone.'
