aS'"Controversies over freedom of speech on college campuses have existed as long as there have been college campuses. But the specific issues vary with each generation".'
p4078
aS'That is the first line of Erwin Chemerinsky\xe2\x80\x99s new book, "Free Speech on Campus," written with Howard Gillman.'
p4079
aS'Mr. Chemerinsky is not only one of the foremost legal scholars on the First Amendment but also a firsthand witness to the free speech debates of today as the new dean of the University of California Berkeley School of Law.'
p4080
aS'Here he talks with Natalie Shutler, the editor of the   column, about hate speech, censorship and what campuses can and can\xe2\x80\x99t do.'
p4081
aS'This interview has been edited and condensed.'
p4082
aS'Hi, Professor!'
p4083
aS'I have spent the past year talking with college students about free speech and, as you know all too well, it\xe2\x80\x99s a contentious topic for them.'
p4084
aS'In this loud internet age, in which provocative opinions are hitting us constantly and from all sides, plenty of students don\xe2\x80\x99t see value in hosting more of the same on their campuses.'
p4085
aS'One thing I appreciate about your new book is that you are thoughtful about these students\xe2\x80\x99 concerns, even if you disagree with their conclusions.'
p4086
aS'I think we have to be attentive to the fact that many students want to restrict speech because of very laudable instincts.'
p4087
aS'They want to protect other students from hate speech.'
p4088
aS'They want to create an inclusive community for all.'
p4089
aS'But the response to hate speech can\xe2\x80\x99t be to prohibit and punish it.'
p4090
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s unconstitutional.'
p4091
aS'We have to find other ways to create inclusive communities.'
p4092
aS'For many students, it\xe2\x80\x99s not just about hate speech, but the kind of speech that creates harm.'
p4093
aS'This term is agonizingly broad and open to wildly different interpretations.'
p4094
aS'But students aren\xe2\x80\x99t wrong in thinking that speech can be a weapon.'
p4095
aS'Students are quite right.'
p4096
aS'We protect speech   of its effects.'
p4097
aS'If speech had no effects, it wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be a fundamental right.'
p4098
aS'Those effects can be positive but they can also be very negative.'
p4099
aS'Speech can cause enormous harm.'
p4100
aS'It can be hurtful, it can cause people to be excluded, and it can interfere with education or employment.'
p4101
aS'Especially in colleges and universities, we have to be attentive to that.'
p4102
aS'But you do take a hard line in your book that even hate speech must be protected.'
p4103
aS'The law under the First Amendment is clear: Hate speech is protected speech.'
p4104
aS'Over 300 colleges and universities adopted hate speech codes in the early 1990s.'
p4105
aS'Every one to be challenged in court was ruled unconstitutional.'
p4106
aS'And there are good reasons for that.'
p4107
aS'After some really ugly incidents at the University of Michigan in the late 1980s, the school adopted a hate speech code that was undoubtedly well intentioned.'
p4108
aS'But a federal court declared it unconstitutional, in part, because it was so vague.'
p4109
aS'It said that there could not be speech that "demeans or stigmatizes" anyone based on race or gender.'
p4110
aS'But what does that mean?'
p4111
aS'A sociobiology student who challenged the law said, "I want to study whether there are inherent differences between women and men. What if my conclusions are deemed stigmatizing on the basis of gender"?'
p4112
aS'And during the years Michigan\xe2\x80\x99s speech code was on the books, more than 20 black students were charged with racist speech by white students.'
p4113
aS'There wasn\xe2\x80\x99t a single instance of a white student being punished for racist speech, even though that was what had prompted the drafting of the Michigan speech code in the first place.'
p4114
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s part of a much bigger historical pattern: As we saw in Michigan, when hate speech codes or laws are adopted, they are most often directed at the very groups they are meant to protect.'
p4115
aS'You make the distinction in your new book that this doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean that the First Amendment is absolute.'
p4116
aS'For example, there is no constitutional protection for a   or for harassment.'
p4117
aS'Campuses can protect students against that kind of speech.'
p4118
aS'But before you address unprotected speech, maybe we should talk a bit about the history of free speech, which you lay out in your book.'
p4119
aS'It is hard to imagine social progress anywhere that wasn\xe2\x80\x99t dependent on freedom of speech.'
p4120
aS'The civil rights protests of the 1960s \xe2\x80\x94 the lunch counter sit-ins, the marches and demonstrations \xe2\x80\x94 were essential to federal civil rights acts and the end of Jim Crow laws that segregated every aspect of the South.'
p4121
aS'The anti-Vietnam War protests were crucial for the end of that war.'
p4122
aS'This has been true throughout American history.'
p4123
aS'The 19th Amendment that gave women the right to vote was the product of demonstrations and speech.'
p4124
aS'Now, as you point out, many students associate free speech with the vitriol of the internet more than they do with the civil rights movement.'
p4125
aS'I feel for them.'
p4126
aS'The internet is terrible.'
p4127
aS'But how do you see things turning around?'
p4128
aS'How do you think students could begin to associate free speech as something for the vulnerable?'
p4129
aS'Some of this is about a lack of education about the history of freedom of speech.'
p4130
aS'I do worry that students today may equate free speech more with cruel or racist posts on Yik Yak than with the civil rights protests of the 1960s.'
p4131
aS'But even when students talk about harm and safety, they need to remember how malleable those terms are.'
p4132
aS'There is no doubt that the civil rights protests deeply offended many Southerners, however objectionable that may sound to us today.'
p4133
aS'An example like that illustrates why offensiveness to an audience can\xe2\x80\x99t justify stopping speech.'
p4134
aS'Identity is important to nearly every college student I talk to, regardless of their background or political persuasion.'
p4135
aS'You make the case that free speech is the basis for asserting identities and, in particular, was necessary for the expansion in public of countercultural identities \xe2\x80\x94 including, and I\xe2\x80\x99m reading straight from the book here, "forms of expression that challenge traditional religion, prevailing social mores, familiar lifestyle choices, inherited views about sexuality, or historic gender roles".'
p4136
aS'But of course, some identities are much more vulnerable to intimidation than others.'
p4137
aS'You argue that college administrations need not ignore that.'
p4138
aS'An administration can\xe2\x80\x99t bar a campus speaker, but it can engage in its own speech by reaffirming the social standards of the community and reaching out to students who might be offended or hurt.'
p4139
aS'Campuses don\xe2\x80\x99t need to stand behind offensive speakers; they just need to allow them the opportunity to speak.'
p4140
aS'I think it\xe2\x80\x99s so important for campus officials to respond to and condemn hate speech.'
p4141
aS'Just because the First Amendment protects a right to say something, that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean it   be said.'
p4142
aS'Campus officials can describe the type of community they want to create and denounce hate speech as inconsistent with it.'
p4143
aS'Many years ago, when I was teaching at the University of Southern California Law School, someone wrote a very offensive homophobic slur on a chalkboard.'
p4144
aS'The dean did not try to find out who did it or threaten punishment.'
p4145
aS'Instead, he wrote a very powerful statement about why what happened was inconsistent with the community we aspired to be.'
p4146
aS'His message had an enormously positive effect.'
p4147
aS'Also, it is very important that the students themselves respond to offensive speech.'
p4148
aS'They can hold counter-demonstrations, teach-ins and protests.'
p4149
aS'All of that is protected speech.'
p4150
aS'They just can\xe2\x80\x99t protest in a way that interferes with the ability of others to speak.'
p4151
aS'The law is clear that even in places that are open to speech, there can be time, place and manner restrictions, so long as there are adequate places for free speech.'
p4152
aS'There is a right to speak on the campus, but there is no right to come into my classroom and shout me down.'
p4153
aS'There is a right to use public streets and sidewalks, but a city can prevent trucks with sound amplification equipment from playing music in the middle of the night.'
p4154
aS'Dormitories are also a very special place of repose for students.'
p4155
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s their home, and the Supreme Court has recognized the protection of privacy of people in their homes.'
p4156
aS'So there can be much greater restrictions in dormitories \xe2\x80\x94 but it always has to be content neutral.'
p4157
aS'It can\xe2\x80\x99t be based on content or message.'
p4158
aS'Right, so you could say that no one is allowed to hang flags from their window, but not that no one is allowed to hang Confederate flags from their window.'
p4159
aS'Exactly.'
p4160
aS'Obviously violence \xe2\x80\x94 like what we saw in Charlottesville and could presumably expect near other college towns in the coming year \xe2\x80\x94 is not protected by the Constitution.'
p4161
aS'But I have heard from many students that they are frustrated with the idea that people of color and other vulnerable demographic groups are responsible for staying nonviolent and peaceful when aggressive demonstrators march on their colleges.'
p4162
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s not that they want violence, but that they feel that they are being told to respond to aggression with passivity.'
p4163
aS'Could you comment on that?'
p4164
aS'I certainly understand where they are coming from.'
p4165
aS'There is no right to engage in violence.'
p4166
aS'Campuses can take steps to prevent violence \xe2\x80\x94 such as preventing weapons at demonstrations, having speakers be in areas where safety can best be assured, and moving counter-demonstrations to another area.'
p4167
aS'Also, if speech is a true threat \xe2\x80\x94 causing a person to reasonably fear imminent physical harm \xe2\x80\x94 it is not protected by the First Amendment.'
p4168
aS'What about the argument that some inflammatory speakers come to campus with the express aim of creating a hostile environment?'
p4169
aS'It is important to recognize that a public university has no choice but to allow speakers on campus even if their message is regarded as hateful or racist.'
p4170
aS'If the campus tried to exclude such a speaker, it would get sued and the speaker would win and likely would be made a martyr for the First Amendment in the process.'
p4171
aS'Nothing can be gained by exclusion.'
p4172
aS'But the campus must ensure safety for its students, staff and faculty.'
p4173
aS'This might include regulating where the controversial speaker is allowed to be present and, likely, it will include more of a police presence.'
p4174
aS'I am sympathetic to the concerns of students who are wary about more police coming to campus, but not having law enforcement present in the face of a danger to public safety risks even greater harms.'
p4175
aS'The central principle of the First Amendment \xe2\x80\x94 and of academic freedom \xe2\x80\x94 is that all ideas and views can be expressed.'
p4176
aS'Sometimes they are ideas and views that we might consider noble, that advance equality.'
p4177
aS'Sometimes they might be ideas that we abhor.'
p4178
aS'But there is no way to empower a government or campus administration to restrict speech without allowing for the possibility that tomorrow, it will be our speech that is restricted.'
