aS'I sit facing the young German neurologist, across a small table in a theater in Hamburg, Germany.'
p4180
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m here giving one-on-one talks called "The Unenhanced: What Has Happened to Those Deemed \xe2\x80\x98Unfit\xe2\x80\x99," about my research on Aktion T4, the Nazi "euthanasia" program to exterminate the disabled.'
p4181
aS'"I\xe2\x80\x99m afraid of what you\xe2\x80\x99re going to tell me," the neurologist says.'
p4182
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m not surprised.'
p4183
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99ve heard similar things before.'
p4184
aS'But this time is different \xe2\x80\x94 the young man sitting across from me is a doctor.'
p4185
aS'Aktion T4 could not have happened without the willing participation of German doctors.'
p4186
aS'I have a personal stake in making sure this history is remembered.'
p4187
aS'In 1960, I was born missing bones in both legs.'
p4188
aS'At the time, some thought I should not be allowed to live.'
p4189
aS'Thankfully, my parents were not among them.'
p4190
aS'I first discovered that people with disabilities were sterilized and killed by the Nazis when I was a teenager, watching the TV mini-series "Holocaust" in 1978.'
p4191
aS'But it would be years before I understood the connections between the killing of the disabled and the killing of Jews and other "undesirables," all of whom were, in one way or another, deemed "unfit".'
p4192
aS'The neurologist does not know much about what I\xe2\x80\x99m telling him.'
p4193
aS'While he does know that approximately 300,000 disabled people were killed in T4 and its aftermath, he doesn\xe2\x80\x99t know about the direct connection between T4 and the Holocaust.'
p4194
aS'He doesn\xe2\x80\x99t know that it was at Brandenburg, the first T4 site, where methods of mass killing were tested, that the first victims of Nazi mass killings were the disabled, and that its personnel went on to establish and run the extermination camps at Treblinka, Belzec and Sobibor.'
p4195
aS'Three years earlier, when I first arrived in Germany, I was consistently confronted with the treatment of those with disabilities under the Third Reich.'
p4196
aS'But I soon realized I had to go back even farther.'
p4197
aS'In the 1920s, the disabled were mistreated, sterilized, experimented on and killed in some German psychiatric institutions.'
p4198
aS'In 1920, the psychiatrist Alfred Hoche and the jurist Karl Binding published their treatise, "Permitting the Destruction of Unworthy Life," which became the blueprint for the exterminations of the disabled carried out by the Third Reich.'
p4199
aS'In Dr. Ewald Melzer\xe2\x80\x99s 1923 survey of the parents of the disabled children in his care, they were asked: "Would you agree definitely to a painless shortcut of your child\xe2\x80\x99s life, after it is determined by experts that it is incurably stupid"?'
p4200
aS'The results, which surprised Melzer, were published in 1925: 73 percent responded they were willing to have their children killed if they weren\xe2\x80\x99t told about it.'
p4201
aS'I am also Jewish.'
p4202
aS'At the Karl Bonhoeffer psychiatric hospital in the Berlin suburb of Wittenau, where the exhibition "A Double Stigma: The Fate of Jewish Psychiatric Patients" was held, I learned about, as the exhibition title suggests, how Jewish patients were doubly stigmatized by being separated from other patients, denied pastoral care, and were cared for not at the expense of the Reich but by Jewish organizations.'
p4203
aS'Jewish patients were singled out for early extermination; by December 1942, the destruction of the Jewish patient population at Wittenau was complete.'
p4204
aS'The young neurologist in Hamburg did not know this history.'
p4205
aS'It is only at the end of my talk with the neurologist that I notice he wears a hearing aid.'
p4206
aS'I want to ask if he knows about "100 Percent," the film produced by deaf Germans to show they could assimilate and be productive citizens who worked.'
p4207
aS'Did he know the hereditary deaf were singled out not only by the German authorities but also by those with acquired deafness who tried to save themselves?'
p4208
aS'Too often, even those of us with disabilities do not know our own history.'
p4209
aS'Not many people know about disability history in the United States.'
p4210
aS'They do not know that in the United States in 1927, Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes wrote that "three generations of imbeciles are enough" as part of his opinion in  , in which the Supreme Court ruled that compulsory sterilization of the "unfit" was constitutional.'
p4211
aS'This decision has never been expressly overturned.'
p4212
aS'Many Americans still do not know about the so-called "ugly laws," which in many states, beginning in the late 1860s, deemed it illegal for persons who were "unsightly or unseemly" to appear in public.'
p4213
aS'The last of these laws was not repealed until 1974.'
p4214
aS'Why is it important to know this history?'
p4215
aS'We often say what happened in Nazi Germany couldn\xe2\x80\x99t happen here.'
p4216
aS'But some of it, like the mistreatment and sterilization of the disabled, did happen here.'
p4217
aS'A reading of Hoche and Binding\xe2\x80\x99s "Permitting the Destruction of Unworthy Life" shows the similarity between what they said and what exponents of practical ethics, such as Peter Singer, say about the disabled today.'
p4218
aS'As recently as 2015, Singer, talking with the radio host Aaron Klein on his show, said, "I don\xe2\x80\x99t want my health insurance premiums to be higher so that infants who can experience zero quality of life can have expensive treatments".'
p4219
