aS'Nineteen sixty-seven may have been a brutal year in Vietnam \xe2\x80\x94 tens of thousands of Vietnamese and more than 11,000 Americans lost their lives in what increasingly looked like an endless war \xe2\x80\x94 but it was also, the United Nations decreed more hopefully, International Tourist Year.'
p4388
aS'The National Tourist Office of the Republic of Vietnam \xe2\x80\x94 yes, the American-backed South Vietnamese government maintained a tourism office during the war \xe2\x80\x94 issued a cheerful guidebook touting the conflict-ravaged country as an enticing destination.'
p4389
aS'With its sophisticated mountain resorts, fine white beaches, extensive hunting reserves and numerous other attractions, Vietnam was "rapidly becoming a \xe2\x80\x98must see\xe2\x80\x99 for thousands of foreign tourists," it maintained.'
p4390
aS'The claim was, of course, ludicrous.'
p4391
aS'Few tourists were making the trip to Vietnam by 1967, and those who did largely stuck to the capital.'
p4392
aS'"It\xe2\x80\x99s rather risky to go far from Saigon," the chief tourism official conceded that spring.'
p4393
aS'Yet the guidebook\xe2\x80\x99s publication, as bizarre as it may seem, reminds us of the extent to which tourism was about far more than travel.'
p4394
aS'For both the Republic of Vietnam and the United States, tourism contained an important political dimension.'
p4395
aS'There was a time, in the late 1950s and early \xe2\x80\x9960s, when Vietnam did attract thousands of pleasure-seeking visitors.'
p4396
aS'Holiday magazine profiled the country in 1957, and Travel magazine did a piece on Vietnam\xe2\x80\x99s "spectacular" sites two years later.'
p4397
aS'By the early 1960s, South Vietnam was enjoying tens of thousands of foreign visitors.'
p4398
aS'This was great news for both Washington and Saigon.'
p4399
aS'Not only would tourism promote the economic development and foreign-currency earnings that were so crucial to the South Vietnamese nation-building project, but, officials hoped, it also could generate positive views of the Republic of Vietnam and its contribution to Washington\xe2\x80\x99s Cold War mission.'
p4400
aS'This was true of both the in-country experiences of foreign tourists as well as the ideologically inflected literature they relied on to mediate their travel.'
p4401
aS'In the years following the 1954 Geneva Accords that temporarily divided Vietnam, the South Vietnamese authorities, using tourism as one of the tools in their soft-power arsenal, attempted to overcome the crisis of legitimacy that imperiled their fledgling state.'
p4402
aS'The republic\xe2\x80\x99s first president, Ngo Dinh Diem, was deeply unpopular, but both independent and government-produced tourism publications overlooked his political shortcomings in favor of a Cold War narrative that portrayed Diem as an effective nation-builder and one of the free world\xe2\x80\x99s greatest assets.'
p4403
aS'The Communist hordes in Vietnam, one American guidebook insisted, sought nothing less than "to enslave the entire population".'
p4404
aS'Fortunately, Diem \xe2\x80\x94 "a man of great vigor, vision and iron will" \xe2\x80\x94 was there to stop them, "Olson\xe2\x80\x99s Orient Guide" continued.'
p4405
aS'The tourism publications of the 1950s and \xe2\x80\x9960s consistently touted the American-backed government\xe2\x80\x99s alleged democratic credentials while delegitimizing the Vietnamese revolution as naked Communist aggression.'
p4406
aS'The southern republic was thus "Free Vietnam," according to Travel magazine.'
p4407
aS'The Democratic Republic of Vietnam, conversely, was the "Communist-dominated" or "Communist-held North".'
p4408
aS'None of this is particularly surprising in the context of Cold War ideology.'
p4409
aS'But it underscores a largely overlooked facet of the Vietnam War: Tourism and its attendant literature played a surprising yet significant role in wartime propaganda.'
p4410
aS'Not only did this literature frame the political unrest in the South for travelers hungry for information, but it was also disseminated outside Southeast Asia.'
p4411
aS'The "Guide to Viet-Nam" published by South Vietnam\xe2\x80\x99s Washington embassy, for example, was ostensibly created for tourists and, generously sprinkled with attractive photographs, included all sorts of information on the points of interest, festivals and Vietnamese culture certain to appeal to foreign visitors.'
p4412
