aS'More than 25 years after the collapse of the Soviet Union and the attempt to build a democracy in its place, Russia has once again become an authoritarian state.'
p4483
aS'The same inability to build democratic institutions plagued the leaders of the February Revolution of 1917, which led to the Bolsheviks gaining power later that year.'
p4484
aS'Russian authoritarianism has profound consequences not just for Russian citizens, but also for neighboring countries and the rest of the world.'
p4485
aS'Still burdened by a "besieged fortress" mentality, the Kremlin pursues a foreign policy aimed at achieving a "balance of forces" between Moscow and the West.'
p4486
aS'This outdated strategy creates a hysteria for military adventurism that threatens the entire planet.'
p4487
aS'Pro-Kremlin propagandists such as  , a well-known state TV host, have even suggested that "aggressive behavior" from the United States could prompt a nuclear response from Russia.'
p4488
aS'It is not surprising that the Kremlin is using   and other   to sow confusion in Western countries and undermine faith in democratic systems.'
p4489
aS'Russia\xe2\x80\x99s leaders are convinced that Western democracy is a threat to the authoritarian order in a country they have cowed into submission.'
