aS'Doing so raises the inevitable question: Do Russia\xe2\x80\x99s size, political culture and distrust of the Western world make it unsuitable for democracy?'
p4495
aS'Absolutely not.'
p4496
aS'I reject the fallacy that Russians are somehow incapable of building democratic institutions.'
p4497
aS'People said the same thing about the Germans.'
p4498
aS'How wrong they were.'
p4499
aS'Countries and their citizens do change, usually in response to their own failures.'
p4500
aS'The majority of Russians have never experienced democratic institutions and don\xe2\x80\x99t understand how they function.'
p4501
aS'But Russians who have moved to the West have adapted quickly and easily to democratic conditions.'
p4502
aS'They see how democracy protects individual rights and property, and allows societies to flourish.'
p4503
aS'Despite an insufficient understanding of democratic practices, Russia today has tens of thousands of civic organizations defending civil rights.'
p4504
aS'A 2012   from the Pew Research Center showed that a majority of Russians support honest elections and a fair judiciary.'
p4505
aS'The Russian people want their voices heard and their leaders held accountable: They want a different political system.'
p4506
aS'To avoid the mistakes of the past, we need to determine why Russia\xe2\x80\x99s two attempts to establish democracy in the 20th century led to new authoritarian regimes.'
p4507
aS'In both cases, having overthrown one tyrant \xe2\x80\x94 the czar in 1917 and communism in 1991 \xe2\x80\x94 Russia ended up handing over power to another.'
p4508
aS'How did this happen?'
p4509
aS'At the beginning of the 20th century, conservatives and liberals were unable to find a common language to discuss a democratic foundation for Russia.'
p4510
aS'As a result, the most reactionary faction within the governing elite came to dominate after the revolution of 1905, stymieing the development of democratic reforms.'
p4511
aS'After the overthrow of the czar in 1917, democracy once again lost out.'
p4512
aS'The Bolsheviks were in essence just as autocratic as the reactionaries who came before them, only with the opposite "ideological polarity".'
p4513
aS'They may have managed to swap the minus and plus signs in a few places, but the Bolsheviks were never able to break free of the magnetic field of Russian authoritarianism.'
p4514
aS'History repeated itself with the rise of Boris Yeltsin, even though he was Russia\xe2\x80\x99s first popularly elected leader.'
p4515
aS'In the early 1990s, the new president was granted extraordinary constitutional powers, with victorious liberals referring to Mr. Yeltsin as "czar".'
p4516
aS'When Vladimir V. Putin was first elected president in 2000, the former K.G.B. lieutenant colonel inherited a system perfectly designed to sustain Russia\xe2\x80\x99s authoritarian traditions.'
p4517
aS'A significant part of the Russian opposition today, unlike opposition movements in the West, sees democratic rights as emanating not from balanced political representation, but from the appointment of a "good czar".'
p4518
aS'This tendency to pursue a magnanimous ruler instead of democratic institutions forces ambitious political leaders to seek public support by relying on the force of their own personality rather than on a clear political program.'
p4519
aS'To win, politicians need to create an image of a "strong leader".'
p4520
aS'The challenge facing democratically minded Russians therefore isn\xe2\x80\x99t simply to remove Mr. Putin from power; it\xe2\x80\x99s to replace the authoritarian system he personifies.'
p4521
aS'The events of 1917 and 1991 teach us that the Kremlin cannot establish democracy by decree, and that democratic institutions will not spring up across the whole of Russia\xe2\x80\x99s territory at once.'
p4522
aS'The process must begin with the political transformation of European-oriented Russia and its cities: Moscow, St. Petersburg, Yekaterinburg and Novosibirsk, among others.'
