p4649
aS'My light-bulb moment among the parked buses was equally nonchalant.'
p4650
aS'I embraced the idea of physical action, without a care for possible consequences.'
p4651
aS'As thoughtlessly as I had supposed myself to be a pacifist, I gave myself permission for violence.'
p4652
aS'The demonstration the next day and the ones to come were increasingly combative.'
p4653
aS'I always hated confrontation, and still do.'
p4654
aS'I was always afraid in those situations.'
p4655
aS'So it may seem paradoxical that within weeks I joined the S.D.S. staff.'
p4656
aS'After that, my fear of fighting never stopped me from encouraging militance and organizing actions in which people could be hurt.'
p4657
aS'If I often avoided going toe-to-toe with the riot squad, I certainly smashed my share of windshields.'
p4658
aS'Strutting and provocation were camouflage for my fear, and for the taint of weakness most people then \xe2\x80\x94 including me \xe2\x80\x94 thought inextricable from being gay.'
p4659
aS'I immersed myself in radicalism for many reasons.'
p4660
aS'I felt betrayed by a democracy so deeply racist and unequal.'
p4661
aS'The stupefying carnage of the war repulsed me.'
p4662
aS'A na\xc3\xafve vision of communism seemed attractive.'
p4663
aS'Plus, passionate involvement replaced my untethered existence with community, a persona, a job and \xe2\x80\x94 however unrealistic \xe2\x80\x94 a life plan.'
p4664
aS'Alongside these motivations were those knottier psychological ones.'
p4665
aS'Then, as now, millions were moved to political action \xe2\x80\x94 and were often met with brutality by the state.'
p4666
aS'But few besides us chose to deliberately instigate and justify violence.'
