aS'Next month marks the seventh anniversary of the cholera outbreak that ravaged Haiti.'
p4673
aS'The disease, which can cause death within hours if left untreated, came less than a year after Haiti was rocked by an enormous earthquake that left hundreds of thousands dead and millions injured, displaced and destitute.'
p4674
aS'Haiti is prone to earthquakes and tropical storms \xe2\x80\x94 the island was spared the worst of Hurricane Irma last week \xe2\x80\x94 but the cholera outbreak was an anomaly; the disease had never before struck Haiti.'
p4675
aS'It was brought in, it is widely believed, by United Nations peacekeepers from Nepal.'
p4676
aS'One of the world\xe2\x80\x99s most infectious waterborne diseases, cholera spreads quickly and has proved extremely difficult to contain in Haiti.'
p4677
aS'Over 10,000 have died and nearly a million have been stricken to date.'
p4678
aS'But one organization has managed to nearly eradicate it in a large slum in Port-au-Prince that lacks clean water and sanitation.'
p4679
aS'One of the game changers that would surprise most people, including global health experts, was actually a building.'
p4680
aS'It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t just any building, but a very intelligently and beautifully designed one: the Cholera Treatment Center, operated by Les Centres Gheskio, an acronym that stands for the Haitian Group for the Study of Kaposi\xe2\x80\x99s Sarcoma and Opportunistic Infections.'
p4681
aS'Gheskio, founded in 1982 in the early days of the AIDS epidemic, provides primary care services free of charge to people suffering from tuberculosis, malnutrition, and other life threatening conditions in an area of the Haitian capital that is home to 60,000 Haitians.'
p4682
aS'(Gheskio is a less well-known sister organization of Partners in Health, which focuses on Haiti\xe2\x80\x99s rural population.'
p4683
aS') After the 2010 earthquake, Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s multi-acre campus was badly damaged.'
p4684
aS'So the organization erected emergency tents to serve as a makeshift cholera treatment clinic.'
p4685
aS'Once cholera reached Port-au-Prince, patients showed up on foot or were carried in wheelbarrows, around the clock.'
p4686
aS'Cholera manifests with extreme diarrhea and vomiting.'
p4687
aS'Virtually all liquid is excreted from the body, causing victims to die of dehydration within hours of full manifestation if untreated.'
p4688
aS'It is relatively easy to treat, but patients must be rehydrated immediately.'
p4689
aS'To prevent it from spreading, infected human waste must be managed carefully.'
p4690
aS'Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s founder, Jean W. Pape, an infectious disease specialist and native of Haiti, knew that eradicating cholera would take years.'
p4691
aS'So even as the organization struggled to keep up with the influx of patients during the first year of the epidemic, he embarked on a long-term solution: building a permanent treatment center.'
p4692
aS'Gheskio turned to MASS Design Group, a Boston-based nonprofit organization that specializes in architecture that promotes dignity and justice in resource-limited settings.'
p4693
aS'It has built hospitals, health-worker housing, schools and civic spaces around the world, including a tuberculosis hospital for Gheskio.'
p4694
aS'MASS Design began by studying the conditions inside the tents.'
p4695
aS'Tents provide relative shade and privacy but offer limited light and poor ventilation, trapping warm air and compounding the smell of bodily waste.'
p4696
aS'The materials become worn by rain, wind and sun, and must be replaced routinely.'
p4697
aS'Because of the nature of cholera, the makeshift beds, fashioned out of old fiberglass school chairs and costly army cots, also didn\xe2\x80\x99t last long.'
p4698
aS'Most problematic, Gheskio was relying on manual removal of human waste by an outside vendor.'
p4699
aS'This was both costly and risky: The organization couldn\xe2\x80\x99t ensure its disposal would not recontaminate the water table, risking the infection of others.'
p4700
aS'"We did some back-of-envelope calculations and found that over a 10-year span of time, which was then considered optimistic for how long it would take to get rid of cholera, the tents and manual waste disposal system they were then using would cost Gheskio in excess of $500,000," according to a co-founder of MASS Design, Alan Ricks.'
p4701
aS'Ricks estimated that MASS Design could build, for a comparable sum, a permanent structure that could be repurposed once the epidemic was fully contained.'
p4702
aS'So MASS Design and Gheskio joined forces to raise philanthropic funding from the Deutsche Bank Foundation, Barr Foundation and individual donors, and began work.'
p4703
aS'One important innovation, developed with Fall Creek Engineers, based in Santa Cruz, Calif., was to bring a water-purification technology to Haiti called anaerobic baffled reactors.'
p4704
aS'The reactors are a form of septic system that uses bacteria to treat sewage and contaminated water, turning it into clean water.'
p4705
aS'Reactors, buried under the cholera center, force water through five chambers, each successively increasing the level of purification.'
p4706
aS'Each week, Pape receives a detailed report on the water quality.'
p4707
aS'The system sanitizes and recycles 250,000 gallons of water annually, ensuring that the water is free enough of bacteria and other pathogens that it can be returned to the water table.'
p4708
aS'This output is supplemented by separate, large cisterns to capture rainwater for drinking.'
p4709
aS'Many other details incorporated into the center also promote health, as well as comfort, beauty and pride.'
p4710
aS'Above the reactors, for example, is a pavilion structure designed to maximize airflow.'
p4711
aS'Rather than spending money on tents, furniture or waste disposal services \xe2\x80\x94 money that leaves the local economy \xe2\x80\x94 the organizations enlisted local artisans, whose metalwork is world renowned, to create perforated metal sheets, painted a chorus of blues, to wrap the building exterior.'
p4712
aS'Waffle-like patterns of these sheets can be opened and closed to provide shade and privacy, or sealed completely during storms, as they were when Hurricane Irma neared Port-au-Prince last week.'
p4713
aS'The airflow is aided by large-diameter fans, like those in gyms and airports.'
p4714
aS'The cement floor is smooth, free of crevices where bacteria can congregate, and sealed with epoxy.'
p4715
aS'MASS Design interviewed many patients and staff members in an effort to design and create prototypes of beds that would be comfortable as well as easily sanitized and reused.'
p4716
aS'"What I love about MASS is their attention to detail," Pape said.'
p4717
aS'"They asked us everything that work and everything that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t work. But most importantly, they are problem solvers".'
p4718
aS'"The building looks absolutely extraordinary," said Roger Glass, a cholera expert who is director of the Fogarty International Center for Advancing Science for Global Health at the National Institutes of Health and has visited the Gheskio campus.'
p4719
aS'"For ventilation and coolness, it\xe2\x80\x99s tremendous".'
p4720
aS'Before encountering a hospital that MASS Design developed in Rwanda, Glass said, he had not seriously considered the relationship between health outcomes and building design.'
p4721
aS'"If you had called me seven years ago to talk about buildings and health, I would have blown you off," he said.'
p4722
aS'Today, Glass is eager to see more collaborations with human-centered design firms, like MASS Design, in the field of global health.'
p4723
aS'Comparing the treatment center to the tents, Pape is blunt: "It was like going from hell to paradise".'
p4724
aS'We realized, however, that architecture could not only help treat these diseases after the fact, but prevent the spread of disease in the first place by controlling recontamination.'
p4725
aS'Amie Shao, who helped lead MASS Design\xe2\x80\x99s work in Haiti, reflected: "When we started, our goal was simply to help Gheskio do their work better in treating their patients in a more dignified setting. In all of our work, we seek to proactively challenge many of the underlying risks and issues that global health faces".'
p4726
aS'To be sure, the cholera treatment center is not solely responsible for halting the spread in Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s target area.'
p4727
aS'Gheskio also developed a robust water chlorination program and maintains its own factory to produce chlorine.'
p4728
aS'The organization also supports and participates in broad efforts by the Ministry of Health to raise public awareness about symptoms and the risk of contamination throughout the country.'
p4729
aS'And Gheskio joined forces with Partners in Health to get cholera vaccines approved in Haiti.'
p4730
aS'Euvichol, a vaccine that can be administered orally and lasts up to 30 days without refrigeration, costs less than $2 per dose.'
p4731
aS'"We would need a budget of less than $50 million for universal coverage for all of Haiti," Pape estimates.'
p4732
aS'Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s Cholera Treatment Center was ultimately built for $750,000.'
p4733
aS'Pape now predicts that the organization will have recouped that cost in just three years.'
p4734
aS'Haiti needs a modern, countrywide water and sanitation system, but it\xe2\x80\x99s unclear where the money will come from.'
p4735
aS'In the meantime, Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s center has saved many lives.'
p4736
aS'By uniquely combining patient care with on-site water treatment, Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s center also holds lessons for other regions struggling to contain cholera or facing it in the future.'
p4737
aS'Globally, the World Health Organization estimates there are between 1.3 million and four million cases of cholera annually in 42 countries, with 21,000 to 143,000 cholera-related deaths each year.'
p4738
aS'This year, Somalia saw a major resurgence of the disease, with over 50,000 people infected.'
p4739
aS'About 1,000 died.'
p4740
aS'In the three years since Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s Cholera Treatment Center opened, the facility has remained in constant use because those outside the organization\xe2\x80\x99s target area continue to be exposed to contaminated water.'
p4741
aS'It has admitted over 10,000 patients to date, including over 7,000 who were hospitalized.'
p4742
aS'Eighty-three percent of those patients came from outside of Gheskio\xe2\x80\x99s catchment area.'
p4743
aS'While cholera reports in Haiti were on the rise in 2015 and 2016 at upward of 25,000 cases annually, the country saw a decrease in 2017, which Pape attributes to higher-than-normal rainfall in the region.'
p4744
aS'Of the 100 beds, no more than a third were occupied at any time this year, with as few as a handful of patients at times.'
p4745
aS'The risk for outbreaks remains high, however, and the disease\xe2\x80\x99s countrywide eradication is still years away.'
p4746
aS'"Haiti\xe2\x80\x99s recently elected government, and the president particular, is focused on universal oral cholera vaccine as well as home chlorination," Pape reports.'
p4747
aS'"If we get the vaccines and if we pursue home chlorination, I truly believe we can rid of cholera within four to five years".'
