aS'Is it permissible to take a selfie in front of the Kaaba during hajj?'
p4749
aS'With spotty internet, I was unable to Google the answer.'
p4750
aS'Forced to call an audible fatwa, I decided, "Yes, if indeed my intention is pure".'
p4751
aS'Fourteen hundred years ago, the Prophet Muhammad and his companions definitely didn\xe2\x80\x99t have to decide between Clarendon and Gingham filters to document the hajj pilgrimage that is recreated by Muslims each year.'
p4752
aS'But then again, they didn\xe2\x80\x99t have Instagram as I did when I went to Mecca to satisfy the pillar of my faith during the last days of August and the beginning of September.'
p4753
aS'They didn\xe2\x80\x99t have access to the air-conditioned tents that I used for shelter.'
p4754
aS'And when they gazed at the Kaaba \xe2\x80\x94 the austere black cube that represents God\xe2\x80\x99s house on earth \xe2\x80\x94 it certainly wasn\xe2\x80\x99t dwarfed, as it is now, by   that the Saudi government added to the landscape in 2012.'
p4755
aS'Awe-struck by the privilege of participating in this tradition while often agitated by the contradictions that surround it today, I made sense of the experience by sharing it \xe2\x80\x94 filtering the pilgrimage through the lens of my smartphone.'
p4756
aS'The most painful aspect of hajj wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the physical toll that came with navigating cramped space with my two million diverse fellow pilgrims, or the intense spiritual concentration.'
p4757
aS'It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the hiking-induced blisters and chafing.'
p4758
aS'It was witnessing the erasure and razing of my religion\xe2\x80\x99s culture, history and narrative by the House of Saud.'
p4759
aS'The Saudi royal family follows the revisionist and extreme ideology of Wahhabism, which preaches an interpretation of strict monotheism that is often at odds with centuries of theological scholarship.'
p4760
aS'They consider veneration and respect of most holy sites and visitations of graves as a form of idolatry.'
p4761
aS'That explains why, in their country, while the Prophet Muhammad\xe2\x80\x99s mosque and courtyard in Medina are spacious, cooled and immaculate, Jannat al-Baqi \xe2\x80\x94 a graveyard directly across from the green dome housing the remains of thousands of Islam\xe2\x80\x99s luminaries \xe2\x80\x94 looks like a set from "Mad Max: Fury Road".'
p4762
aS'There are no tombstones, just slabs of rock sticking out like middle fingers from the dirt.'
p4763
aS'If you linger too long to pay respects or offer a prayer, the mutawwa \xe2\x80\x94 religious police \xe2\x80\x94 rush you along.'
p4764
aS'When you ask them who\xe2\x80\x99s buried here, they answer, "Allah knows best," although they know the truth: the daughter of the prophet, his family members and some of his most loyal companions.'
p4765
aS'My friends and I spent hours at the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s tomb and the rawdah \xe2\x80\x94 a space between his original pulpit and grave considered by Muslims to be some of the hottest spiritual real estate on earth.'
p4766
aS'The moving experience was tempered by the awareness that most Muslims long to offer their "salaams" (prayers of peace) to the prophet, but cannot afford to visit his mosque.'
p4767
aS'Also, women are often unable to properly perform the "ziyarat" (religious visitation) there because they\xe2\x80\x99re allowed only limited access.'
p4768
aS'In Mecca, I hiked nearly an hour under the remorseless afternoon sun to visit the Cave of Hira, where the prophet is believed to have received his first revelation: "Recite"!'
p4769
aS'There are no golden signs, air-conditioning, wheelchair ramps or video presentations here.'
p4770
aS'The austere cave used to offer a clear line of sight to the Kaaba, but now the view is now obscured by that monstrous, $15 billion, Saudi-government-funded clock tower and the accompanying world\xe2\x80\x99s tallest hotel.'
p4771
aS'That tableau is a perfect symbol of the strained marriage between the house of God \xe2\x80\x94 the Kaaba, in Mecca \xe2\x80\x94 and the House of Saud, which controls everything related to the sacred mosques.'
p4772
aS'In adherence to the reactionary religious ideology it embraces, the government has allowed the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s house to fall into decrepitude.'
p4773
aS'It has flattened the home of his first wife, Khadija, and installed public toilets where it used to stand.'
p4774
aS'But it has no objection to the construction of extravagant hotels not far away.'
p4775
aS'These government\xe2\x80\x99s conflicting values were on display wherever I looked: While non-Muslims are forbidden from even entering Mecca, everyone is free to eat American Hardee\xe2\x80\x99s hamburgers or KFC fried chicken, or buy a Rolex watch across from the Kaaba.'
p4776
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s forbidden to excessively venerate the prophet and his companions, but there\xe2\x80\x99s no problem with the giant posters of King Abdulaziz, King Salman and his son, Crown Prince Muhammad bin Salman, that are all around town.'
p4777
aS'But whenever I found myself lamenting the ugliness and hypocrisy of these elements of my journey, the people I met reminded me why I was there, with displays of untarnished spirituality.'
p4778
aS'In the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s mosque, local people brought bread, dates and milk to feed fasting pilgrims.'
p4779
aS'Children begged me to eat from the plates they had prepared, hoping to gain some of the blessings.'
p4780
aS'In the desert plain of Arafat, east of Mecca, I walked with nearly two million pilgrims to the Mount of Mercy.'
p4781
aS'Men and women offered whatever they had: water, food, ice cream, a helping hand for a wheelchair-user.'
p4782
aS'They shared the shade under their umbrellas, and sometimes even the clothes off their back with fellow pilgrims.'
p4783
aS'We were united in a shared journey: seeking to find forgiveness, mercy and salvation.'
p4784
aS'It made sense to invite fellow Muslims and friends along for a view of this often-schizophrenic experience, unfiltered through Wahhabi propaganda.'
p4785
aS'While I initially worried it might distract me from my prayer, sharing the photos and Facebook Live videos made hajj a communal experience, in the most modern way possible.'
p4786
aS'In Mecca and Medina, often through my camera\xe2\x80\x99s lens, I looked up at the heavens and at the shiny buildings, but I also looked around me and engaged with a community of believers \xe2\x80\x94 some of them with me on ground, and some of them looking at screens on the other side of the world.'
p4787
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s where I found God \xe2\x80\x94 and beauty \xe2\x80\x94 in all its glorious contradictions.'
