aS'Last week, Americans woke up to news of yet another mass breach of their personal data.'
p4789
aS'The consumer credit reporting agency Equifax revealed that  , dates of birth, names and addresses may have been stolen from its files \xe2\x80\x94 just the kind of information that allows for identity theft and other cybercrimes.'
p4790
aS'I don\xe2\x80\x99t know about you, but I\xe2\x80\x99ve lost count of the number of times in recent years that I\xe2\x80\x99ve been informed by a corporation of such a breach.'
p4791
aS'"We regret to inform you \xe2\x80\xa6".'
p4792
aS'I don\xe2\x80\x99t doubt that companies regret these things, but I don\xe2\x80\x99t think they care that much either.'
p4793
aS'To them it means just a few days of bad press and at most a fine that amounts to a minuscule portion of their profits.'
p4794
aS'With penalties like that, why would companies bother to make things better?'
p4795
aS'There are technical factors that explain why cybersecurity is so weak, but the underlying reason is political, and it\xe2\x80\x99s pretty simple: Big corporations have poured large amounts of money into our political system, helping to create a regulatory environment in which consumers shoulder more and more of the risk, and companies less and less.'
p4796
aS'This is a general feature of our lopsided world, but software businesses (and the technology sides of other companies) have acquired perhaps the greatest degree of impunity.'
p4797
aS'Information technology arrived on the scene only recently, so it has faced fewer of the kinds of regulations that consumers and citizens, in more progressive eras, managed to impose on other industries.'
p4798
aS'Today, almost every piece of software comes with a disclaimer on its user license that basically says that the product may not work as intended and that its maker may stop supporting it at any time, and that\xe2\x80\x99s the user\xe2\x80\x99s problem.'
p4799
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a wonder companies don\xe2\x80\x99t insert "nyah nyah nyah nyah" into the tiny-print legalese.'
p4800
aS'Don\xe2\x80\x99t get me wrong: I\xe2\x80\x99m a former programmer; I\xe2\x80\x99m not unsympathetic to the needs of software developers.'
p4801
aS'Some number of unexpected errors \xe2\x80\x94 bugs \xe2\x80\x94 are unavoidable in computer programs.'
p4802
aS'It would be unreasonable to allow a consumer to sue a software company every time a program suffered a glitch.'
p4803
aS'But the situation was different when the industry was younger and wasn\xe2\x80\x99t rolling in billions of dollars, as it is now.'
p4804
aS'Most software failures and data breaches aren\xe2\x80\x99t inevitable; they are a result of neglect and underinvestment in product reliability and security.'
p4805
aS'No software system can be free from bugs (or intruders), and users must be mindful of the risks.'
p4806
aS'But the inherent lack of perfect automotive safety doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean we don\xe2\x80\x99t try to make cars safer.'
p4807
aS'Obviously, people should drive more carefully, but seatbelts, airbags and better car design reduce injury enormously, and that has been great for the industry as well as consumers.'
p4808
aS'The software industry should be no different.'
