aS'These days, many of us would rather not be living in the present, a time of persistent crisis, political uncertainty and fear.'
p4877
aS'Not that the future looks better, shadowed by technological advances that threaten widespread unemployment and by the perils of catastrophic climate change.'
p4878
aS'No wonder some are tempted by the comforts of a nostalgically imagined past.'
p4879
aS'Inspiring as it seems on first inspection, the self-help slogan "live in the present" slips rapidly out of focus.'
p4880
aS'What would living in the present mean?'
p4881
aS'To live each day as if it were your last, without a thought for the future, is simply bad advice, a recipe for recklessness.'
p4882
aS'The idea that one can make oneself invulnerable to what happens by detaching from everything but the present is an irresponsible delusion.'
p4883
aS'Despite this, there is an interpretation of living in the present, inspired by Aristotle, that can help us to confront the present crisis and the perpetual crises of struggle and failure in life.'
p4884
aS'There is an insight in the self-help slogan that philosophy can redeem.'
p4885
aS'The beginning of wisdom here is to think about what we are doing.'
p4886
aS'We engage in all sorts of activities: reading an article in the newspaper, reflecting on life, attending a protest, preparing a report, listening to music, driving home, making dinner, spending time with family or friends.'
p4887
aS'Though all these activities take time, there is a crucial difference in how they relate to the present moment.'
p4888
aS'Using terminology from linguistics, we can distinguish activities of two fundamental kinds.'
p4889
aS'Telic activities \xe2\x80\x94 from "telos," the Greek word for purpose \xe2\x80\x94 aim at terminal states, by which they are completed.'
p4890
aS'Think of reading this article or driving home from work.'
p4891
aS'Once you arrive at the goal, you are finished: The point of the activity has been achieved.'
p4892
aS'You can do it again, but only by way of repetition.'
p4893
aS'Not all activities are like this.'
p4894
aS'Some activities are atelic: They do not aim at terminal states.'
p4895
aS'However much you reflect on life or spend time with your family, you cannot complete these activities.'
p4896
aS'Though you will eventually stop doing them, they do not aim at a point at which there is no more of them to do.'
p4897
aS'Aristotle made the same distinction, contrasting two kinds of action or praxis: kinesis and energeia.'
p4898
aS'Kinetic actions are telic and therefore incomplete.'
p4899
aS'As Aristotle wrote in his "Metaphysics": "If you are learning, you have not at the same time learned".'
p4900
aS'When you care about telic activities, projects such as writing a report, getting married or making dinner, satisfaction is always in the future or the past.'
p4901
aS'It is yet to be achieved and then it is gone.'
p4902
aS'Telic activities are exhaustible; in fact, they aim at their own exhaustion.'
p4903
aS'They thus exhibit a peculiar self-subversion.'
p4904
aS'In valuing and so pursuing these activities, we aim to complete them, and so to expel them from our lives.'
p4905
aS'Atelic activities, by contrast, do not by nature come to an end and are not incomplete.'
p4906
aS'In defining such activities, we could emphasize their inexhaustibility, the fact that they do not aim at terminal states.'
p4907
aS'But we could also emphasize what Aristotle does: They are fully realized in the present.'
p4908
aS'"At the same time, one is seeing and has seen, is understanding and has understood, is thinking and has thought".'
p4909
aS'There is nothing you need to do in order to perform an atelic activity except what you are doing right now.'
p4910
aS'If what you care about is reflecting on your life or spending time with family or friends, and that is what you are doing, you are not on the way to achieving your end: You are already there.'
p4911
aS'What would it mean, then, to live in the present, and what do we gain by doing it?'
p4912
aS'To live in the present is to appreciate the value of atelic activities like going for a walk, listening to music, spending time with family or friends.'
p4913
aS'To engage in these activities is not to extinguish them from your life.'
p4914
aS'Their value is not mortgaged to the future or consigned to the past, but realized here and now.'
p4915
aS'It is to care about the process of what you are doing, not just projects you aim to complete.'
p4916
aS'The advice is easy to misread.'
p4917
aS'To live in the present is not to deny the value of telic activities, of making a difference in the world.'
p4918
aS'That would be a terrible mistake.'
p4919
aS'Nor can we avoid engaging in such activities.'
p4920
aS'But if projects are all we value, our lives become self-subversive, aimed at extinguishing the sources of meaning within them.'
p4921
aS'To live in the present is to refuse the excessive investment in projects, in achievements and results, that sees no inherent value in the process.'
p4922
aS'To live in the present is not to avoid hard work or strife.'
p4923
aS'Alongside the projects that occupy you in your profession, or in your political life, the telic activities that matter to you, is the atelic process of protesting injustice or doing your job.'
p4924
aS'To value the process is not to flee from work or political engagement.'
p4925
aS'That is why living in the present is not an abdication of ethical responsibility or a recipe for detachment.'
p4926
aS'To focus on the telic is to focus, all too often, on the distance and precariousness of our goals: to provide health care for all, to halt the resurgence of white supremacy, to limit global warming to 2 degrees.'
p4927
aS'Consequences matter, as do activities that aim at them.'
p4928
aS'The point of political protest is to change the world.'
p4929
aS'And yet the process matters, too.'
p4930
aS'The value of standing up for what is right, of going on strike or marching in the streets, is not exhausted by the value of its effects.'
p4931
aS'It is not wholly erased by failure.'
p4932
aS'We protest in part because we see no better way to make a difference, in part to make the present count for something, whatever the future holds.'
