aS'Dublin \xe2\x80\x94 Shortly after midnight on Nov. 2, 1950, when the Cold War was well underway, all the illuminated signs on Broadway and Times Square were dimmed in salute to the most prominent Western admirer of Stalin.'
p4934
aS'The Irish dramatist George Bernard Shaw had just died, and the tribute reflected the fame of plays such as "Pygmalion," "Man and Superman" and "Saint Joan".'
p4935
aS'But Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s plays were nothing if not political, and few of his American admirers could have been in doubt that his politics included support for Communism in general and for Stalin in particular.'
p4936
aS'That he was nonetheless honored in the United States is a reminder that the great divide of the Cold War was never as simple as it seemed.'
p4937
aS'Beneath Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s infatuation with Stalin, moreover, was a force that is still with us: a desire to see in Russia all the qualities that the Western democracies lack.'
p4938
aS'On the face of it, Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s idolization of Stalin is a great puzzle.'
p4939
aS'The man known around the world by his initials G.B.S. was not just a great playwright; he was arguably the single most influential public intellectual of the first half of the 20th century.'
p4940
aS'At Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s death, Jawaharlal Nehru, the first prime minister of independent India, said, "He was not only one of the greatest figures of his age, but one who influenced the thought of vast numbers of human beings during two generations".'
p4941
aS'That influence could be summed up in one bracing imperative: the duty to be a skeptic.'
p4942
aS'He challenged his readers and audiences to burst bubbles of conventional wisdom on almost every issue imaginable, from the rightful place of women to the pretensions of empires, from the glory of war to the treatment of animals, from homosexuality to children\xe2\x80\x99s rights, from religious doctrine to the treatment of the poor.'
p4943
aS'When Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s demolitions of received ideas provoked outrage and obloquy, he courageously defended his intellectual independence.'
p4944
aS'He abhorred cruelty and made mincemeat of propaganda.'
p4945
aS'And yet, he was devoted to one of the cruelest figures in the bloody annals of tyranny, and he was a willing dupe of the propaganda that projected the Soviet Union as a workers\xe2\x80\x99 paradise.'
p4946
aS'The great skeptic allowed all his skepticism to melt away when he looked at the picture of Stalin he kept by his mantelpiece.'
p4947
aS'His support was unwavering.'
p4948
aS'Neither the Great Purge nor the Ukrainian famine, nor even the pact between Stalin and Hitler, seem to have troubled his faith in the genius and historic rectitude of the Soviet dictator.'
p4949
aS'To understand this contradiction, we have to remember the power of wish fulfillment and the way Russia became for many Westerners not a place but an idea, not a mere reality but a fantasy.'
p4950
aS'In part, Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s inability to challenge the myth of Stalin as a great friend of humanity can be explained by flattery.'
p4951
aS'When he visited the Soviet Union in 1931 (accompanied by the American-born Conservative member of Parliament Nancy Astor), he was greeted in Moscow by a military guard of honor, banners emblazoned with his portrait and crowds crying, "Hail, Shaw"!'
p4952
aS'An enormous banquet was held to celebrate Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s 75th birthday.'
p4953
aS'And Stalin himself granted Shaw a two-hour-long private audience at which his guest found the dictator in "charmingly good-humored" mood.'
p4954
aS'In part, too, Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s insistence on seeing the Soviet Union as the harbinger of the great socialist utopia can be explained by the disappointments of democracy.'
p4955
aS'He had fought for decades to establish universal adult suffrage, especially for women and the working class.'
p4956
aS'Like many radical intellectuals, he was dismayed to find that many of these new voters preferred king-and-country conservatism to the socialism they were supposed to support.'
p4957
aS'Especially as the Great Depression took hold, parliaments and political parties seemed utterly ineffectual.'
p4958
aS'Stalin\xe2\x80\x99s apparent ability to move mountains and transform society with triumphant five-year plans offered an antidote to his impatience with the frustrations of democracy.'
p4959
aS'But underlying all of this, there was an even stronger impulse: the fantasy of Russia itself.'
p4960
aS'Long before the Bolshevik Revolution gave the dream a very particular political content, Shaw was primed to expect a global spiritual resurrection that would begin in Russia.'
p4961
aS'This hope was not as fanciful as it may now seem: In the late 19th century, when Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s political and artistic consciousness was being formed, Russian music, drama and literature were at the leading edge of modern Western culture.'
p4962
aS'As he later wrote to Maxim Gorky, "I myself am as strongly susceptible as anyone to the fascination of the Russian character as expressed by its art and personally by its artists".'
p4963
aS'The creation of G.B.S. owes almost as much to Russia as it does to Ireland or England.'
p4964
aS'He learned much of his political style from anti-czarist exiles in London, especially the anarchist Peter Kropotkin and the nihilist Sergius Stepniak.'
p4965
aS'Arguably Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s greatest play, "Heartbreak House," is subtitled "A Fantasia in the Russian Manner on English Themes" and was greatly influenced by Chekhov.'
p4966
aS'Above all, Shaw was caught up in the great wave of enthusiasm for Tolstoy that broke over the English-speaking world in the mid-1880s when "War and Peace," "Anna Karenina" and most of his other works appeared in translation.'
p4967
aS'Shaw called Tolstoy "the master".'
p4968
aS'His own insistence on the didactic purpose of art and his forging of a sage-like persona are pure Tolstoy.'
p4969
aS'This was not just a matter of artistic influence.'
p4970
aS'Russia became, for Shaw, a kind of alternate universe, an imaginative field in which grandiosities that he would otherwise have delighted in puncturing were given free rein.'
p4971
aS'He would have made devastating fun of anyone writing about "the Irish soul," or "the English soul," but he was happy to write without irony of "the soul of the Russian people".'
p4972
aS'When Kropotkin\xe2\x80\x99s daughter told him that "the Russians would give the world back its lost soul," Shaw did not scoff.'
p4973
aS'Rather, as he wrote to Gorky, "I quite understand that; it is not at all ridiculous to me".'
p4974
aS'It was, of course, Marx who wrote that everything in history happens twice, "the first time as tragedy, the second time as farce".'
p4975
aS'There is something tragic in Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s journey from Tolstoy to Stalin, from seeing Russia as the place to give the world back its lost soul to his eventual embrace of the Soviet project as "the only hope of the world".'
p4976
aS'But perhaps this same impulse is now with us \xe2\x80\x94 in full-on farcical mode.'
p4977
aS'Vladimir Putin is no Stalin, and the white nationalists around Donald Trump are certainly no Shaws.'
p4978
aS'But some of the same impulse is still at work: the tendency to fantasize about Russia as the vigorous counterweight to a supposedly decadent West.'
p4979
aS'There is the same impatience with the messiness and inefficiency of democracy, and it leads to the same crush on the strongman leader who can cut through the irrelevant natterings of parliaments and parties.'
p4980
aS'Shaw\xe2\x80\x99s infatuation with Russia became a full-on love affair with a Soviet autocrat, whereas the Trump bromance with President Putin appears unconsummated.'
p4981
aS'But they share a fatal attraction that both preceded and survived the Soviet Union: the allure of a faraway place where the great leader is obeyed because he embodies a people\xe2\x80\x99s soul.'
