aS'When schools reopened in New York last week, students were greeted by teachers who had spent the summer preparing for their return.'
p5019
aS'Unfortunately, many of those teachers had had to devote some of their time not to lesson plans, but to a state teacher-certification process that emphasizes bureaucratic procedures more than real-world qualifications.'
p5020
aS'So as a teacher who recently had to jump through the New York certification hoops, I was pleased to learn that the  , which authorizes charter operators,   to certify their teachers themselves.'
p5021
aS'The comment period for the proposal closes on Monday, and the institute could approve it as early as next month.'
p5022
aS'Here\xe2\x80\x99s my story.'
p5023
aS'In February 2015, I was delighted to receive an offer from Democracy Prep Public Schools, one of New York City\xe2\x80\x99s thriving charter school networks, to join an innovative new educational program for students with disabilities called Pathways.'
p5024
aS'There was just one problem: I was not certified to teach in New York State.'
p5025
aS'That I did not possess the requisite certification did not mean that I lacked the requisite qualifications.'
p5026
aS'When I received my offer from Democracy Prep, I had already spent six years of teaching and coaching aspiring teachers in Boston and Chicago.'
p5027
aS'As a graduate of Boston Teacher Residency, an alternative teacher-preparation program based in Boston Public Schools, I am certified to teach in Massachusetts.'
p5028
aS'I also have a master\xe2\x80\x99s in education from the University of Massachusetts, Boston.'
p5029
aS'Nevertheless, because of New York\xe2\x80\x99s approach to teacher credentialing, it took 18 months, three exams, one teaching portfolio, countless hours and about $1,000 for me to get my initial certificate through reciprocity.'
p5030
aS'And I\xe2\x80\x99m one of the lucky ones.'
p5031
aS'Because I was already certified in another state, I did not have to take additional graduate courses.'
p5032
aS'Democracy Prep even reimbursed all of my application and exam fees.'
p5033
aS'Still, I found myself having to divert precious time from my work in the classroom to study for exams and compile a teaching portfolio just to demonstrate that I was a competent teacher, which I had already proved six years before in Boston.'
p5034
aS'It can be a daunting task, one that can deter great prospective teachers, or prompt already great teachers to leave the field rather than deal with the paperwork involved in getting certified in a new state or renewing their certification.'
p5035
aS'Even as charter schools become more numerous and more popular, they are having problems finding enough instructors, and so they rely on young, new teachers, often from nontraditional backgrounds, who have yet to receive certification.'
p5036
aS'Under the Charter School Institute proposal, schools would be able to design their own training programs and certify teachers.'
p5037
aS'These new teachers would have to get a minimum of 100 hours of "field experience" under the supervision of another teacher and 30 hours of "content core" instruction, among other requirements.'
p5038
aS'Many charter schools, including Democracy Prep, are already in a position to undertake such programs.'
p5039
aS'By mid-August of this year, I was headlong into summer professional development.'
p5040
aS'Teachers at Democracy Prep engage in approximately 240 hours of training throughout the school year.'
p5041
aS'I also receive constant feedback and support to improve my teaching practice and help students grow.'
p5042
aS'I am observed weekly by school leaders, instructional coaches and other network staff members.'
p5043
aS'At the end of each trimester, I sit down with my principal to review my performance and progress and to set goals for the remainder of the year.'
p5044
aS'While some unions and professors at teachers colleges have criticized the certification proposal, my experiences in schools around this country have taught me that no one actually cares where or how you learned to teach.'
p5045
aS'No one has ever walked into my classroom and asked to see my degree or questioned my qualifications; all that has mattered is the classroom environment that I\xe2\x80\x99ve helped to create, the relationships that I\xe2\x80\x99ve built with students and families, and the growth of my students.'
p5046
aS'Limiting the ability of schools to attract great teachers makes little sense.'
p5047
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s not important to our students whether their teachers went through a traditional graduate school of education, Teach for America or a charter school training program; all that matters is that they get the very best teachers that we can give them.'
p5048
aS'Our communities, schools and students deserve the highest-quality teachers, not merely the ones with a paper certificate.'
