aS'We had a reliable store of batteries and flashlights, battery-powered hurricane lamps, a battery-operated radio, gallons of water, cans and boxes of food that would keep.'
p5276
aS'And bottles of vodka, for Susie, and bourbon for me.'
p5277
aS'Lots of it.'
p5278
aS'The best way to get through a hurricane thrashing against your house is to drink your way through it, wake the next day with a headache to see the wind gone.'
p5279
aS'At first, we bought our supplies three and four days before a hurricane hit.'
p5280
aS'Then we refined our strategy to a day or two.'
p5281
aS'I filled the bathtub with water we could use in the toilet when we lost power.'
p5282
aS'I cleaned and oiled our 9-millimeter pistols, then loaded them.'
p5283
aS'In 2004, three hurricanes hit us in the space of six weeks, Charley, Frances and Jean.'
p5284
aS'They each lingered off shore, one after the other, blowing at us for weeks as we sat in darkness.'
p5285
aS'We were in our mid-60s when Wilma hit in 2005.'
p5286
aS'Wilma was a beast, its force like a herd of dinosaurs thundering past our shuttered windows.'
p5287
aS'It was the first time we were ever scared for our lives in a hurricane.'
p5288
aS'Susie held our oldest dog, Kiri, who was shivering from fear.'
p5289
aS'Wilma lingered from the early morning until noon when, suddenly, it was gone.'
p5290
aS'The sun came out.'
p5291
aS'We ventured outside like cave dwellers into sunlight, blinking our eyes.'
p5292
aS'All our neighbors were outside, too, sawing fallen limbs, heaping trash and broken objects on the swale.'
p5293
aS'Paradise was never the same for us again.'
p5294
aS'Our beloved Kiri died three weeks after Wilma.'
p5295
aS'We put our house up for sale in 2008, and in March 2009, we moved into our current house, a big, old Victorian on a hill here in Abbeville, S.C.'
p5296
aS'Our real estate broker told us we would never have to worry about hurricanes again.'
p5297
aS'"Abbeville doesn\xe2\x80\x99t get weather," she said.'
p5298
aS'"The only weather we ever got was a tornado in \xe2\x80\x9973".'
p5299
aS'One night a few days after we arrived, Susie and the dogs were sleeping while I watched a movie on TV.'
p5300
aS'A narrow banner of letters rolled across the top of the screen: "Tornado warning for Abbeville County".'
p5301
aS'Three minutes later all hell broke loose.'
p5302
aS'A fierce wind rattled our old windows, and I heard the cracking of tree limbs and then their thunderous crashes to earth.'
p5303
aS'In minutes the tornado was gone and everything was still again.'
p5304
aS'My wife and the dogs slept through it.'
p5305
aS'That was the only weather we\xe2\x80\x99ve ever had in Abbeville for the eight years we\xe2\x80\x99ve lived here.'
p5306
aS'Until today, of course, with Irma bearing up on us, from Florida.'
p5307
aS'We\xe2\x80\x99re two old people now, with a sense of mortality we lacked when we arrived in Florida three decades ago, oblivious to the effect hurricanes could have on people\xe2\x80\x99s lives.'
