aS'Who should have the right to define rape: survivors who have experienced sexual violence or those who are accused of perpetrating it?'
p5358
aS'That is the core question raised by Education Secretary   this month to replace Obama-era guidelines on how universities handle sexual misconduct complaints.'
p5359
aS'In a strongly worded speech, Ms. DeVos made clear that she believed the previous administration had used "intimidation and coercion" to force colleges to adopt disciplinary procedures that deprived accused students of their rights.'
p5360
aS'To come to these conclusions, Ms. DeVos and her staff appear to have given special consideration to the concerns of men accused of sexual assault.'
p5361
aS'After one hearing about campus rape policies, Candice Jackson, the top civil rights official in the Department of Education, said, "The accusations \xe2\x80\x94 90 percent of them \xe2\x80\x94 fall into the category of \xe2\x80\x98we were both drunk, we broke up, and six months later I found myself under a Title IX investigation because she just decided that our last sleeping together was not quite right. \xe2\x80\x99 " Ms. Jackson has since called these remarks "flippant," but they reveal a gross misunderstanding of sexual assault.'
p5362
aS'Ms. Jackson essentially intimated that she believes either that alcohol-facilitated sexual assault and intimate partner violence are not real or that, at the very least, they are not harmful enough to merit disciplinary action.'
p5363
aS'No wonder Ms. DeVos thinks many sexual assault complaints on campus are baseless.'
p5364
aS'According to Ms. Jackson\xe2\x80\x99s incorrect logic, almost any college man facing disciplinary proceedings would be falsely accused.'
p5365
aS'And yet there is plenty of evidence that false accusations of rape are  .'
p5366
aS'Obama-era policies did not malign men.'
p5367
aS'What they did was make it easier for victims to come forward.'
p5368
aS'A 2011 "Dear Colleague" letter from the Obama administration advised universities to change the standard for how to determine guilt from proof that was "beyond a reasonable doubt" to a "preponderance of evidence" \xe2\x80\x94 or, more colloquially, more likely than not.'
p5369
aS'Before 2011, most colleges had already voluntarily made these changes.'
p5370
aS'There are several good reasons for that.'
p5371
aS'The "beyond a reasonable doubt" evidentiary standard usually applies to criminal charges \xe2\x80\x94 and college tribunals are not criminal courts.'
p5372
aS'Colleges can\xe2\x80\x99t determine whether or not an assailant will go to prison.'
p5373
aS'But they are required to keep students safe and promote equal access to education under Title IX, the civil rights law that secures nondiscrimination on the basis of sex or gender in federally funded educational programs.'
p5374
aS'Sexual assault complaints are essentially civil rights disputes, and a preponderance of evidence standard is what is   in civil rights cases.'
p5375
aS'The preponderance of evidence standard is also survivor-centered.'
p5376
aS'When judging whether someone has been raped, it\xe2\x80\x99s almost impossible to assert that a sex act constituted violence "beyond a reasonable doubt".'
p5377
aS'Many survivors struggle to produce what campus hearing boards would consider evidence, especially when it comes to acquaintance- or date-based   in which alcohol made it impossible for someone to physically resist.'
p5378
aS'Sexual assaults also commonly occur away from third-party witnesses, limiting the potential for corroborating testimonies.'
p5379
aS'Finally, trauma can make survivors seem   to campus administrators who are untrained.'
p5380
aS'The difficulty in providing hard evidence has long presented a devastating barrier for victims\xe2\x80\x99 access to recourse and remedies, and it discouraged survivors from coming forward.'
p5381
aS'The Obama administration responded to survivors\xe2\x80\x99 needs by lowering the burden of proof necessary to gain access to institutional support.'
p5382
aS'That   are reporting their sexual assaults to their universities shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t lead us to the conclusion that more college students are being raped or that more students are lying \xe2\x80\x94 just that more feel comfortable coming forward.'
p5383
