aS'From the moment we humans first imagined having mechanical servants at our beck and call, we\xe2\x80\x99ve assumed they would be constructed in our own image.'
p5394
aS'Outfitted with arms and legs, heads and torsos, they would perform everyday tasks that we\xe2\x80\x99d otherwise have to do ourselves.'
p5395
aS'Like the indefatigable maid Rosie on "The Jetsons," the officious droid C-3PO in "Star Wars" and the tortured "host" Dolores Abernathy in "Westworld," the robotic helpmates of popular culture have been humanoid in form and function.'
p5396
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s time to rethink our assumptions.'
p5397
aS'A robot invasion of our homes is underway, but the machines \xe2\x80\x94 so-called smart speakers like Amazon Echo, Google Home and the forthcoming Apple HomePod \xe2\x80\x94 look nothing like what we expected.'
p5398
aS'Small, squat and stationary, they resemble vases or cat food tins more than they do people.'
p5399
aS'Echo and its ilk do, however, share a crucial trait with their imaginary forebears: They illuminate the times.'
p5400
aS'Whatever their shape, robots tell us something important about our technologies and ourselves.'
p5401
aS'Although smart speakers have been around just three years, they already have a hold on us.'
p5402
aS'The devices, powered by "chatbots" like Siri and Alexa, are in the midst of a sales boom.'
p5403
aS'Some 35 million Americans now use the diminutive, talking computers \xe2\x80\x94 more than twice the number of just a year ago, according to estimates by eMarketer \xe2\x80\x94 and analysts predict that three-quarters of United States households will own at least one of the gadgets by 2020.'
p5404
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s not hard to understand the attraction.'
p5405
aS'Smart speakers are oracles of the countertop.'
p5406
aS'They may not be able to speak for the gods, but they can deliver reports on news, traffic and weather.'
p5407
aS'And they have other talents that their Delphic ancestor couldn\xe2\x80\x99t even dream of: They can serve as D.J.'
p5408
aS'They can diagnose ailments and soothe anxieties.'
p5409
aS'They can read bedtime stories.'
p5410
aS'They can even bark like a watchdog to scare off burglars.'
p5411
aS'And they promise to be the major-domos of home automation, adjusting lights, controlling appliances and issuing orders to specialized robots like the Roomba vacuum cleaner.'
p5412
aS'Still, if you were looking forward to having a Rosie scurrying around your abode, feather duster in hand, an Echo feels like a letdown.'
p5413
aS'It just sits there.'
p5414
aS'There are good reasons that the domestic robot has taken such an uninspiring form.'
p5415
aS'Some are technical.'
p5416
aS'Visualizing a nimble, sure-footed android is easy, but building one is hard.'
p5417
aS'As the Carnegie Mellon professor Illah Nourbakhsh explains in his book "Robot Futures," it requires advances not only in artificial intelligence but also in the complex hardware systems required for movement, perception and dexterity.'
p5418
aS'The human nervous system is a marvel of physical control, able to sense and respond fluidly to an ever-changing environment.'
p5419
aS'Achieving such agility with silicon and steel lies well beyond the reach of today\xe2\x80\x99s engineers.'
p5420
aS'Even the most advanced of our current automatons still get flustered by mundane tasks like loading a dishwasher or dusting knickknacks.'
p5421
aS'Meanwhile, thanks to gains in networking, language processing and miniaturization, it has become simple to manufacture small, cheap computers that can understand basic questions and commands, gather and synthesize information from online databanks and control other electronics.'
p5422
aS'The technology industry has enormous incentives to promote such gadgets.'
p5423
aS'Now that many of the biggest tech companies operate like media businesses, trafficking in information, they\xe2\x80\x99re in a race to create new products to charm and track consumers.'
p5424
aS'Smart speakers provide a powerful complement to smartphones in this regard.'
p5425
aS'Equipped with sensitive microphones, they serve as in-home listening devices \xe2\x80\x94 benign-seeming bugs \xe2\x80\x94 that greatly extend the companies\xe2\x80\x99 ability to monitor people\xe2\x80\x99s habits.'
p5426
aS'Whenever you chat with a smart speaker, you\xe2\x80\x99re disclosing valuable information about your routines and proclivities.'
p5427
aS'Beyond the technical challenges, there\xe2\x80\x99s a daunting psychological barrier to constructing and selling anthropomorphic machines.'
p5428
aS'No one has figured out how to bridge what computer scientists term the "uncanny valley" \xe2\x80\x94 the wide gap we sense between ourselves and imitations of ourselves.'
p5429
aS'Because we\xe2\x80\x99re such social beings, our minds are exquisitely sensitive to the expressions, gestures and manners of others.'
p5430
aS'Any whiff of artificiality triggers revulsion.'
p5431
aS'Humanoid robots seem creepy to us, and the more closely they\xe2\x80\x99re designed to mimic us, the creepier they are.'
p5432
aS'That puts roboticists in a bind: The more perfect their creations, the less likely we\xe2\x80\x99ll want them in our homes.'
p5433
aS'Lacking human characteristics, smart speakers avoid the uncanny valley altogether.'
p5434
aS'Although they may not look like the robots we envisioned, smart speakers do have antecedents in our cultural fantasy life.'
p5435
aS'The robot they most recall at the moment is HAL, the chattering eyeball in Stanley Kubrick\xe2\x80\x99s sci-fi classic "2001: A Space Odyssey".'
p5436
aS'But their current form \xe2\x80\x94 that of a stand-alone gadget \xe2\x80\x94 is not likely to be their ultimate form.'
p5437
aS'They seem fated to shed their physical housing and turn into a sort of ambient digital companion.'
p5438
aS'Alexa will come to resemble Samantha, the "artificially intelligent operating system" that beguiles the Joaquin Phoenix character in the movie "Her".'
p5439
aS'Through a network of speakers, microphones and sensors scattered around our homes, we\xe2\x80\x99ll be able to converse with our solicitous A.I. assistants wherever and whenever we like.'
p5440
aS'Mark Zuckerberg, the Facebook C.E.O., spent much of last year programming a prototype of such a virtual agent.'
p5441
aS'In a video released in December, he gave a demo of the system.'
p5442
aS'Walking around his Silicon Valley home, he conducted a running dialogue with his omnipresent chatbot, calling on it to supply him with a clean T-shirt and toast bread for his breakfast, play movies and music, and entertain his infant daughter.'
p5443
aS'Hooked up to cameras with facial-recognition software, the digitized Jeeves also acted as a sentry for the Zuckerberg compound, screening visitors and unlocking the gate.'
p5444
aS'Whether real or fictional, robots hold a mirror up to society.'
p5445
aS'If Rosie and her kin embodied a 20th-century yearning for domestic order and familial bliss, smart speakers symbolize our own, more self-absorbed time.'
p5446
aS'It seems apt that as we come to live more of our lives virtually, through social networks and other simulations, our robots should take the form of disembodied avatars dedicated to keeping us comfortable in our media cocoons.'
p5447
aS'Even as they spy on us, the devices offer sanctuary from the unruliness of reality, with all its frictions and strains.'
p5448
aS'They place us in a virtual world meticulously arranged to suit our bents and biases, a world that understands us and shapes itself to our desires.'
p5449
aS'Amazon\xe2\x80\x99s decision to draw on classical mythology in naming its smart speaker was a masterstroke.'
p5450
aS'Every Narcissus deserves an Echo.'
