p5500
aS'The governor correctly sees it as a way to raise gobs of cash for the city\xe2\x80\x99s ailing mass-transit network.'
p5501
aS'But let\xe2\x80\x99s not forget that the true goal of this pricing mechanism is embodied in its name: decongesting streets for the benefit of drivers and pedestrians \xe2\x80\x94 and their lungs.'
p5502
aS'The main idea in play for now is a plan put forth by  .'
p5503
aS'It would discourage cars and trucks from entering Manhattan south of 60th Street during peak business hours, in part by imposing tolls on four East River bridges that are now free.'
p5504
aS'(Lost in the mists of time is the fact that the bridges once had tolls.'
p5505
aS'Mayor William Gaynor got rid of them in 1911.'
p5506
aS') As compensation, tolls on outer bridges like the Verrazano-Narrows and the Throgs Neck would be lowered.'
p5507
aS'Electronic sensors would make it possible for the fees to be adjusted according to the time of day.'
p5508
aS'There\xe2\x80\x99s no reason they could not be sharply lowered, even eliminated, late at night or on weekends.'
p5509
aS'Anyone observing traffic on the toll-free bridges can see vast numbers of cars that carry only the person behind the wheel.'
p5510
aS'Many people drive into Midtown and Lower Manhattan because they bear no cost other than the price of gas.'
p5511
aS'Naturally, this proposal has resisters, notably politicians representing Brooklyn, Queens and the eastern suburbs, whose constituents take to cars more than Manhattan or Bronx residents do.'
p5512
aS'No one pretends that getting Albany\xe2\x80\x99s required approval is a cinch.'
p5513
aS'Bill de Blasio, the city\xe2\x80\x99s Brooklyn-philic mayor, has his own objections.'
p5514
aS'He describes congestion pricing as a "regressive tax" on lower-income drivers, unfairly making them pay the same toll as the wealthy.'
p5515
aS'The mayor prefers what he describes as a "millionaires tax" to raise money for the subways.'
p5516
aS'The reality, however, is that New York car owners tend to be better off.'
p5517
aS'For starters, more than half the households in the city are carless, according to a census analysis by the  .'
p5518
aS'The median household income of those with wheels is more than double that of those without \xe2\x80\x94 $85,000 compared with $40,630.'
p5519
aS'Writing in   on Sunday, Veronica Vanterpool, executive director of the tri-state campaign, said, "A regressive transportation policy is what we have now: a system that favors free travel by drivers and ignores the environmental, social and economic costs of car-clogged city streets".'
p5520
aS'We agree.'
p5521
aS'Besides, there\xe2\x80\x99s nothing regressive about plowing toll revenue into improvements for mass transit, which is how most low- and middle-income New Yorkers get around.'
p5522
aS'Some might even call it progressive.'
