aS'When the South Korean military killed hundreds of pro-democracy protesters and laid siege to the southwestern city of Gwangju in  , few people outside the city knew what was happening.'
p5524
aS'Martial law had been declared, the already censored press was completely gagged, and all communications with Gwangju were cut off.'
p5525
aS'The end of the 10-day siege marked the beginning of a seven-year period of military repression and terror under Gen.  , who outdid his predecessor, Gen. Park Chung-hee, in brutality and corruption.'
p5526
aS'One generation later, millions of Korean citizens   in dozens of cities across the country for 20 continuous weekends of "candlelight rallies," from the autumn of 2016 to the spring of 2017.'
p5527
aS'They called for the   of then-President  , General Park\xe2\x80\x99s daughter, for her part in a scandal involving corruption, bribery and abuse of power.'
p5528
aS'This time around, the entire world knew what was going on in South Korea.'
p5529
aS'The country\xe2\x80\x99s advanced information technology infrastructure made the difference.'
p5530
aS'Smartphones turned front-line protesters into videographers.'
p5531
aS'Millions commented on the political situation on Kakao Talk (a Korean messaging service), Facebook and other social media channels.'
p5532
aS'Technology alone is not enough to establish true democracy.'
p5533
aS'Not all technologically advanced nations have vibrant grass-roots political engagement, and in many countries, devices and software are being abused \xe2\x80\x94 used for surveillance or to manipulate information, while anti-democratic extremists spread their views on the same platforms.'
p5534
aS'Advanced technology can enable democracy by giving citizens more time and energy for political engagement and by making corrupt political practices like vote-buying more difficult.'
p5535
aS'However, what\xe2\x80\x99s most important is constant civic engagement \xe2\x80\x94 without that, democracy withers away.'
p5536
aS'The popular "Asian values" thesis suggests that Asians are culturally disinclined to democracy because they favor the good of the community over individual rights.'
p5537
aS'That is untrue: South Koreans have fought for democracy throughout modern history.'
p5538
aS'In 1945, when the Japanese left after 35 years of colonial rule, no South Korean called for the restoration of the monarchy.'
p5539
aS'In 1960, a mass protest against misrule and electoral fraud ousted the republic\xe2\x80\x99s first president, Rhee Syngman.'
p5540
aS'Throughout General Park\xe2\x80\x99s 18 years of iron-fisted rule, students and workers agitated and risked their lives for democracy.'
p5541
aS'In 1987, 19 days of violent street demonstrations led by students, workers and even young managers ended his successor\xe2\x80\x99s military rule.'
p5542
aS'With the "candlelight revolution," Koreans have elevated their democracy to another level.'
p5543
aS'But the challenge they face is formidable.'
p5544
aS'The protesters were calling for more than just the ousting of an errant president and her cronies: They want to create a cleaner and fairer society.'
p5545
aS'The most immediate challenge Koreans face is that of ridding the political system of corruption.'
p5546
aS'Illicit dealings among politicians, high-ranking officials and chaebols \xe2\x80\x94 family-controlled business empires \xe2\x80\x94 are common.'
p5547
aS'This August,  , the de facto head of Samsung, one of the most prominent chaebols, was   to five years in prison for bribing Park and her notorious confidante  .'
p5548
aS'Some believe that corruption can be eliminated by further deregulation, with the idea that this would reduce the number of opportunities for collusion with public officials, and by strengthening minority shareholder rights, on the theory that shareholders will expose corrupt dealings by those who run the chaebols.'
p5549
aS'However, a much more fundamental shift in the distribution of power is required if there is to be a reduction in corruption.'
p5550
aS'Decision-making abilities need to be transferred from the political and business elites to citizens, civic organizations, trade unions and other "countervailing powers," to borrow an expression from the economist John Kenneth Galbraith.'
p5551
aS'Then there is the issue of fairness.'
p5552
aS'Increasing deregulation has reduced protections for small factories and shops, which used to supply jobs that kept income inequality relatively low.'
p5553
aS'The spread of American-style salary norms in the past decade or so has led to a tremendous increase in wage inequality \xe2\x80\x94 South Korea has one of the fastest-growing levels among the countries in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.'
p5554
aS'But what angers South Koreans most is the marked drop in social mobility and the sense of hopelessness that haunts young people from less-privileged backgrounds \xe2\x80\x94 that is, most young people.'
p5555
aS'This lack of social mobility is sometimes the result of blatantly corrupt practices.'
p5556
aS'Of all the corruption scandals the former president faces, particularly upsetting for many was the accusation that Ms. Choi   Ewha Womans University in Seoul, one of the nation\xe2\x80\x99s leading universities, to accept Ms. Choi\xe2\x80\x99s daughter at the expense of candidates who were better qualified.'
p5557
aS'The barriers to university applicants are usually subtle.'
p5558
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s the extras that make a candidate for admission stand out, such as extracurricular activities or expensive private tutoring for university entrance exams.'
p5559
aS'At the beginning of their careers, expectations that candidates have completed internships may stand in the way.'
p5560
aS'Poor parents cannot even dream of helping their children with such things.'
p5561
aS'Many young Koreans believe, rightly, that equality of opportunity is impossible in the face of ostensibly fair rules that favor the daughters and sons of the rich and the powerful.'
p5562
aS'Removing these barriers to social mobility will be even more difficult than reducing corruption.'
p5563
aS'Big changes in the education system are needed, and especially in the university application process.'
p5564
aS'This will also require the expansion of the welfare state so that children from less-privileged backgrounds can have a chance at moving up the social ladder through early learning programs, publicly funded enrichment schemes, and the increased parental attention and family stability that extra income can provide.'
p5565
aS'Koreans have shown the world that an engaged citizenry, armed with the latest technologies, can work a democratic miracle.'
p5566
aS'That miracle will fade away and people will become disillusioned with democracy if the government does not deliver a cleaner and fairer society soon.'
