aS'Nelson Mandela\xe2\x80\x99s dream of a free, prosperous and nonracial South Africa has turned into a nightmare.'
p5603
aS'The nation\xe2\x80\x99s constitution, often hailed as one of the most progressive in the world, is under siege by the very man who took an oath to protect it.'
p5604
aS'President Jacob Zuma, in office since 2009, is subverting democracy.'
p5605
aS'Mr. Zuma, who recently survived his   vote in Parliament, has enabled political patronage and exploited South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s institutions for his own benefit and that of the ruling elites in his party, the African National Congress.'
p5606
aS'He has grossly mismanaged the country\xe2\x80\x99s resources and engaged in acts of far-reaching cronyism.'
p5607
aS'Saddest of all, Mr. Zuma has fomented a deep sense of disillusionment among many of the nation\xe2\x80\x99s black youth.'
p5608
aS'Yes, Mr. Mandela\xe2\x80\x99s   brought prosperity to post-apartheid South Africa, but the distribution of economic benefits was skewed in favor of the white establishment and black elite.'
p5609
aS'Even today, little of this prosperity has reached the black youth, and many blame Mr. Mandela for delivering what they see as a superficial notion of freedom rather than an enduring democracy with opportunities for all.'
p5610
aS'Mr. Zuma\xe2\x80\x99s rampant corruption has bolstered this disillusionment.'
p5611
aS'For instance, shortly after he became president, Mr. Zuma spent 246 million rand (about $23 million at the time) in state funds to upgrade his private country residence.'
p5612
aS'In 2014, South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s Office of the Public Protector   to reimburse some of those costs, yet he resisted for more than a year, at times pointing to the A.N.C.\xe2\x80\x99s majority in Parliament to validate his defiance.'
p5613
aS'Eventually, South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s High Court ordered him to comply with the public protector\xe2\x80\x99s order, but the impunity has continued.'
p5614
aS'More recently, according to media reports, leaked emails and the findings of the public protector, Mr. Zuma outsourced some aspects of governance to a family of expats from India that has established businesses with his son, Duduzane Zuma, and is profiting from government contracts while exerting political influence wherever it can.'
p5615
aS'The family \xe2\x80\x94 brothers Ajay, Atul and Rajesh Gupta, and their nephew Varun Gupta \xe2\x80\x94 even influence ministerial appointments.'
p5616
aS'In 2016 Mcebisi Jonas, then a deputy minister of finance, reported that he had been summoned to the Gupta family mansion and offered 600 million rand (about $43 million) if he accepted the position of finance minister.'
p5617
aS'According to Mr. Jonas, the Guptas told him that the president was going to remove the current minister of finance, who had allegedly blocked some lucrative contracts and become an obstacle to the Guptas\xe2\x80\x99 access to the treasury.'
p5618
aS'Mr. Jonas had enough integrity to refuse the offer.'
p5619
aS'But Mr. Zuma nevertheless replaced the finance minister with a Gupta-approved official, who, after a public outcry, lasted only a weekend.'
p5620
aS'Meanwhile, as the Guptas and Duduzane Zuma amass untold wealth in South Africa, and as allegations of their profiteering dominate the headlines, President Zuma\xe2\x80\x99s ruling A.N.C. has  .'
p5621
aS'And yet the president continues to enjoy powerful support from sectors of the electorate.'
p5622
aS'Mr. Zuma remains popular in rural areas, particularly among the Zulu people, South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s largest ethnic group.'
p5623
aS'They embrace him as a charismatic, conservative man with four wives who speaks their language at political rallies and makes inside ethnic jokes.'
p5624
aS'Another source of power for Mr. Zuma is South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s electoral system, which is not constituency-based, but proportion-based.'
p5625
aS'Voters do not directly elect their representatives; they vote for political parties.'
p5626
aS'Party bosses then compile lists of candidates and dictate how members of the legislatures should vote.'
p5627
aS'All of them toe the line, since none want to jeopardize their livelihoods.'
p5628
aS'Then there is the Umkhonto We Sizwe Military Veterans Association, a ragtag army of ardent Zuma supporters in ill-fitting camouflage uniforms who purport to be veterans of the A.N.C.\xe2\x80\x99s guerrilla war against the apartheid regime (though members in their early 20s are too young to have fought in a war that ended more than 25 years ago).'
p5629
aS'Mr. Zuma recently tried to put this group on a war footing, instructing them to close ranks behind him and defend his beleaguered "revolution" against those who protest against him.'
p5630
aS'Not all is lost, however.'
p5631
aS'Despite South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s perverted state, the independent judiciary has been a saving grace, and a robust media regularly exposes government corruption.'
p5632
aS'Additionally, the Congress of South African Trade Unions, the South African Communist Party and factions within the A.N.C. have banded together and demanded that Mr. Zuma step down.'
p5633
aS'So have a number of civil society organizations (some led by A.N.C. members), which have organized mass demonstrations in major cities.'
p5634
aS'Additionally, opposition parties, previously weak and ineffectual, have a much louder voice since being joined in Parliament by the Economic Freedom Fighters, a more radical party that has gained a large following among unemployed black youths.'
p5635
aS'Despite all this, Mr. Zuma is unlikely to relinquish power.'
p5636
aS'Were he to step down, civil groups and the opposition would undoubtedly see to it that the   of corruption and money laundering leveled against Mr. Zuma in 2009 be reactivated.'
p5637
aS'The charges were dropped shortly before his election as president, but last year South Africa\xe2\x80\x99s High Court ordered that they be reinstated.'
p5638
aS'However, the prosecution authority is stalling.'
p5639
aS'Additional charges relating to the Guptas are likely to be added.'
p5640
aS'Mr. Zuma is also trying to position his ex-wife, Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma, to take over as president in 2019 when his second term ends, most likely in the hope that she will grant him a pardon.'
p5641
aS'The opposition parties are demanding that Mr. Zuma step down now.'
p5642
aS'But it is unlikely that any party will secure an outright majority in 2019; instead, the opposition parties will gang up against the A.N.C. and form coalitions in some provinces.'
p5643
aS'They have already done so in three major metropolitan areas where the A.N.C. failed to get a majority in the last local election.'
p5644
aS'For too long Mr. Zuma has fostered a culture of arrogance and impunity among the ruling elite, and for too long the decay has continued unabated.'
p5645
aS'South Africa must change course, before a troubled democracy is reduced to a thugocracy.'
