aS'Today, while the city\xe2\x80\x99s white population has largely recovered since 2005, approximately 100,000 fewer African-Americans live here than did before Katrina.'
p5772
aS'This stark racial disparity cannot be explained by the flood alone, which discriminated less than many people realize.'
p5773
aS'Rather, political power and policy decisions account for the dramatic change.'
p5774
aS'Some of those decisions were bold and public.'
p5775
aS'As protesters were tear-gassed and stun-gunned outside of City Hall, for example, the legislators voted to demolish 4,500 public housing apartments, nearly all home to African-Americans.'
p5776
aS'"Our residents deserve better, much better than what we offered before," said the City Council president, Arnie Fielkow, which may have been true.'
p5777
aS'But a housing official\xe2\x80\x99s claim that "Katrina has come in and washed it away" was certainly not.'
p5778
aS'The brick buildings still stood and could easily have been reopened.'
p5779
aS'Five years after the storm, fewer than half of the families who once called those places home had returned to New Orleans.'
p5780
aS'Other decisions were more opaque, though their effects were just as profound.'
p5781
aS'Take a detail buried within what stands as America\xe2\x80\x99s largest housing recovery program, which Louisiana called Road Home.'
p5782
aS'The government paid out grants to flooded homeowners according to the so-called fair market value of their houses, rather than the replacement value.'
p5783
aS'Because of historically racist practices of underdevelopment and discrimination, this seemingly race-neutral policy meant that for comparable damage, homeowners in white neighborhoods were paid more than homeowners in African-American neighborhoods.'
p5784
aS'African-American homeowners sued and forced changes in the program, but the resolution did not come until six years after the storm.'
p5785
aS'For many families, it was too late to matter.'
p5786
aS'In fact, few people got enough from Road Home to replace the homes they lost, but the racial disparity in resources available to rebuild was vast.'
p5787
aS'In the predominantly white, middle-class neighborhood of Lakeview, the average gap between the cost of repairs and the amount homeowners received in private insurance and Road Home funds was $44,000.'
p5788
aS'But in the mostly African-American, middle-class neighborhood of New Orleans East, the average gap was $69,000.'
p5789
aS'In this way, Katrina cost African-Americans more than it cost whites.'
