aS'NAIROBI, Kenya \xe2\x80\x94 Peace means so much more after you\xe2\x80\x99ve experienced violence.'
p6352
aS'Less than a month ago, my country, Kenya,  .'
p6353
aS'On the morning the polls opened, my heart raced \xe2\x80\x94 I come from and work in the Kibera slums, and it is often said, "When Kibera burns, so does Kenya".'
p6354
aS'But not this time.'
p6355
aS'During my childhood, campaign season was the only time we ate rice.'
p6356
aS'My mother would come home with a small portion of rice, a handout from a politician.'
p6357
aS'"Where did the rice come from"?'
p6358
aS'I would ask her, and she would say from someone campaigning, the name unimportant, her vote equally unassured.'
p6359
aS'As she served the rice to my siblings and our neighbors, she would repeat an old refrain: "Empty containers make a lot of noise".'
p6360
aS'My mother understood who the real winners and losers are in Kenyan politics.'
p6361
aS'Her allegiance was never to the politicians but to the people, from many tribes, with whom we lived.'
p6362
aS'In Kibera, neighbors are often the only safety nets.'
p6363
aS'They offer a cup of maize meal on hungry nights.'
p6364
aS'They watch over children as they walk to school.'
p6365
aS'Without my neighbors \xe2\x80\x94 Luos, Kikuyus, Nubians \xe2\x80\x94 I wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be where I am today.'
p6366
aS'And I am not alone.'
p6367
aS'Yet barely 10 years ago, we forgot this simple truth: Our communities are more fundamental to our survival than the oft-broken promises of politicians.'
p6368
aS'The violence surrounding our 2007 elections left more than 1,000 dead and hundreds of thousands displaced.'
p6369
aS'Politicians driven by self-interest turned tribes against one another \xe2\x80\x94 neighbor against neighbor.'
p6370
aS'On the night of the election, Kibera, normally filled with the sounds of life, was filled with the noise of gunfire.'
p6371
aS'I cowered under my bed, the walls of my shack made from discarded milk cartons the only barrier between the bullets outside and me.'
p6372
aS'Neighbors from different tribes who had lived together for years turned against one another in an instant.'
p6373
aS'One night, I planned to stay with friends in another part of Kibera.'
p6374
aS'By chance, I didn\xe2\x80\x99t make it to their house.'
p6375
aS'All four of my friends were killed that night, murdered in the cold blood of tribal hatred.'
p6376
aS'The next day, I fled for my safety.'
p6377
aS'As I left Kenya, I passed checkpoints where vigilantes asked at random to see ID cards, to establish ethnic identity.'
p6378
aS'I saw a man being beheaded for being from the "wrong" tribe.'
p6379
aS'I resolved that never again would we be misled to believe that there are more than two tribes in Kenya: the rich and the poor.'
p6380
aS'And though I ended up attending college in the United States, I returned to Kenya, to Kibera, to help my neighbors so that they will never again turn on one another.'
p6381
aS'Today I am building a movement for community-led change to transform urban slums through services like health care and education.'
p6382
aS'We\xe2\x80\x99ve made progress since 2007, but the names of those we lost are still fresh in our minds.'
p6383
aS'I asked a friend whom I had known since childhood what might happen after this year\xe2\x80\x99s elections.'
p6384
aS'He told me, "It will be peaceful, unless we lose".'
p6385
aS'I asked, "What then"?'
p6386
aS'He replied simply, "We are ready for war".'
p6387
aS'This desperation comes with a life in extreme poverty.'
p6388
aS'This desperation is the barrier to lasting peace.'
p6389
aS'In Kenya, there are millions of angry young people.'
p6390
aS'Elections give them a cause.'
p6391
aS'Politicians exploit this vulnerability.'
p6392
aS'I realized that if a call to violence could provide people an opportunity to contribute, so could a call to peace.'
p6393
aS'So months ago I met with a childhood friend, Milar, one of Kibera\xe2\x80\x99s most influential residents.'
p6394
aS'Over beers, I asked him if he might consider becoming a peace ambassador, bridging divides in the run-up to the election.'
p6395
aS'He said yes, and over many weeks we met with hundreds of leaders across Kibera to preach an allegiance to our community instead of to the will of the political class.'
p6396
aS'On the night the results of the election were announced, policemen in Kibera opened fire on angry opposition protesters.'
p6397
aS'Milar stepped in between the protesters and the police \xe2\x80\x94 his boldness shocked both sides.'
p6398
aS'Milar told the police commander that if the officers would retreat, he would in turn persuade the protesters to go home.'
p6399
aS'After a tense moment, the police agreed, and both sides pulled back.'
p6400
aS'A few days later, Milar saw a young woman wearing a T-shirt from the Jubilee party, a coalition led by President Uhuru Kenyatta, being beaten by a group of young men in Kibera, an opposition stronghold.'
p6401
aS'Milar, though himself an opponent of Jubilee, jumped into the fray and saved her life.'
p6402
aS'Despite the provocations of the police and the calls for violence, peace has held on in Kibera.'
p6403
aS'Last month my friend Leymah Gbowee, a Nobel Peace Prize laureate from Liberia, and Abigail Disney, an American filmmaker, joined me at several town hall meetings that I had organized before the Supreme Court was set to rule on the validity of the election.'
p6404
aS'Although Mr. Kenyatta\xe2\x80\x99s party declared victory, a petition from the opposition leader Raila Odinga claimed that there were voting irregularities and that the election should be annulled.'
p6405
aS'There was a real chance of violence however the court ruled.'
p6406
aS'Leymah asked, "If you burn down your community, where will your child go to the hospital"?'
p6407
aS'The audience answered, "Nowhere".'
p6408
aS'"Where will the children of your politicians go"?'
p6409
aS'They replied, "London, South Africa, India".'
p6410
aS'Afterward, Milar came to me, his face streaked with tears.'
p6411
aS'"We have to stop fighting the rich man\xe2\x80\x99s wars," he said.'
p6412
aS'In that room, surrounded by women and men, many of whom have fought on the streets before, a realization dawned: We must fight poverty, not one another.'
p6413
aS'On Sept. 1, the Supreme Court ruled in favor of the opposition\xe2\x80\x99s petition and annulled the election.'
p6414
aS'And the peace held.'
p6415
aS'It will be only through the experience of hope and community-led progress that this peace might last.'
p6416
aS'Together, we can build something that our politicians promise but cannot deliver: lasting hope.'
p6417
aS'But we cannot wait; we must follow my mother\xe2\x80\x99s example and share our rice.'
