aS'As Gen. H. R. McMaster, the national security adviser, wrote in his book "Dereliction of Duty," the early stages of the Vietnam War caught America\xe2\x80\x99s military leaders flat-footed.'
p6419
aS'Having gone through World War II and Korea, they were all ready for a conventional war.'
p6420
aS'But insurgencies and unconventional warfare were something else.'
p6421
aS'As a result, they were inordinately acquiescent to the wishful thinking of their civilian overseers \xe2\x80\x94 and no one thought more wishfully about the war than Walt Whitman Rostow.'
p6422
aS'A Yale Ph.D. and a Rhodes scholar, Rostow left his academic perch at M.I.T. to join the State Department under John F. Kennedy; he was later Lyndon Johnson\xe2\x80\x99s national security adviser during the center-cut of American involvement in Vietnam, from April 1966 to January 1969.'
p6423
aS'More than anyone else, he epitomized the overweening confidence of the civilian strategists of the era \xe2\x80\x94 he was the best and the brightest of "the best and the brightest".'
p6424
aS'He could lay distant claim to operational warfighting competence, having selected bombing targets as a major in the Office of Strategic Services during World War II.'
p6425
aS'But like many other prominent civilian strategists of the day, he was by training and disposition an economist and a technocrat.'
p6426
aS'In his 1960 book "The Stages of Economic Growth: A Non-Communist Manifesto," Rostow posited that robust growth was a nation\xe2\x80\x99s best insurance against the political emergence of Communism, and cast growth as a multistage process that depended crucially on a "takeoff" period propelled by rapid expansion in key segments of an economy.'
p6427
aS'Though criticized as tendentiously Western-centric, the book attracted Kennedy\xe2\x80\x99s attention.'
p6428
aS'In a matter of months, Rostow moved from holding forth in the academy to planning America\xe2\x80\x99s strategy in Vietnam, tightly guided by his ideas about economic development.'
p6429
aS'Most leading civilian strategists, who were so inventive and authoritative on nuclear strategy, steered a safe middle course between withdrawal and escalation in Vietnam, and did not enunciate big strategic concepts to guide the prosecution of the war.'
p6430
aS'Rostow was different.'
p6431
aS'He believed that the Vietcong were impeding South Vietnam\xe2\x80\x99s advancement to the takeoff stage, and that the United States therefore needed to expend all necessary military and diplomatic means to stop the Vietcong\xe2\x80\x99s guerrilla infiltration.'
p6432
aS'This was a neatly packaged but narrow vision that both opened the door to expansive military action but also reduced it to an adjunct of politics and economics.'
p6433
aS'Along those lines, Rostow reflexively argued for a "flexible response" when it came to military escalation, from ratcheting up the role of military "advisers" \xe2\x80\x94 that is, embedded Special Forces \xe2\x80\x94 in the early 1960s, to bombing North Vietnam starting in 1965, to steadily increasing the United States\xe2\x80\x99 expeditionary combat presence in the mid- and late 1960s.'
p6434
aS'Directly defeating the enemy was never the goal; military action was just a way to apply pressure, to maximize psychological intimidation \xe2\x80\x94 what came to be known as the "Rostow thesis".'
p6435
aS'But crucially, Rostow didn\xe2\x80\x99t actually know much about fighting a war.'
p6436
aS'Any soldier could have told him that increased bombing or troop levels were not the same as, say, increasing food aid.'
p6437
aS'Nor could one rely on data in the same way when it came to war.'
p6438
aS'Rostow was one of the most avid followers of the weekly body counts, equating the number of enemy reported killed with military progress, as if he were reading the latest reports on grain production.'
p6439
aS'In November 1967, an increasingly wary Robert McNamara, the secretary of defense, raised the idea of reassessing the war effort, shifting greater combat responsibility to the South Vietnamese \xe2\x80\x94 the policy that would become known as "Vietnamization" under President Richard Nixon \xe2\x80\x94 and a bombing halt.'
p6440
aS'Rostow agreed to the first two measures, but opposed the third, and President Johnson sided with him.'
p6441
aS'Despite McNamara\xe2\x80\x99s crisis of confidence \xe2\x80\x94 he departed the Pentagon in February 1968 \xe2\x80\x94 Rostow continued to comb through intelligence reports looking for reassuring factoids.'
p6442
aS'During the Tet offensive he denied even the possibility that the surprise attacks had provided a psychological shot in the arm to the Vietcong, concentrating instead on the huge casualties American and South Vietnamese forces had inflicted on them.'
p6443
aS'"This is a great victory for our side," he told a colleague while they sat in the White House Situation Room.'
p6444
aS'The ensuing 24-day battle for Hue, an agonizing engagement that American forces would also tactically win, drove home the strength of the enemy\xe2\x80\x99s determination and staying power.'
p6445
aS'But Rostow never saw the battle that way.'
p6446
aS'To the end, Rostow remained not just a supporter of the president, but a crutch.'
p6447
aS'As David Halberstam wrote of Rostow in "The Best and the Brightest": The upshot was that Rostow\xe2\x80\x99s status as designated administration hawk in chief induced in him a preoccupation with bureaucratic politics and buoying morale that impaired his strategic objectivity as American frustrations in Vietnam mounted.'
p6448
aS'He, more than any of Johnson\xe2\x80\x99s other advisers, was consumed with showing the press and the American public "light at the end of the tunnel".'
p6449
aS'The historian David Milne has called Rostow "America\xe2\x80\x99s Rasputin".'
p6450
aS'He was not alone as an early advocate for flexible response and a deepening commitment in Vietnam.'
p6451
aS'But long after McNamara and others turned against the war, even as evidence mounted against the Rostow thesis, he remained steadfast.'
p6452
aS'And while in the ensuing decades most of the advisers, including McNamara, admitted that they were wrong, Rostow,  , pointedly refused to apologize for the war or second-guess himself.'
p6453
aS'He remained a Cold Warrior until the end.'
p6454
aS'In 1986 he superficially attributed the fall of Saigon to Congressional budget cuts.'
p6455
aS'And he continued to insist that the war was worthwhile.'
p6456
aS'Joining a wave of historical revisionists, he argued that the war had bought time for other Southeast Asian nations to consolidate Western-leaning governments and subdue Communist influences \xe2\x80\x94 in other words, that the domino theory was right.'
p6457
aS'Like many of Kennedy\xe2\x80\x99s brain trust, Rostow was initially praised for his pragmatic, technocratic liberalism \xe2\x80\x94 but in his determination to impose his sterile ideas on the complicated realities of Southeast Asia, he proved to be as ideologically committed as the Communists he so adamantly opposed.'
