aS'OAKLAND, Calif.'
p6459
aS'\xe2\x80\x94 This was the summer that the forests turned red.'
p6460
aS'From the fir and hemlock stands of Puget Sound to the oak and pine groves of California, the light in the woods has gone all kinds of wrong.'
p6461
aS'The greens have been replaced by oranges, the normal hues vaporized in the smoke that has choked so much of the West in this season of wildfire.'
p6462
aS'The West, of course, is no stranger to fire.'
p6463
aS'Natives and newcomers alike grow accustomed to our annual apocalypse of flame.'
p6464
aS'While this fire season is no doubt bad \xe2\x80\x94 more than 80 big burns now burning from Montana to Southern California, while the August conflagrations that swept British Columbia were the province\xe2\x80\x99s   \xe2\x80\x94 we\xe2\x80\x99re still unlikely to surpass the record fires of 2015, when more than 10 million acres burned.'
p6465
aS'What has made this fire season so terrifying isn\xe2\x80\x99t the size or intensity of the fires, awful as they were, but the enormous clouds of smoke that have come with them.'
p6466
aS'In many places, for days on end the sky has been enveloped in haze, the sun reduced to a hot, distant penny.'
p6467
aS'The smoke screens that have hit Seattle, San Francisco, Denver, Portland, Ore., and most of Montana are a product of the same enormous high-pressure system that incited a historic heat wave earlier in the summer.'
p6468
aS'The heat contributes to the fires, then the smoke gets trapped.'
p6469
aS'The West Coast\xe2\x80\x99s natural air-conditioning of Pacific Ocean wind hasn\xe2\x80\x99t been able to blow the smoke away.'
p6470
aS'And now there\xe2\x80\x99s ash coating Portland.'
p6471
aS'The smoke makes the very air we breathe toxic.'
p6472
aS'At one point last month, the air quality in the Seattle region was likened to that of Beijing at its worst, a threat to the old and the young, and those with respiratory problems.'
p6473
aS'Also terrifying is how the smoke has twisted the light.'
p6474
aS'With the ordinary palette of the world turned upside down, the familiar has become disorienting.'
p6475
aS'Usual comforts seem unsettling and uncanny.'
p6476
aS'Normally I go to the woods for retreat, for contemplation and invigoration.'
p6477
aS'But the forest has become alien with all of the smoke.'
p6478
aS'In the Pacific Northwest during the zenith of the British Columbia fires, it was as if a cinematographer had put a red lens on the camera.'
p6479
aS'The evergreens went matte, while the rust-colored trunks of madrone trees were poppingly visible from hundreds of yards away.'
p6480
aS'The cedar trunks were nearly pulsating with color.'
p6481
aS'In Northern California during the Labor Day heat wave, the woods were changed, too.'
p6482
aS'The patches of sun on a trail at midmorning had the pastel cast of evening.'
p6483
aS'The natural detritus of the California woods \xe2\x80\x94 old bay and willow leaves, spent bracken and downed logs \xe2\x80\x94 looked ominous in the orange light.'
p6484
aS'Friends in Montana report that the haze and the smoke remind them of the recent solar eclipse.'
p6485
aS'Shadows go fuzzy, similar to how it was when the sun was at 25 percent of normal.'
p6486
aS'Everyone seems to agree that the sunsets have been epic, but that the moons are spooky: heavy peach globes, weirdly portentous.'
p6487
aS'One summer night in Washington, I saw a waxing crescent moon stained a red darker than blood.'
p6488
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s hard not to think that these alterations are just a glimpse of things to come.'
p6489
aS'Perhaps this is the new normal of climate change.'
p6490
aS'With all the dust and smoke in the air, the world will begin to look different.'
p6491
aS'The sky will be milkier, less often intensely blue.'
p6492
aS'Every sunset will be hot pink and hallucinogenic.'
p6493
aS'The green trees of the forest will be cast under a rose lamp.'
p6494
aS'The transformation of familiar sites is bound to take a psychic toll.'
p6495
aS'In 1893, the Norwegian artist Edvard Munch completed his most famous painting, "The Scream," with its haunting vibe of existential dread.'
p6496
aS'The nightmare image, with its swirls of deep reds and blues, was inspired by Munch\xe2\x80\x99s experience, a decade earlier, of witnessing an unearthly sunset, created in part by airborne particulates emitted by the eruption of the Indonesian volcano Krakatau, on the other side of the planet.'
p6497
aS'All of the ash from the volcano scattered the blue-violet wavelengths of light, just as the smoke blanketing the West is doing now.'
p6498
aS'At the sight of ruptured sky, Munch said he felt "a great, unending scream piercing through nature".'
p6499
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s a pretty good description of what these smoke storms have felt like.'
p6500
aS'Maybe the strange, never-before-seen landscapes of our hot, hazy century will make for some incredible art.'
p6501
aS'But like Munch, I also worry that it will bring us something much darker, more forlorn.'
p6502
aS'Not for nothing did he title one study for his painting "Despair".'
