aS'CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va.'
p6504
aS'\xe2\x80\x94 On Wednesday, Facebook revealed that hundreds of Russia-based accounts had run anti-Hillary Clinton ads precisely aimed at Facebook users whose demographic profiles implied a vulnerability to political propaganda.'
p6505
aS'It will take time to prove whether the account owners had any relationship with the Russian government, but one thing is clear: Facebook has contributed to, and profited from, the erosion of democratic norms in the United States and elsewhere.'
p6506
aS'The audacity of a hostile foreign power trying to influence American voters rightly troubles us.'
p6507
aS'But it should trouble us more that Facebook makes such manipulation so easy, and renders political ads exempt from the basic accountability and transparency that healthy democracy demands.'
p6508
aS'The majority of the Facebook ads did not directly mention a presidential candidate, according to Alex Stamos, head of security at Facebook, but "appeared to focus on amplifying divisive social and political messages across the ideological spectrum \xe2\x80\x94 touching on topics from L.G.B.T. matters to race issues to immigration to gun rights".'
p6509
aS'The ads \xe2\x80\x94 about 3,000 placed by 470 accounts and pages spending about $100,000 \xe2\x80\x94 were what the advertising industry calls "dark posts," seen only by a very specific audience, obscured by the flow of posts within a Facebook News Feed and ephemeral.'
p6510
aS'Facebook calls its "dark post" service "unpublished page post ads".'
p6511
aS'This should not surprise us.'
p6512
aS'Anyone can deploy Facebook ads.'
p6513
aS'They are affordable and easy.'
p6514
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s one reason that Facebook has grown so quickly, taking in $27.6 billion in revenue in 2016, virtually all of it from advertisers, by serving up the attention of two billion Facebook users across the globe.'
p6515
aS'The service is popular among advertisers for its efficiency, effectiveness and responsiveness.'
p6516
aS'Facebook gives rich and instant feedback to advertisers, allowing them to quickly tailor ads to improve outcomes or customize messages even more.'
p6517
aS'There is nothing mysterious or untoward about the system itself, as long as it\xe2\x80\x99s being used for commerce instead of politics.'
p6518
aS'What\xe2\x80\x99s alarming is that Facebook executives don\xe2\x80\x99t seem to grasp, or appreciate, the difference.'
p6519
aS'A core principle in political advertising is transparency \xe2\x80\x94 political ads are supposed to be easily visible to everyone, and everyone is supposed to understand that they are political ads, and where they come from.'
p6520
aS'And it\xe2\x80\x99s expensive to run even one version of an ad in traditional outlets, let alone a dozen different versions.'
p6521
aS'Moreover, in the case of federal campaigns in the United States, the 2002 McCain-Feingold campaign-finance act requires candidates to state they approve of an ad and thus take responsibility for its content.'
p6522
aS'None of that transparency matters to Facebook.'
p6523
aS'Ads on the site meant for, say, 20- to 30-year-old home-owning Latino men in Northern Virginia would not be viewed by anyone else, and would run only briefly before vanishing.'
p6524
aS'The potential for abuse is vast.'
p6525
aS'An ad could falsely accuse a candidate of the worst malfeasance a day before Election Day, and the victim would have no way of even knowing it happened.'
p6526
aS'Ads could stoke ethnic hatred and no one could prepare or respond before serious harm occurs.'
p6527
aS'Unfortunately, the range of potential responses to this problem is limited.'
p6528
aS'The First Amendment grants broad protections to publishers like Facebook.'
p6529
aS'Diplomacy, even the harsh kind, has failed to dissuade Russia from meddling.'
p6530
aS'And it\xe2\x80\x99s even less likely to under the current administration.'
p6531
aS'Daniel Kreiss, a communication scholar at the University of North Carolina, proposes that sites such as Facebook, Twitter and YouTube maintain a repository of campaign ads so that regulators, scholars, journalists and the public can examine and expose them.'
p6532
aS'But the companies have no impetus to concur and coordinate.'
p6533
aS'And Congress is unlikely to reform a system that campaigns are just learning to master.'
p6534
aS'Facebook has no incentive to change its ways.'
p6535
aS'The money is too great.'
p6536
aS'The issue is too nebulous to alienate more than a few Facebook users.'
p6537
aS'The more that Facebook saturates our lives, families and communities, the harder it is to live without it.'
p6538
aS'Facebook has pledged to install better filtering systems using artificial intelligence and machine-learning to flag accounts that are run by automated "bots" or violate the site\xe2\x80\x99s terms of service.'
p6539
aS'But these are just new versions of the technologies that have caused the problem in the first place.'
p6540
aS'And there would be no accountability beyond Facebook\xe2\x80\x99s word.'
p6541
aS'The fact remains that in the arms race to keep propaganda flowing, human beings review troublesome accounts only long after the damage has been done.'
p6542
aS'Our best hopes sit in Brussels and London.'
p6543
aS'European regulators have been watching Facebook and Google for years.'
p6544
aS'They have taken strong actions against both companies for violating European consumer data protection standards and business competition laws.'
p6545
aS'The British government is investigating the role Facebook and its use of citizens\xe2\x80\x99 data played in the 2016 Brexit referendum and 2017 national elections.'
p6546
aS'We are in the midst of a worldwide, internet-based assault on democracy.'
p6547
aS'Scholars at the Oxford Internet Institute have tracked armies of volunteers and bots as they move propaganda across Facebook and Twitter in efforts to undermine trust in democracy or to elect their preferred candidates in the Philippines, India, France, the Netherlands, Britain and elsewhere.'
p6548
aS'We now know that agents in Russia are exploiting the powerful Facebook advertising system directly.'
p6549
aS'In the 21st-century social media information war, faith in democracy is the first casualty.'
