p7410
aS'The American way of war also inflicted a huge toll on village life in South Vietnam.'
p7411
aS'To limit its own casualties and cope with unfamiliar and often inhospitable terrain, the United States unleashed extraordinary firepower on the country it was trying to save.'
p7412
aS'Areas of suspected enemy strength were bombed and shelled and burned with napalm, often with little consideration of its impact on civilians.'
p7413
aS'Defoliants were used to deny the enemy food and cover, with horrific short- and long-term consequences for Vietnamese.'
p7414
aS'American firepower destroyed homes, villages and crops and alienated those whose hearts and minds were to be won.'
p7415
aS'American commanders declared entire areas free-fire zones.'
p7416
aS'Troops would round up villagers, burn their hooches and relocate them from their ancestral lands into squalid refugee camps.'
p7417
aS'The area would then be bombed and shelled.'
p7418
aS'During Operation Cedar Falls in 1967, Americans forcibly relocated some 6,000 civilians from the village of Ben Suc.'
p7419
aS'Caught between the Viet Cong and the Americans, villagers who wanted only to be left alone became sullen or outright hostile.'
p7420
aS'By early 1967, over 1.5 million refugees had drifted into urban slums, where they were susceptible to Viet Cong propaganda.'
p7421
aS'To be sure, many Americans developed close ties with Vietnamese.'
p7422
aS'Many also committed acts of kindness such as providing medical care and food to people in need.'
p7423
aS'Especially in the early years and in remote areas, American advisers formed attachments with Vietnamese soldiers and villagers.'
p7424
aS'Thousands of troops married Vietnamese women.'
p7425
aS'Still, most Americans arrived in the country without knowledge of the land and the people.'
p7426
aS'"My time in Vietnam is the memory of ignorance," one soldier later wrote.'
p7427
aS'Not knowing the language or culture, the Americans did not know what the people felt, or even at times how to tell friend from foe.'
p7428
aS'"What we need is some kind of litmus paper than turns red when it\xe2\x80\x99s near a Communist," one officer half-jokingly told a journalist.'
p7429
aS'Relations with South Vietnamese soldiers were likewise strained.'
p7430
aS'Unaware of the difficulties their counterparts labored under, American troops disparaged their fighting qualities.'
p7431
aS'The newcomers expected the people they were defending to offer the sort of gratitude they believed their fathers had gained for liberating France in World War II.'
p7432
aS'When instead they encountered indifference or even hostility, they grew resentful.'
p7433
aS'For many Americans, the South Vietnamese became an object of contempt, even hatred.'
p7434
aS'"The people were treacherous," one soldier later recalled.'
p7435
aS'"They say \xe2\x80\x98G.I. No. 1\xe2\x80\x99 when we\xe2\x80\x99re in the village, but at night the dirty little rats are V.C." The ability of the villagers to step around mines and booby traps that killed and maimed Americans provoked suspicion of collusion \xe2\x80\x94 and anger.'
p7436
aS'Americans also brought with them deeply entrenched racist attitudes that prompted the use of slurs such as "gook" and "dink," which they applied to enemy and friend alike.'
p7437
aS'Contempt could quickly change to a rage that might be turned on Vietnamese civilians.'
p7438
aS'During the summer and fall of 1967, the notorious Tiger Force, an elite commando unit, was assigned to remove civilians from the Song Ve River Valley, suspected to be a source of rice for Viet Cong units.'
p7439
aS'The very name of the mission, Operation Rawhide, suggested a cattle roundup, which had a dehumanizing effect.'
p7440
aS'When the civilians resisted, the Tigers vented their rage by burning their villages.'
p7441
aS'Unhappy with the assignment and under constant fire from enemy snipers, the Americans declared the area a free-fire zone and shot anything that moved, resulting in the brutal killing of numerous civilians.'
p7442
aS'Nevertheless, the Tigers were assigned another, similar mission, to remove civilians from Quang Tin province.'
p7443
aS'Early in the operation, they were caught in a deadly ambush and suffered heavy losses.'
p7444
aS'After that, all restraints came off.'
p7445
aS'Commanders abetted their vengeance by setting a body count goal of 327 kills (to match the number of the 327 Infantry Regiment, of which the Tigers were a part).'
p7446
aS'The Tigers proceeded to kill hundreds of civilians and compounded their crime by mutilating the bodies of victims, including old women and even babies.'
p7447
aS'The carnage stopped only when the operation ended in November.'
p7448
aS'The actions of the Tiger Force were replicated with even more savage results at My Lai, in Quang Ngai province, in February 1968, where American soldiers killed hundreds of Vietnamese civilians.'
p7449
aS'Such atrocities were not typical of American behavior, and even at My Lai there were soldiers who pushed back against their commanders\xe2\x80\x99 orders to kill.'
p7450
aS'Nevertheless, the atrocious violence reflected attitudes toward Vietnamese that divided the two peoples and made the Vietnamese subservient to Americans.'
p7451
aS'Given the frustrations and failures and mounting casualties of the American war effort, atrocities were perhaps only a matter of time.'
