aS'MEXICO CITY \xe2\x80\x94 When the earthquake rattled this mountain capital on Tuesday, a five-story office and apartment block round the corner from my home collapsed into a mountain of rubble, burying computer programmers, salesmen, secretaries.'
p7492
aS'Right away, a handful of neighbors approached the wreckage, calling to see if anyone was alive and removing debris.'
p7493
aS'Within hours, the group had swelled into the hundreds, joined by volunteers from across the city arriving by foot, truck and bicycle.'
p7494
aS'The volunteers shoveled rubble into buckets and cleared it from the scene in human chains.'
p7495
aS'Firefighters, civil defense workers and finally soldiers arrived and labored in unison with the civilians.'
p7496
aS'At intervals, they would shout for people to be silent and raise their fists as they listened for the sounds of survivors.'
p7497
aS'Hundreds more volunteers organized to supply water, food and tools as the force worked through the night.'
p7498
aS'This immense human effort, shown in the pictures of ordinary men and women sweating with spades, running with wheelbarrows, passing stretchers over their heads will surely be the lasting image of the 7.1 magnitude tremor that struck Mexico less than two weeks after a more distant 8.1 earthquake.'
p7499
aS'It is a story of tragedy, but also of solidarity and hope.'
p7500
aS'"I felt I had to do something," says Sergio Fragoso, a 31-year-old music producer, who came on a borrowed bike to toil at the site for 16 hours straight, his determination conquering his exhaustion.'
p7501
aS'"I thought about what it would be like if it was me trapped under there. I would want people to help".'
p7502
aS'Similar scenes were repeated at dozens of collapsed buildings across the battered capital as thousands of volunteers worked nonstop.'
p7503
aS'Their efforts paid off, with more than 50 people rescued by the end of Wednesday, the mayor announced.'
p7504
aS'On Thursday morning, workers used jackhammers to break up the last concrete blocks left at the building near my home.'
p7505
aS'The entire office block had been cleared in less than two days, an incredible physical feat.'
p7506
aS'The effort was all the more impressive considering the scale of the devastation.'
p7507
aS'Electricity and phone lines were down in much of the city, streets were blocked by debris and broken glass, and it was difficult to move anywhere.'
p7508
aS'People were scrambling to find their own loved ones and get them to hospitals.'
p7509
aS'I saw a man running through the street with an unconscious girl in his arms, another stumbling with a bleeding head into an ambulance.'
p7510
aS'Many abandoned their cracked homes, fearing they could also collapse.'
p7511
aS'But despite people\xe2\x80\x99s own problems, they were ready to help those they didn\xe2\x80\x99t even know.'
p7512
aS'The roots of this human force lie in the earthquake that hammered Mexico City on exactly the same day 32 years earlier and killed thousands.'
p7513
aS'Back then, civilian brigades also formed, although they took longer to mobilize and didn\xe2\x80\x99t work alongside soldiers.'
p7514
aS'It was an era of one-party rule, and the government tried to hide the scale of the damage and stop civilians from helping, worried that groups of Good Samaritans in the streets could turn into political protesters.'
p7515
aS'The stories of those volunteers of 1985 feature strongly in the collective memory of Mexico City residents, known as "chilangos".'
p7516
aS'When the nightmare was relived, the new generation drew on this memory to act.'
p7517
aS'Lorenzo Meyer, a politics professor and author, joined the volunteer forces of 1985, and is proud that his grown-up children took to the streets this week.'
p7518
aS'He described the stark differences between the two experiences.'
p7519
aS'"Back then, we took almost two days to get to the buildings," he said.'
p7520
aS'This time, there were text messages and social media feeds telling people where to go.'
p7521
aS'"It was very hard to find information on what was happening. And now the social energy is so strong it\xe2\x80\x99s impossible to repress".'
p7522
aS'The brigades of 1985 had an impact on Mexican politics, Dr. Meyer said.'
p7523
aS'Angry with a government they saw as uncaring, these empowered volunteers sought change.'
p7524
aS'Many became activists fighting to end the hegemonic rule of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or P.R.I. The capital became a bastion of opposition, and the P.R.I. lost political control of it in 1997, before losing the presidency in 2000, after seven decades.'
p7525
aS'The latest mass mobilization may also have a lasting political effect.'
p7526
aS'The country now has multiparty democracy, and more open media and civil society.'
p7527
aS'But people are angry about officials embezzling millions of dollars, governors working with drug traffickers and brutal violence that haunts communities.'
p7528
aS'The P.R.I. returned to power in 2012 under President Enrique Pe\xc3\xb1a Nieto, but he has suffered his own corruption scandals and his approval ratings have at times dropped to the teens.'
p7529
aS'A certain political reaction to the earthquake is already erupting.'
p7530
aS'As it became clear that thousands had lost their homes from the tremor, people started online petitions calling for Mexico\xe2\x80\x99s electoral institute to redirect hefty campaign finances for a presidential vote next year to earthquake relief.'
p7531
aS'One of   rapidly topped a million signatures.'
p7532
aS'A group created to support the petitions,  , emphasizes the links between the political movements of past and present.'
p7533
aS'"After the earthquake of 1985, Mexican civil society showed a power of solidarity and union without precedent; now we need it again," it says on its page on the Change.org petition website.'
p7534
aS'A heightened awareness of people power could favor the presidential hopeful Andr\xc3\xa9s Manuel L\xc3\xb3pez Obrador, who trumpets a populist anti-establishment discourse from the left.'
p7535
aS'A former Mexico City mayor, he already leads many opinion polls for the 2018 election as he calls for "el pueblo" to defeat a "mafia of power".'
p7536
aS'However, the advantage could swing to an independent candidate who offers an alternative to politicians and appeals to the many young professionals in the ranks of the volunteer brigades.'
p7537
aS'Various personalities, including a TV anchor, an academic and a human rights defender, have expressed interest in running.'
p7538
aS'It could also strengthen Mexico\xe2\x80\x99s resolve against the aggressive stance of the Trump administration, Dr. Meyer said.'
