aS'An independent Kurdish state would be a victory for democratic values, national self-determination and the rights of women and minorities.'
p8196
aS'Is there a more iconic image of the fight against the Islamic State than that of female Kurdish peshmerga fighters doing battle on the front lines against jihadists who demand the subjugation of women?'
p8197
aS'An independent Kurdish state would empower these warriors in a part of the world where women and girls are typically second-class citizens.'
p8198
aS'In addition to its commitment to gender equality, Kurdistan has also shown its commitment to minority rights.'
p8199
aS'Over the past three years, Kurdistan, which is about the size of Maryland, has taken in nearly two million refugees, including Assyrians, Yazidis, Turkmen, Shabaks and Christians fleeing the Islamic State and sectarian violence in other parts of Iraq and in Syria.'
p8200
aS'Even without a formal state, the Kurds have built a society that meets many of the criteria of statehood.'
p8201
aS'They are economically viable, with a well-developed energy industry.'
p8202
aS'They have functioning institutions, including elections for Parliament and a relatively free media.'
p8203
aS'And they\xe2\x80\x99ve proved capable of defending themselves against the Islamic State without attacking others.'
p8204
aS'Kurdistan is already, in values and governance, a democratic nation in waiting.'
p8205
aS'Is it a perfect Jeffersonian democracy?'
p8206
aS'No.'
p8207
aS'Does it have a long way to go?'
p8208
aS'Yes.'
p8209
aS'But in a region where tyranny is the norm, it\xe2\x80\x99s on the right track.'
p8210
aS'With a state, the Kurds could become an even more valuable and constructive ally against extremism.'
p8211
aS'That would be in the American interest, but just as important, it would be a fulfillment of American values.'
p8212
aS'Supporting Kurdish independence means supporting the right to self-determination of a people that have overcome oppression, persecution and tyranny to build a thriving, vibrant society.'
p8213
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s one of the reasons Israel supports the Kurds\xe2\x80\x99 right to self-determination.'
p8214
aS'Some 30 years ago, the Kurdish people were being choked with chemical weapons by Saddam Hussein.'
p8215
aS'Today they stand as a nation reborn, about to embark on an inspiring exercise in democracy.'
p8216
aS'We have a moral duty to support its outcome.'
p8217
aS'In a region where the flags of liberal democracies are routinely set alight, Kurdistan has chosen to embrace liberal democratic values.'
p8218
aS'Now the United States faces a critical choice.'
p8219
aS'President Trump has the chance to demonstrate American leadership, promote American values and strengthen an American ally.'
p8220
aS'Israel would welcome his support for the Kurds.'
p8221
aS'And if handled intelligently, the pragmatic Arab states such as Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Jordan and the United Arab Emirates could follow suit, on the grounds that Kurdistan could serve as a bulwark against Iran and the Islamic State.'
p8222
aS'If we wait for the region to be perfectly stable, for Islamist extremism to disappear or for the collective blessing of Ankara, Tehran and Baghdad, we could be waiting forever.'
p8223
aS'If, however, the United States wants to support a stabilizing, modernizing and democratic force, the choice is clear: Mr. Trump should bet on a winner and support an independent Kurdish state.'
p8224
aS'Pakistan is often seen as a country with a small Birkin-bag-sporting elite, a poverty-ridden mass and little in between.'
p8225
aS'The reality is that Pakistan does have a large urban population, which identifies itself as middle class.'
p8226
aS'Being middle class is a status closely associated with a progressive modernity \xe2\x80\x94 in Pakistan, in India \xe2\x80\x94 that individuals and successive governments alike yearn for.'
p8227
aS'In undivided, colonial India, the term "middle class" was associated with Indian officials, bureaucrats, doctors, lawyers and teachers who were linked to the colonial state.'
p8228
aS'But while they displayed the values and ambitions of the modernizing English middle class \xe2\x80\x94 mediating between the rulers and the ruled \xe2\x80\x94 many of them came from aristocratic and landed backgrounds.'
p8229
aS'After the formation of Pakistan in 1947, the families employed in the colonial government were at the forefront of the national project of modernization, along with emerging groups such as urban professionals from India and educated families from smaller towns in Punjab.'
p8230
aS'They are known as the "old middle class" in contemporary Pakistan.'
p8231
aS'Their children don\xe2\x80\x99t work for the state but tend to be employed at midlevel and top positions in the more lucrative private sector.'
p8232
aS'In Lahore, Pakistan\xe2\x80\x99s second-largest city, old middle-class families distance themselves from the upwardly mobile through their genealogical ties to prestigious families, local notables and their display of affinity for the "lost" culture of the 1950s and 1960s.'
p8233
aS'They share photos and stories of Ava Gardner staying at Faletti\xe2\x80\x99s Hotel during the filming of "Bhowani Junction" and Dizzy Gillespie playing saxophone with a snake charmer \xe2\x80\x94 evidence of a period when Pakistan enjoyed a more favorable global reputation.'
p8234
aS'The old middle class sees Pakistan as being on the path toward modernity before the Islamization agenda of Gen. Zia-ul-Haq (1978-88) brought upheaval.'
p8235
aS'Their nostalgia influences foreign commentators, who tend to showcase events, such as literary festivals, that glorify the earlier progressive history of the country.'
p8236
aS'Implicit in these portrayals is a vilification of the upwardly mobile groups whose more visible religiosity is viewed as the legacy of General Zia.'
p8237
aS'It is these groups that constitute the new urban middle class that has emerged since the 1980s.'
p8238
aS'In Lahore, many of them are second-generation migrants from small towns and rural areas in Punjab.'
p8239
aS'Products of the state education system of the 1980s \xe2\x80\x94 a time when General Zia gave religious clergy free rein and curbed political parties \xe2\x80\x94 most members of the new middle class are familiar with the discourses of Islamic groups.'
p8240
aS'While many are sympathetic to Islamist parties\xe2\x80\x99 call for social justice, and some have had affiliations with such groups, few are lasting members.'
p8241
aS'Support for an Islamist party is often issue-based and transient, and in most cases, does not translate into votes.'
p8242
aS'The new middle class has a strong sense that the solution to Pakistan\xe2\x80\x99s problems lies in becoming better Muslims and instilling Islamic values.'
p8243
aS'But it is also conspicuous for its members\xe2\x80\x99 considerable investment in the latest mobile phones and consumer electronics, along with frequent trips to Western-style shopping malls, megastores and markets in Lahore.'
p8244
aS'Careful attention is paid to rearing children: using branded diapers instead of local nappies, buying clothes from well-known Pakistani labels and feeding them Western-style snacks, such as chicken nuggets and instant noodles.'
p8245
aS'Yet twinned with the desire for consumption is anxiety about such exhibition and how to sustain it.'
p8246
aS'Most homes possess microwaves and mixer-grinders, but their owners use them sparingly and store them in their original packaging.'
p8247
aS'They buy sofas to match what they see in soap operas and advertisements, but protect them with plain sheets that are removed only on special occasions.'
p8248
aS'Families on the poorer end of the new middle class visit malls and shopping spaces for recreational experiences.'
p8249
aS'They rarely make purchases from such places and prefer to look for the same or similar goods in cheaper bazaars and wholesale markets.'
p8250
aS'Their ability to find more economical deals becomes a way to distinguish themselves from the presumed decadent and self-indulgent upper classes.'
p8251
aS'Members of the new middle class covet government employment, which still remains a mark of status, but such work does not provide sufficient income to sustain their idealized level of middle-class consumption.'
p8252
aS'Many in this group augment their state income through investment in real estate.'
p8253
aS'Many families in new middle-class circles have acquired their current status through money made by a relative in a semiskilled job in the Gulf countries or North America.'
p8254
aS'The most significant waves of semiskilled labor migration from Pakistan over the past half-century have been for industrial work in Britain in the 1960s, construction labor in Saudi Arabia and the Gulf in the 1970s and 1980s and, since the 1980s, taxi driving, construction and restaurant employment in the United States.'
p8255
aS'Pakistan received $20 billion in remittances in 2016, according to the World Bank.'
p8256
aS'The visible religiosity of the new middle class is often identified as the Wahhabi Islam of Saudi Arabia.'
p8257
aS'However, it is not Wahhabi Islam but the globalized Islam practiced by Muslims in the West that better explains contemporary religious trends.'
p8258
aS'Made familiar with Muslim practices abroad through relatives living abroad and returning migrants, many members of the new middle class have started incorporating them in their own lives.'
p8259
aS'For instance, Quran schools and religious study circles, where the Quran is studied with translation and interpretation, were introduced in Lahore in the early 2000s by returnees from the United States.'
p8260
aS'Similarly, many women have replaced dupattas and chadors \xe2\x80\x94 the traditional ways of showing modesty in public \xe2\x80\x94 with head scarves and cloaks similar to those worn by relatives in the West, Saudi Arabia or the Gulf.'
p8261
aS'It is not so much the desire to be closer to the heartland of Islam that prompts these changes, but the desire to display a modern Muslim identity, a shift commensurate with their economic progress.'
p8262
aS'Denied the status of modernity in the local class hierarchy, these groups look for it through a familiarity with a global Muslim community.'
p8263
aS'Just as the old middle class gains its modern status through a narrative that is used to explain Pakistan to the outside world, so the new middle class attempts to use its own connections to the West to assert its modernity.'
p8264
aS'Let me begin with thanks to the Lowy Institute for bringing me all the way to Sydney and doing me the honor of hosting me here this evening.'
p8265
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m aware of the controversy that has gone with my selection as your speaker.'
p8266
aS'I respect the wishes of the Colvin family and join in honoring Mark Colvin\xe2\x80\x99s memory as a courageous foreign correspondent and an extraordinary writer and broadcaster.'
p8267
aS'And I\xe2\x80\x99d particularly like to thank Michael Fullilove for not rescinding the invitation.'
p8268
aS'This has become the depressing trend on American university campuses, where the roster of disinvited speakers and forced cancellations includes former Secretaries of State Henry Kissinger and Condoleezza Rice, former Harvard University President Larry Summers, actor Alec Baldwin, human-rights activist Ayaan Hirsi Ali, DNA co-discoverer James Watson, Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi, filmmaker Michael Moore, conservative Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist George Will and liberal Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist Anna Quindlen, to name just a few.'
p8269
aS'So illustrious is the list that, on second thought, I\xe2\x80\x99m beginning to regret that you didn\xe2\x80\x99t disinvite me after all.'
p8270
aS'The title of my talk tonight is "The Dying Art of Disagreement".'
p8271
aS'This is a subject that is dear to me \xe2\x80\x94 literally dear \xe2\x80\x94 since disagreement is the way in which I have always earned a living.'
p8272
aS'Disagreement is dear to me, too, because it is the most vital ingredient of any decent society.'
p8273
aS'To say the words, "I agree" \xe2\x80\x94 whether it\xe2\x80\x99s agreeing to join an organization, or submit to a political authority, or subscribe to a religious faith \xe2\x80\x94 may be the basis of every community.'
p8274
aS'But to say, I disagree; I refuse; you\xe2\x80\x99re wrong;   \xe2\x80\x94 these are the words that define our individuality, give us our freedom, enjoin our tolerance, enlarge our perspectives, seize our attention, energize our progress, make our democracies real, and give hope and courage to oppressed people everywhere.'
p8275
aS'Galileo and Darwin; Mandela, Havel, and Liu Xiaobo; Rosa Parks and Natan Sharansky \xe2\x80\x94 such are the ranks of those who disagree.'
p8276
aS'And the problem, as I see it, is that we\xe2\x80\x99re failing at the task.'
p8277
aS'This is a puzzle.'
p8278
aS'At least as far as far as the United States is concerned, Americans have rarely disagreed more in recent decades.'
p8279
aS'We disagree about racial issues, bathroom policies, health care laws, and, of course, the 45th president.'
p8280
aS'We express our disagreements in radio and cable TV rants in ways that are increasingly virulent; street and campus protests that are increasingly violent; and personal conversations that are increasingly embittering.'
p8281
aS'This is yet another age in which we judge one another morally depending on where we stand politically.'
p8282
aS'Nor is this just an impression of the moment.'
p8283
aS'Extensive   show that Republicans are much more right-leaning than they were twenty years ago, Democrats much more left-leaning, and both sides much more likely to see the other as a mortal threat to the nation\xe2\x80\x99s welfare.'
p8284
aS'The polarization is geographic, as more people live in states and communities where their neighbors are much likelier to share their politics.'
p8285
aS'The polarization is personal: Fully 50 percent of Republicans would not want their child to marry a Democrat, and nearly a third of Democrats return the sentiment.'
p8286
aS'Interparty marriage has taken the place of interracial marriage as a family taboo.'
p8287
aS'Finally the polarization is electronic and digital, as Americans increasingly inhabit the filter bubbles of news and social media that correspond to their ideological affinities.'
p8288
aS'We no longer just have our own opinions.'
p8289
aS'We also have our separate "facts," often the result of what different media outlets consider newsworthy.'
p8290
aS'In the last election, fully 40 percent of Trump voters named Fox News as their chief source of news.'
p8291
aS'Thanks a bunch for that one, Australia.'
p8292
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s usually the case that the more we do something, the better we are at it.'
p8293
aS'Instead, we\xe2\x80\x99re like Casanovas in reverse: the more we do it, the worse we\xe2\x80\x99re at it.'
p8294
aS'Our disagreements may frequently hoarsen our voices, but they rarely sharpen our thinking, much less change our minds.'
p8295
aS'It behooves us to wonder why.'
p8296
aS'* * * Thirty years ago, in 1987, a philosophy professor at the University of Chicago named Allan Bloom \xe2\x80\x94 at the time best known for his graceful translations of Plato\xe2\x80\x99s "Republic" and Rousseau\xe2\x80\x99s "Emile" \xe2\x80\x94 published a learned polemic about the state of higher education in the United States.'
p8297
aS'It was called "The Closing of the American Mind".'
p8298
aS'The book appeared when I was in high school, and I struggled to make my way through a text thick with references to Plato, Weber, Heidegger and Strauss.'
p8299
aS'But I got the gist \xe2\x80\x94 and the gist was that I\xe2\x80\x99d better enroll in the University of Chicago and read the great books.'
p8300
aS'That is what I did.'
p8301
aS'What was it that one learned through a great books curriculum?'
p8302
aS'Certainly not "conservatism" in any contemporary American sense of the term.'
p8303
aS'We were not taught to become American patriots, or religious pietists, or to worship what Rudyard Kipling called "the Gods of the Market Place".'
p8304
aS'We were not instructed in the evils of Marxism, or the glories of capitalism, or even the superiority of Western civilization.'
p8305
aS'As I think about it, I\xe2\x80\x99m not sure we were taught anything at all.'
p8306
aS'What we did was read books that raised serious questions about the human condition, and which invited us to attempt to ask serious questions of our own.'
p8307
aS'Education, in this sense, wasn\xe2\x80\x99t a "teaching" with any fixed lesson.'
p8308
aS'It was an exercise in interrogation.'
p8309
aS'To listen and understand; to question and disagree; to treat no proposition as sacred and no objection as impious; to be willing to entertain unpopular ideas and cultivate the habits of an open mind \xe2\x80\x94 this is what I was encouraged to do by my teachers at the University of Chicago.'
p8310
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s what used to be called a liberal education.'
p8311
aS'The University of Chicago showed us something else: that every great idea is really just a spectacular disagreement with some other great idea.'
p8312
aS'Socrates quarrels with Homer.'
p8313
aS'Aristotle quarrels with Plato.'
p8314
aS'Locke quarrels with Hobbes and Rousseau quarrels with them both.'
p8315
aS'Nietzsche quarrels with everyone.'
p8316
aS'Wittgenstein quarrels with himself.'
p8317
aS'These quarrels are never personal.'
p8318
aS'Nor are they particularly political, at least in the ordinary sense of politics.'
p8319
aS'Sometimes they take place over the distance of decades, even centuries.'
p8320
aS'Most importantly, they are never based on a misunderstanding.'
p8321
aS'On the contrary, the disagreements arise from perfect  ; from having chewed over the ideas of your intellectual opponent so thoroughly that you can properly spit them out.'
p8322
aS'In other words, to disagree well you must first   well.'
p8323
aS'You have to read deeply, listen carefully, watch closely.'
p8324
aS'You need to grant your adversary moral respect; give him the intellectual benefit of doubt; have sympathy for his motives and participate empathically with his line of reasoning.'
p8325
aS'And you need to allow for the possibility that you might yet be persuaded of what he has to say.'
p8326
aS'"The Closing of the American Mind" took its place in the tradition of these quarrels.'
p8327
aS'Since the 1960s it had been the vogue in American universities to treat the so-called "Dead White European Males" of the Western canon as agents of social and political oppression.'
p8328
aS'Allan Bloom insisted that, to the contrary, they were the best possible instruments of spiritual liberation.'
p8329
aS'He also insisted that to sustain liberal democracy you needed liberally educated people.'
p8330
aS'This, at least, should not have been controversial.'
p8331
aS'For free societies to function, the idea of open-mindedness can\xe2\x80\x99t simply be a catchphrase or a dogma.'
p8332
aS'It needs to be a personal habit, most of all when it comes to preserving an open mind toward those with whom we disagree.'
p8333
aS'* * * That habit was no longer being exercised much 30 years ago.'
p8334
aS'And if you\xe2\x80\x99ve followed the news from American campuses in recent years, things have become a lot worse.'
p8335
aS'According to a   from the Brookings Institution, a plurality of college students today \xe2\x80\x94 fully 44 percent \xe2\x80\x94 do not believe the First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution protects so-called "hate speech," when of course it absolutely does.'
p8336
aS'More shockingly, a narrow majority of students \xe2\x80\x94 51 percent \xe2\x80\x94 think it is "acceptable" for a student group to shout down a speaker with whom they disagree.'
p8337
aS'An astonishing 20 percent also agree that it\xe2\x80\x99s acceptable to use violence to prevent a speaker from speaking.'
p8338
aS'These attitudes are being made plain nearly every week on one college campus or another.'
p8339
aS'There are speakers being shouted down by organized claques of hecklers \xe2\x80\x94 such was the experience of Israeli ambassador   at the University of California, Irvine.'
p8340
aS'Or speakers who require hundreds of thousands of dollars of security measures in order to appear on campus \xe2\x80\x94 such was the experience of conservative pundit   earlier this month at Berkeley.'
p8341
aS'Or speakers who are physically barred from reaching the auditorium \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s what happened to   at Claremont McKenna College in April.'
p8342
aS'Or teachers who are humiliated by their students and hounded from their positions for allegedly hurting students\xe2\x80\x99 feelings \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s what happened to Erika and Nicholas Christakis of Yale.'
p8343
aS'And there is violence.'
p8344
aS'Listen to a description from Middlebury College professor   of what happened when she moderated a conversation with the libertarian scholar Charles Murray in March: Middlebury is one of the most prestigious liberal-arts colleges in the United States, with an acceptance rate of just 16 percent and tuition fees of nearly $50,000 a year.'
p8345
aS'How does an elite institution become a factory for junior totalitarians, so full of their own certitudes that they could indulge their taste for bullying and violence?'
p8346
aS'There\xe2\x80\x99s no one answer.'
p8347
aS'What\xe2\x80\x99s clear is that the mis-education begins early.'
p8348
aS'I was raised on the old-fashioned view that sticks and stones could break my bones but words would never hurt me.'
p8349
aS'But today there\xe2\x80\x99s a belief that since words can cause stress, and stress can have physiological effects, stressful words are tantamount to a form of violence.'
p8350
aS'This is the age of protected feelings purchased at the cost of permanent infantilization.'
p8351
aS'The mis-education continues in grade school.'
p8352
aS'As the Brookings findings indicate, younger Americans seem to have no grasp of what our First Amendment says, much less of the kind of speech it protects.'
p8353
aS'This is a testimony to the collapse of civics education in the United States, creating the conditions that make young people uniquely susceptible to demagogy of the left- or right-wing varieties.'
p8354
aS'Then we get to college, where the dominant mode of politics is identity politics, and in which the primary test of an argument isn\xe2\x80\x99t the quality of the thinking but the cultural, racial, or sexual standing of the person making it.'
p8355
aS'This is the baroque way Americans often speak these days.'
p8356
aS'It is a way of replacing individual thought \xe2\x80\x94 with all the effort that actual thinking requires \xe2\x80\x94 with social identification \xe2\x80\x94 with all the attitude that attitudinizing requires.'
p8357
aS'In recent years, identity politics have become the moated castles from which we safeguard our feelings from hurt and our opinions from challenge.'
p8358
aS'It is our "safe space".'
p8359
aS'But it is a safe space of a uniquely pernicious kind \xe2\x80\x94 a safe space   thought, rather than a safe space   thought, to borrow a line I recently heard from Salman Rushdie.'
p8360
aS'Another consequence of identity politics is that it has made the distance between making an argument and causing offense terrifyingly short.'
p8361
aS'Any argument that can be cast as insensitive or offensive to a given group of people isn\xe2\x80\x99t treated as being merely wrong.'
p8362
aS'Instead it is seen as immoral, and therefore unworthy of discussion or rebuttal.'
p8363
aS'The result is that the disagreements we need to have \xe2\x80\x94 and to have vigorously \xe2\x80\x94 are banished from the public square before they\xe2\x80\x99re settled.'
p8364
aS'People who might otherwise join a conversation to see where it might lead them choose instead to shrink from it, lest they say the "wrong" thing and be accused of some kind of political -ism or -phobia.'
p8365
aS'For fear of causing offense, they forego the opportunity to be persuaded.'
p8366
aS'Take the arguments over same-sex marriage, which you are now debating in Australia.'
p8367
aS'My own views in favor of same-sex marriage are well known, and I hope the Yes\xe2\x80\x99s wins by a convincing margin.'
p8368
aS'But if I had to guess, I suspect the No\xe2\x80\x99s will exceed whatever they are currently polling.'
p8369
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s because the case for same-sex marriage is too often advanced not by reason, but merely by branding every opponent of it as a "bigot" \xe2\x80\x94 just because they are sticking to an opinion that was shared across the entire political spectrum only a few years ago.'
p8370
aS'Few people like outing themselves as someone\xe2\x80\x99s idea of a bigot, so they keep their opinions to themselves even when speaking to pollsters.'
p8371
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s just what happened last year in the Brexit vote and the U.S. presidential election, and look where we are now.'
p8372
aS'If you want to make a winning argument for same-sex marriage, particularly against conservative opponents, make it on a conservative foundation: As a matter of individual freedom, and as an avenue toward moral responsibility and social respectability.'
p8373
aS'The No\xe2\x80\x99s will have a hard time arguing with that.'
p8374
aS'But if you call them morons and Neanderthals, all you\xe2\x80\x99ll get in return is their middle finger or their clenched fist.'
p8375
aS'One final point about identity politics: It\xe2\x80\x99s a game at which two can play.'
p8376
aS'In the United States, the so-called "alt-right" justifies its white-identity politics in terms that are coyly borrowed from the progressive left.'
p8377
aS'One of the more dismaying features of last year\xe2\x80\x99s election was the extent to which "white working class" became a catchall identity for people whose travails we were supposed to pity but whose habits or beliefs we were not supposed to criticize.'
p8378
aS'The result was to give the Trump base a moral pass it did little to earn.'
p8379
aS'* * * So here\xe2\x80\x99s where we stand: Intelligent disagreement is the lifeblood of any thriving society.'
p8380
aS'Yet we in the United States are raising a younger generation who have never been taught either the how or the why of disagreement, and who seem to think that free speech is a one-way right: Namely, their right to disinvite, shout down or abuse anyone they dislike, lest they run the risk of listening to that person \xe2\x80\x94 or even allowing someone else to listen.'
p8381
aS'The results are evident in the parlous state of our universities, and the frayed edges of our democracies.'
p8382
aS'Can we do better?'
p8383
aS'This is supposed to be a lecture on the media, and I\xe2\x80\x99d like to conclude this talk with a word about the role that editors and especially publishers can play in ways that might improve the state of public discussion rather than just reflect and accelerate its decline.'
p8384
aS'I began this talk by noting that Americans have rarely disagreed so vehemently about so much.'
p8385
aS'On second thought, this isn\xe2\x80\x99t the whole truth.'
p8386
aS'Yes, we disagree constantly.'
p8387
aS'But what makes our disagreements so toxic is that we refuse to make eye contact with our opponents, or try to see things as they might, or find some middle ground.'
p8388
aS'Instead, we fight each other from the safe distance of our separate islands of ideology and identity and listen intently to echoes of ourselves.'
p8389
aS'We take exaggerated and histrionic offense to whatever is said about us.'
p8390
aS'We banish entire lines of thought and attempt to excommunicate all manner of people \xe2\x80\x94 your humble speaker included \xe2\x80\x94 without giving them so much as a cursory hearing.'
p8391
aS'The crucial prerequisite of intelligent disagreement \xe2\x80\x94 namely: shut up; listen up; pause and reconsider; and only then speak \xe2\x80\x94 is absent.'
p8392
aS'Perhaps the reason for this is that we have few obvious models for disagreeing well, and those we do have \xe2\x80\x94 such as the Intelligence Squared debates in New York and London or Fareed Zakaria\xe2\x80\x99s show on CNN \xe2\x80\x94 cater to a sliver of elite tastes, like classical music.'
p8393
aS'Fox News and other partisan networks have demonstrated that the quickest route to huge profitability is to serve up a steady diet of high-carb, low-protein populist pap.'
p8394
aS'Reasoned disagreement of the kind that could serve democracy well fails the market test.'
p8395
aS'Those of us who otherwise believe in the virtues of unfettered capitalism should bear that fact in mind.'
p8396
aS'I do not believe the answer, at least in the U.S., lies in heavier investment in publicly sponsored television along the lines of the BBC.'
p8397
aS'It too, suffers, from its own form of ideological conformism and journalistic groupthink, immunized from criticism due to its indifference to competition.'
p8398
aS'Nor do I believe the answer lies in a return to what in America used to be called the "Fairness Doctrine," mandating equal time for different points of view.'
p8399
aS'Free speech must ultimately be free, whether or not it\xe2\x80\x99s fair.'
p8400
aS'But I do think there\xe2\x80\x99s such a thing as private ownership in the public interest, and of fiduciary duties not only to shareholders but also to citizens.'
p8401
aS'Journalism is not just any other business, like trucking or food services.'
p8402
aS'Nations can have lousy food and exemplary government, as Great Britain demonstrated for most of the last century.'
p8403
aS'They can also have great food and lousy government, as France has always demonstrated.'
p8404
aS'But no country can have good government, or a healthy public square, without high-quality journalism \xe2\x80\x94 journalism that can distinguish a fact from a belief and again from an opinion; that understands that the purpose of opinion isn\xe2\x80\x99t to depart from facts but to use them as a bridge to a larger idea called "truth"; and that appreciates that truth is a large enough destination that, like Manhattan, it can be reached by many bridges of radically different designs.'
p8405
aS'In other words, journalism that is grounded in facts while abounding in disagreements.'
p8406
aS'I believe it is still possible \xe2\x80\x94 and all the more necessary \xe2\x80\x94 for journalism to perform these functions, especially as the other institutions that were meant to do so have fallen short.'
p8407
aS'But that requires proprietors and publishers who understand that their role ought not to be to push a party line, or be a slave to Google hits and Facebook ads, or provide a titillating kind of news entertainment, or help out a president or prime minister who they favor or who\xe2\x80\x99s in trouble.'
p8408
aS'Their role is to clarify the terms of debate by championing aggressive and objective news reporting, and improve the quality of debate with commentary that opens minds and challenges assumptions rather than merely confirming them.'
