aS'Brazil is home to   of uncontacted indigenous communities of any country in the world.'
p8454
aS'Hidden deep in primeval Amazon forests, these groups represent the final frontier of a seemingly inexorable conquest that began with the landing of Portuguese and Spanish navigators on South America\xe2\x80\x99s shores at the start of the 16th century.'
p8455
aS'The history of Brazil\xe2\x80\x99s Amazon region, as elsewhere in the Americas, abounds with tales of mass death and brutality perpetrated against its native inhabitants.'
p8456
aS'Entire tribes disappeared, many without a trace.'
p8457
aS'Few of these atrocities figured in official accounts; rarely was anyone brought to justice.'
p8458
aS'But 30 years ago, Brazil took an extraordinary step toward halting the march of this dismal history.'
p8459
aS'It recognized the right of its indigenous people to pursue their traditional ways of life, including remaining apart from modern society.'
p8460
aS'It also recognized that they require intact, pristine forests and rivers to survive as they have since before the arrival of Europeans.'
p8461
aS'To that end, the government created a special unit inside Funai, its indigenous affairs agency.'
p8462
aS'The unit was charged with protecting those untrammeled lands and ensuring the viability of the indigenous communities living within them.'
p8463
aS'Field agents who previously sought to woo uncontacted tribes from the bush were assigned a new role: to identify the forests where such tribes live and staff outposts to block intrusions that could threaten the well-being of the native populations.'
p8464
aS'The rights of these tribes \xe2\x80\x94 and the government\xe2\x80\x99s duty to safeguard them \xe2\x80\x94 were enshrined in statutes, international agreements and the country\xe2\x80\x99s 1988 Constitution, which remains the law of the land, at least on paper.'
p8465
aS'But Brazil is rapidly backpedaling on these commitments.'
p8466
aS'Severe budget cuts to Funai and the forced retirement of its most seasoned backwoods officials have caused the withdrawal of personnel and the closing of nearly one-third of the control posts that guard access to the territories of isolated tribes across the Amazon.'
p8467
aS'And now Brazilian officials are   believed to have taken place in August on a riverbank deep in the Amazon rain forest.'
p8468
aS'The tribe that suffered this latest atrocity is known as the flecheiros \xe2\x80\x94 or Arrow People \xe2\x80\x94 a seldom-glimpsed group of hunter-gatherers living in extreme isolation inside the Javari Valley indigenous land, one of a dozen reserves in the Amazon that are home to uncontacted indigenous populations.'
p8469
aS'I am one of few outsiders to see the flecheiros, albeit fleetingly.'
p8470
aS'I trekked through their land on a 10-week expedition through the far reaches of the Javari Valley with Funai in 2002.'
p8471
aS'Officials and indigenous scouts were on a mission to protect the flecheiros, collecting information from their abandoned campsites and monitoring possible threats to their territory, while seeking to avoid direct contact with them.'
p8472
aS'Many of these isolated groups splintered off from larger, now-settled communities, and their cultures are familiar to anthropologists and other experts.'
p8473
aS'But the flecheiros have remained so isolated that we do not know what their ethnicity is, what language they speak or what they call themselves.'
p8474
aS'We do know that they are deft archers who have retreated into one of the Amazon\xe2\x80\x99s most inaccessible redoubts, from which they shun all contact with the outside world.'
p8475
aS'This latest incident goes a long way toward explaining their choice.'
p8476
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s also the clearest signal yet that Brazil\xe2\x80\x99s failure to uphold its constitutional obligations carries with it lethal consequences.'
p8477
aS'The Javari Valley indigenous land has been a secure bastion for the flecheiros and 15 other isolated tribal groups by dint of its rugged topography and the policies put in place to protect them.'
p8478
aS'Until now.'
p8479
aS'The government outpost on the Jandiatuba River, where the massacre is reported to have occurred, was shut down in 2014 because of budget cuts.'
p8480
aS'Since then, alluvial gold dredges, largely manned by itinerant desperados, have penetrated deep upriver.'
p8481
aS'Some of the prospectors also venture out to hunt bushmeat, and it was such a hunting party that came upon the flecheiros.'
p8482
aS'The miners\xe2\x80\x99 reaction apparently was swift and definitive.'
p8483
aS'Had the checkpoint on the Jandiatuba River remained in operation, it\xe2\x80\x99s likely this terrible encounter could have been avoided.'
p8484
aS'There would be no gold dredges ransacking the Jandiatuba, one of the principal watersheds that sustain the flecheiros, nor hunters stalking game deep in their forests.'
p8485
aS'As we hiked through the primal homeland of the flecheiros 15 years ago, we found ample evidence that Brazil\xe2\x80\x99s policies were working as intended: towering trees dripping with lianas, crystal-clear streams teeming with fish, an astonishing abundance of birds and wild animals, as well as a profound sense of security the flecheiros must have been enjoying.'
