aS'I do not know how to drive.'
p8597
aS'My middle sister, Kerri, learned to drive a few years ago.'
p8598
aS'We are both well into adulthood, but I still rely on her and our oldest sister, Kirsten, for any sort of transportation outside of New York City.'
p8599
aS'So this summer, when we took a road trip, with our mother and Kirsten\xe2\x80\x99s husband and two children, to women\xe2\x80\x99s history sites, I found myself in the slightly disempowering back seat while on a search for empowerment.'
p8600
aS'It was a road trip to answer the following question: What does the rallying cry of sisterhood and the concept of feminism mean when last year, the majority of white, female voters chose whiteness as a political identity over womanhood?'
p8601
aS'What does feminism mean to each of us, as black women, when we had just lived through an election season of hearing candidates and commentators use that old, unexamined phrase, "women and black people," skipping over our existence as both?'
p8602
aS'How do we understand women\xe2\x80\x99s history as triumphant when we are still smarting from the very public smackdown of a woman attempting to reach the highest seat of power?'
p8603
aS'My sisters were the perfect people with whom to seek some answers.'
p8604
aS'I idolized my sister Kerri growing up.'
p8605
aS'I still do.'
p8606
aS'When she was a teenager and I was still in middle school, she wore high-rise short shorts and tube tops, the living embodiment of the song "Shoop," strutting down the halls of our super-white prep school.'
p8607
aS'She also played cello, loved Pushkin and read and wrote obsessively.'
p8608
aS'She was that thing that too much of America fears and ridicules \xe2\x80\x94 the loud, black teenage girl.'
p8609
aS'And now she\xe2\x80\x99s an academic, bumping vintage D\xe2\x80\x99Angelo in her hybrid car as she pulls into her university parking space.'
p8610
aS'I did not need critical race theory or third-wave feminism to tell me about the myth of the Jezebel.'
p8611
aS'I had Kerri.'
p8612
aS'My sister Kirsten taught me the importance of work for women.'
p8613
aS'There is the seductive, unobtainable fantasy of "A Room of One\xe2\x80\x99s Own," and then there is the reality of the life of a working mother and artist \xe2\x80\x94 revising your work and responding to students and drafting grant applications from the front seat of your car while your kids are in dance practice.'
p8614
aS'I watched her live the life of a playwright-mother, and seeing her do it gave me the courage to try for a similar life myself.'
p8615
aS'My sisters taught me how to be a feminist.'
p8616
aS'They taught me in their contradictions, in the fact that they contain multitudes.'
p8617
aS'My family is black in Northeastern America, which means our economic and social success was dependent on fleeing as far away from predominantly black neighborhoods and schools as possible.'
p8618
aS'So my upwardly mobile parents moved us to a predominantly white neighborhood and I always went to predominantly white schools.'
p8619
aS'My best friend was the little white girl who lived next door.'
p8620
aS'Her mother loves to tell this story: After playing at our house, she begged her mother for a Barbie.'
p8621
aS'On Christmas morning, my best friend opened her present and burst into tears.'
p8622
aS'"This is not Barbie"!'
p8623
aS'she sobbed.'
p8624
aS'She held up the white, blond Barbie in its box.'
p8625
aS'She has black curly hair!'
p8626
aS'"Barbie has brown skin! This is not the Barbie at Kaitlyn\xe2\x80\x99s house"!'
p8627
aS'Black womanhood was always centered in our home, so I didn\xe2\x80\x99t look at white women with envy because they were white.'
p8628
aS'And I was rarely instinctively suspicious of them.'
p8629
aS'Like most black and brown people in this country, despite what white people may believe, I was not actively looking for the ways whites slighted me because I was black.'
p8630
aS'Especially when you live and work in predominantly white spaces, you have to hold on to the social fiction that white people are responding to you as an individual.'
p8631
aS'If you do not hold on to that lie, or at least use it judiciously, you risk going mad with grief and anger.'
p8632
aS'But since the election, that has changed.'
p8633
aS'The art historian Moyo Okediji notes that in Yoruban concepts of history, the community must assure children that they are not physically alone and "that a series of road maps exists, made by great and talented ancestors who as individuals have beaten a track for succeeding generations".'
p8634
aS'That is why history is a comfort to me, in times of doubt.'
p8635
aS'And this is, of course, why the past is a battleground.'
p8636
aS'Why we fight about statues, and which system of oppression should be enshrined in bronze to be remembered or torn down to be recorded differently.'
p8637
aS'I have seen, first hand, how understanding history can change people\xe2\x80\x99s present-day attitudes.'
