aS'A decade ago, in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, I led a group of black high school students on a tour of the Hunterfly Road Houses.'
p8639
aS'I told them the story of black self-determination and liberation in 19th-century Brooklyn.'
p8640
aS'By the end, these students literally broke into song \xe2\x80\x94 a spontaneous rendition about freedom and joy and black excellence.'
p8641
aS'It was one of the most profound moments of my life.'
p8642
aS'Whenever anyone insists that the past doesn\xe2\x80\x99t matter, that we should get over it, I think of those students, dancing on a lawn in central Brooklyn on a school-day afternoon, stepping to the rhythm of the names of black abolitionists.'
p8643
aS'This July, my sisters and I were chasing something like that feeling.'
p8644
aS'We wanted to find women who could remind us that another, more tolerant, hopeful way of being is possible.'
p8645
aS'It was possible 150 years ago, during a time when people supposedly didn\xe2\x80\x99t know any better \xe2\x80\x94 and we hoped that perspective would help us in this present time, when people supposedly do.'
p8646
aS'My sisters selected the following women to lead us on our tour: Prudence Crandall, Sarah Harris, Belinda Sutton and Ellen Garrison.'
p8647
aS'Our first stop is the Prudence Crandall Museum, a wide, Federalist-style building in Canterbury, Conn.'
p8648
aS'In 1831, Crandall, a young white woman, opened a school in the building for the daughters of the wealthy white families in town.'
p8649
aS'It was a success.'
p8650
aS'The next year, Sarah Harris, a 20-year-old black woman, wrote to Crandall.'
p8651
aS'Harris hoped to eventually open a school for black children in Connecticut.'
p8652
aS'She wrote: "Miss Crandall, I want to get a little more learning, if possible, enough to teach colored children and if you will admit me to your school, I shall forever be under greatest obligation to you. If you think it will be the means of injuring you, I will not insist on the favor".'
p8653
aS'I think about this letter, the carefulness of the words.'
p8654
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a tone that I recognize, that I think most people who have ever worked under oppression recognize.'
p8655
aS'It is the tone you adopt when you are unsure if the person you are talking to has the ability to see you as a fellow human.'
p8656
aS'Crandall admitted Harris, and the white parents pressured her to expel Harris.'
p8657
aS'Crandall refused, and parents removed their daughters.'
p8658
aS'In response, Crandall doubled down on her commitment to educating black women.'
p8659
aS'She reached out to black communities and to the white abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison to recruit more black female students.'
p8660
aS'The surrounding white community attacked the school and attempted to burn it down.'
p8661
aS'Connecticut passed a law that made it illegal to educate African-Americans who were not already state residents.'
p8662
aS'The museum has a section dedicated to the stories of the women who studied there.'
p8663
aS'Students returned to their states and started schools of their own for black people, started black newspapers and antislavery newspapers, and opened their homes to activists.'
p8664
aS'Kerri, history nerd that she is, recognizes all the names on the wall as though they are old friends.'
p8665
aS'Our next stop on the tour was the   and Slave Quarters, in Medford, Mass., home of the only standing slave quarters north of the Mason-Dixon line.'
p8666
aS'The Royalls were the largest slaveholding family in Massachusetts, making their money from the enslaved people who worked their plantations in the Caribbean.'
p8667
aS'The family used the fortune earned from enslaved labor to found Harvard Law School.'
p8668
aS'My sisters chose this stop because of Belinda Sutton, a woman the Royall family enslaved.'
p8669
aS'By her own account, she was born in Africa, kidnapped at around 12 and sold to the Royall plantation in Antigua.'
p8670
aS'She was enslaved into her old age.'
p8671
aS'When the family patriarch, Isaac Royall Jr., died, his will gave her the choice of freedom or enslavement.'
p8672
aS'Sutton, even at her advanced age, chose the unknown of freedom.'
p8673
aS'She was promised an annuity, which she successfully sued the Royall family for \xe2\x80\x94 twice.'
p8674
aS'Kirsten has been writing a play about Belinda Sutton for the past few years.'
p8675
aS'Standing in the stately home, Penny Outlaw, a co-president of the museum, reminded us that Isaac Royall Jr. opposed the American Revolution.'
p8676
aS'Yet, she told us on the tour, the American government compensated him fully for seizing his property during the war.'
p8677
aS'Sutton got three years\xe2\x80\x99 worth of compensation for more than 60 years of stolen labor, she said.'
p8678
aS'Unlike some other plantations, the Royall House museum emphasizes what the enslaved people there would have experienced.'
p8679
aS'In the main house, we are shown the slaves\xe2\x80\x99 staircase.'
p8680
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a winding staircase with only one or two windows and very little light.'
p8681
aS'There\xe2\x80\x99s no banister, the stairs are steep, and the walls would have been painted black, so that the handprints of the enslaved men and women using the stairs remained invisible.'
p8682
aS'"Can you imagine," Ms. Outlaw said, "going up and down these stairs on a winter night, in the dark"?'
p8683
aS'Our final stop, on the Fourth of July, was the Robbins House, in Concord, Mass.'
p8684
aS'The house now sits directly across the street from the North Bridge, on the site where the first successful battle of the Revolutionary War was fought.'
p8685
aS'The   was part of the farm that the patriarch of the family, Caesar Robbins, a previously enslaved man and a Revolutionary War veteran, was invited to live on.'
p8686
aS'The house, on the outskirts of Concord, was then far from the white residents.'
p8687
aS'A generation later, Thoreau would reference some of Robbins\xe2\x80\x99s descendants in his journals.'
p8688
aS'But to me, the most remarkable descendant was Ellen Garrison, born in the homestead in 1823.'
p8689
aS'As a young woman, she and her mother were deeply involved in the antislavery movement, and she signed petitions protesting the federal government\xe2\x80\x99s treatment of the Cherokee and calling for states to repeal the death penalty.'
