aS'U.S. President Donald Trump blocked a Chinese-backed private equity firm from buying a U.S.-based chipmaker on Wednesday, sending a clear signal to Beijing that Washington will oppose takeover deals that involve technologies with potential military applications.'
p8829
aS'Canyon Bridge Capital Partners\xe2\x80\x99 planned $1.3 billion acquisition of Lattice Semiconductor Corp was one of the largest attempted by a Chinese-backed firm in the U.S. microchip sector and was the first announced deal for the buyout fund, which launched last year with a focus on technology investment.'
p8830
aS'U.S. regulatory scrutiny grew after Reuters reported in November that Canyon Bridge was funded partly by capital from China\xe2\x80\x99s central government and had indirect links to its space program.'
p8831
aS'U.S. defense officials subsequently raised concerns about the Lattice acquisition by a firm backed by the Chinese government.'
p8832
aS'Portland, Oregon-based Lattice makes chips known as field-programmable gate arrays, which allow companies to put their own software on silicon chips for different uses.'
p8833
aS'It said it no longer sells chips to the U.S. military, unlike its two biggest rivals, Xilinx Inc and Intel Corp\xe2\x80\x99s Altera.'
p8834
aS'Trump said in an executive order that Lattice and Canyon Bridge "shall take all steps necessary to fully and permanently abandon the proposed transaction" within 30 days.'
p8835
aS'Trump\xe2\x80\x99s decision chimes with the views of the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States (CFIUS), which scrutinizes deals for potential national security threats.'
p8836
aS'U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin said in a statement following the decision that "CFIUS and the president assess that the transaction poses a risk to the national security of the United States that cannot be resolved through mitigation".'
p8837
aS'Mnuchin added that the national security risk was related to the transfer of intellectual property, the Chinese government\xe2\x80\x99s role in supporting the deal, the importance of semiconductor supply chain integrity to the U.S. government and the U.S. government\xe2\x80\x99s use of Lattice products.'
p8838
aS'China expressed concern about the decision.'
p8839
aS'"We believe conducting security examinations of investments in sensitive sectors is a country\xe2\x80\x99s legitimate right, but it should not become a tool for advancing protectionism," Chinese Commerce Ministry spokesman Gao Feng told a press briefing on Thursday.'
p8840
aS'Gao said he hoped the United States could view Chinese firms\xe2\x80\x99 acquisitions objectively and provide fair treatment to what was their "normal commercial behavior".'
p8841
aS'Lattice and Canyon Bridge said in a joint statement late on Wednesday they had terminated the proposed deal.'
p8842
aS'Lattice also said it is committed to achieving profitable growth.'
p8843
aS'Canyon Bridge had said in an earlier statement that it was disappointed in the decision, and called the proposed transaction "an excellent deal for Lattice\xe2\x80\x99s shareholders and its employees".'
p8844
aS'The announcement comes at a sensitive time for U.S.-China relations, which are already strained over trade issues and North Korea.'
p8845
aS'The Chinese Communist Party is also preparing to hold its once-every-five-years Congress in October.'
p8846
aS'Trump\xe2\x80\x99s decision ends a prolonged campaign by Canyon Bridge and Lattice to seal the deal.'
p8847
aS'Canyon Bridge and Lattice had spent more than eight months trying in vain to persuade CFIUS to clear the acquisition.'
p8848
aS'Both companies had said the deal did not pose any security risks and Canyon Bridge told CFIUS it would double the number of Lattice\xe2\x80\x99s employees in a bid to make the deal more palatable, according to people familiar with the matter who declined to be identified because details of the regulatory process are confidential.'
p8849
aS'The companies\xe2\x80\x99 decision to appeal directly to Trump was a last-ditch gamble.'
p8850
aS'It was the first such deal to hit Trump\xe2\x80\x99s desk and only the fourth time in three decades that an acquisition was put in front of a president after CFIUS recommended against it.'
p8851
aS'Trump has hewed to the presidential tradition of following the advice of national security officials on deals.'
p8852
aS'The U.S. refusal potentially hurts Canyon Bridge\xe2\x80\x99s ability to acquire other Western semiconductor companies.'
