aS'The investigation in March was described internally as "a top-secret project" and one that Smith was overseeing personally, according to one person with direct knowledge of the matter.'
p9188
aS'The relationship with Mandiant broke down sometime over the next several weeks\xe2\x80\x94a period that would later turn out to be critical in how the breach unfolded.'
p9189
aS'Mandiant warned Equifax that its unpatched systems and misconfigured security policies could indicate major problems, a person familiar with the perspectives of both sides said.'
p9190
aS'For its part, Equifax believed Mandiant had sent an undertrained team without the expertise it expected from a marquee security company.'
p9191
aS'A Mandiant spokesman declined to comment on the March investigation.'
p9192
aS'Although the hackers inside Equifax were able to evade detection for months, once the hack was discovered on July 29, investigators quickly reconstructed their movements down to the individual commands they used.'
p9193
aS"The company's suite of tools included Moloch, which works much like a black box after an airliner crash by\xc2\xa0keeping a record of a network's internal communications and data traffic."
p9194
aS'Using Moloch, investigators\xc2\xa0reconstructed\xc2\xa0every step.'
p9195
aS'Once the hackers found the vulnerability Zheng reported, they installed a simple backdoor known as a web shell.'
p9196
aS"It didn't matter if Equifax fixed the vulnerability after that."
p9197
aS"The hackers had an invisible portal into the company's network."
p9198
aS'The Moloch data\xc2\xa0suggests the initial group of hackers struggled to jump through internal roadblocks like firewalls and security policies, but that changed once the advanced team took over.'
p9199
aS"Those intruders used special tunneling tools to slide around firewalls, analyzing and cracking one database after the next\xe2\x80\x94while stockpiling data on the company's own storage systems."
p9200
aS'Besides amassing data on nearly every American adult, the hackers also sought information on specific people.'
p9201
aS"It's not clear exactly why, but there are at least two possibilities: They were looking for high-net-worth individuals\xc2\xa0to defraud, or they wanted the financial details of people with potential intelligence value."
p9202
aS'Eventually the intruders installed more than 30 web shells, each on a different web address, so they could continue operating in case some were discovered.'
p9203
aS'\xc2\xa0Groups known to exploit web shells most effectively include teams with links to Chinese intelligence, including one nicknamed Shell Crew.'
p9204
aS'Some investigators within Equifax reached the conclusion that they were facing Chinese state hackers relatively quickly after analyzing the Moloch data, according to a person briefed on those discussions.'
p9205
aS'If the Equifax breach was a purely criminal act, one would expect at least some of the stolen data, especially the credit card numbers that were taken, to have showed up for sale on the black market.'
p9206
aS'That hasn\xe2\x80\x99t happened.'
p9207
aS'What\xe2\x80\x99s more, banks are typically asked to shut down all stolen cards if investigators are near certain who is behind a hack.'
p9208
aS'In this case, they still aren\xe2\x80\x99t sure.'
p9209
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s why on Sept. 11, the FBI asked several major banks to monitor the credit card accounts of small batches of consumers\xe2\x80\x94in one case just 20 people\xe2\x80\x94for suspicious activity.'
p9210
aS'Investigators were still looking for anything that could give them insight into the hackers\' identity and motives, according to security experts". This wasn\'t a credit card play," said one person familiar with the investigation.'
p9211
aS'"This was a \'get as much data as you can on every American\xe2\x80\x99 play".'
