aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s been more than a week since I\xe2\x80\x99ve had any word in New York from my 93-year-old father in Puerto Rico.'
p9221
aS'He lives in Coamo, a town in the path of the worst storm to hit the island since 1928.'
p9222
aS'My experience has been shared by millions of Puerto Ricans in the diaspora since Hurricane Maria wreaked its havoc on Sept. 20.'
p9223
aS'The so-called natural disaster wiped out the deteriorating infrastructure of the entire commonwealth, destroying homes and roads, and leaving Puerto Rico without electricity.'
p9224
aS'Estimates are that it will take months to make the grid fully functional again.'
p9225
aS'The loss of communications has meant no news at all from the more remote communities like Coamo, which is also my hometown.'
p9226
aS'This wasn\xe2\x80\x99t just nature\xe2\x80\x99s work.'
p9227
aS'Another type of storm had been pounding the island long before last week.'
p9228
aS'With no real representation in Washington, Puerto Rico has always been subject to the whims of stateside politicians unaccountable to the island\xe2\x80\x99s people.'
p9229
aS'More than half a century ago, tax breaks lured industry from the mainland to Puerto Rico, but in recent decades those advantages were yanked back.'
p9230
aS'That set the stage for vulture hedge funds to swoop into the vacuum, but left hospitals, schools, electrical and communications grids too underfunded and fragile to weather a Category 4 hurricane.'
p9231
aS'The immediate cause of the humanitarian crisis we\xe2\x80\x99re witnessing now was a one-two punch by Hurricanes Irma and Maria.'
p9232
aS'But the seeds for it were sown by a public debt crisis that has made life harder and harder for Puerto Ricans in recent years.'
p9233
aS'The island tried to meet draconian debt payments by making disastrous cuts to public services.'
p9234
aS'Those measures pushed Puerto Ricans out of work and into poverty.'
p9235
aS'By 2015,  , including about   of the island\xe2\x80\x99s children.'
p9236
aS'The governor at the time, Alejandro Garc\xc3\xada Padilla, declared the debt unpayable and began defaulting on debt payments.'
p9237
aS'The cruelly named Promesa law ("promesa" means "promise" in Spanish) passed by Congress last year was supposed to resolve the debt crisis and right Puerto Rico\xe2\x80\x99s economy.'
p9238
aS'But any meaningful recovery for Puerto Rican families remains a distant hope.'
p9239
aS'The commonwealth\xe2\x80\x99s tight budget has made life on the island impossible for hundreds of thousands of families.'
p9240
aS'They migrated to the mainland; in Central Florida, they were arriving daily by the hundreds before hurricane season.'
p9241
aS'Then came Hurricanes Irma and Maria.'
p9242
aS'Immediate needs on the island include search and rescue, getting communications back up and clearing roads to get goods and help to people who need it.'
p9243
aS'Beyond that, though, Puerto Rico needs Congress to help it recover from the devastation wrought by economic strategies that have failed the island for decades.'
p9244
aS'Congress and the Trump administration cannot hide behind the Financial Oversight Board created by Promesa \xe2\x80\x94 a semi-colonial entity that in effect controls Puerto Rico\xe2\x80\x99s future.'
p9245
aS'To undo the damage done by years of neglect and abuse by corporations that strip-mined profits out of Puerto Rico with federal blessing, Congress must act to create conditions for a sustainable economy.'
p9246
aS'That plan must begin with the collapsing health system.'
p9247
aS'Puerto Rico is in urgent need of the   funding that Congress approved in the spring, and additional funds to rebuild a system that is putting some of the country\xe2\x80\x99s sickest, poorest and most vulnerable citizens at risk.'
p9248
aS'On Thursday, the Trump administration said it would temporarily waive the century-old Jones Act, which Puerto Rican officials said was slowing delivery of relief supplies.'
p9249
aS'The act requires ships carrying cargo to the island to be built and owned by Americans, and to make port in the mainland United States before continuing on to Puerto Rico.'
p9250
aS'A temporary waiver will help, but it is not enough; Congress must repeal the act itself, because it has hindered economic growth and stability on the island even in the best of times.'
p9251
aS'In addition, whatever emergency assistance the Federal Emergency Management Agency sends must come with no strings attached.'
p9252
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s time we faced facts about Puerto Rico\xe2\x80\x99s debt: as former Governor Padilla said, it\xe2\x80\x99s unpayable.'
p9253
aS'The only thing Promesa has done for the people of Puerto Rico is put a temporary stay on claims from bondholders and other creditors.'
p9254
aS'Even as he acknowledged the disaster, President Trump reminded people on Monday that the island, "which was already suffering from broken infrastructure and massive debt, is in deep trouble".'
p9255
aS'It would be immoral to insist that before Puerto Ricans can rebuild their homes, hospitals, schools and roads, they must pay back this onerous debt.'
p9256
aS'Instead, repayment must be postponed, maybe even eliminated.'
p9257
aS'The banks that have benefited from the debt must take their own losses and let people come first.'
p9258
aS'Already, the vultures have been circling.'
p9259
aS'Even as Maria hit Puerto Rico, hedge fund creditors were filing motions in court to further their claims to be repaid \xe2\x80\x94 sparing no thought for need for rescue, recovery and rebuilding in the coming months.'
p9260
aS'A good model for recovery and moving forward is the Marshall Plan, which Washington passed into law after World War II to help rebuild the economies of Western Europe, restoring confidence and prosperity for generations.'
p9261
aS'In the past few years, Puerto Ricans like me across the United States have come together to support our families still on the island, and to demand an end to the cuts that have made life harder and harder for our parents, our brothers and sisters.'
p9262
aS'We will send help to them and our communities, but we must also defend them in the States, by resisting any measures from Washington that will make matters worse.'
p9263
aS'As the president of a union that represents thousands of Puerto Ricans along the East Coast \xe2\x80\x94 from Boston to New York to Florida \xe2\x80\x94 I will push our congressional representatives to extend the moratorium on the debt service and create a comprehensive plan to get the island back on its feet.'
p9264
aS'In the past, terrible storms like the one in 1928 set Puerto Rico back.'
p9265
aS'I hope we can use this opportunity to make changes that will leave the island more resilient.'
p9266
aS'As I await news from my family, I think about the long road back to normality ahead of us.'
p9267
aS'And I hope our fellow Americans will stand in solidarity with us and demand lasting relief from the crisis we face today.'
p9268
aS'All we really need, like the tropical forests crippled by the storm, is an opportunity to grow again, in a sustainable and more equitable way.'
