aS'Insurers are counting on real-time technology to help them cut back payouts, from a system warning ships of nearby pirates to an app offering to buy\xc2\xa0sleepy drivers a coffee on the motorway.'
p9616
aS'The lure of products promising to save on claims in a highly competitive market has led to a leap in investment in "insurtech" in Europe to more than $400 million (294 million pounds) in the first half of 2017, from just $50 million a year ago.'
p9617
aS'The aim is to move insurance from a "grudge" purchase, when the only interaction with customers is after something has gone wrong, to a "nudge" product, encouraging safer behaviour.'
p9618
aS'While the idea is not entirely new, the technology is making it more prevalent, prompting warnings from regulators about the risk of discrimination.'
p9619
aS'Insurers say they can navigate those hazards as they explore blockchain - tamper-proof databases shared and updated across a network - "big data", analysing reams of information for trends, as well as the artificial intelligence technology behind driverless cars, drones and voice-recognition software.'
p9620
aS'"The new technologies have the potential to change the game (from compensation to risk mitigation)," said Simon Tottman, head of insurance research, UK & Ireland, for consultants Accenture.'
p9621
aS'The biggest surge of insurtech investment was in Britain, where, despite the vote to leave the European Union, it hit $279 million in the six months to end-June from $9 million a year earlier, analysis by Accenture of data from CB Insights showed.'
p9622
aS'In the rest of Europe, investment jumped to $134 million from $37 million and some insurers are also forming partnerships with insurtech firms.'
p9623
aS'A focus in Britain on analysis of social media to assess the probability of claims has fuelled concerns about data security.'
p9624
aS'British motor insurer Admiral had to abandon plans last year to take data from Facebook to set insurance premiums following objections by the social media firm.'
p9625
aS'The Federation of German Consumer Organisations (VZBV) sees risks from big data in personal insurance outweighing benefits, fearing it will shift insurance from spreading risk collectively to being an arbiter of social norms.'
p9626
aS'New European Union data protection legislation coming into force in 2018 should strengthen consumer rights, according to a discussion paper published by European supervisory authorities in Dec 2016, which warned financial institutions to consider the legal dimensions of processing social media data.'
p9627
aS'European regulators also worry about social exclusion, and are checking whether data is being used in a way that makes insurance too expensive for those regarded as a higher risk.'
p9628
aS'Andrew Brem, chief digital officer at UK insurer Aviva, which is aiming to invest 100 million pounds over the next few years in insurtech start-ups, says the aim is only to promote less risky behaviour.'
p9629
aS'"In our sector, technology can be very powerful in helping people make smarter choices," said Brem, whose company has an insurtech-focused office in a converted garage in London\xe2\x80\x99s so-called Silicon Roundabout area in the east of the city.'
p9630
aS'Health app Tictrac, due to start working with Aviva later this year, tracks exercise, sleep patterns and the weight of employees in corporate healthcare, offering tips and setting challenges to help prevent the onset of costly conditions.'
p9631
aS'"Companies don\xe2\x80\x99t get any access to their employees\xe2\x80\x99 data," said Martin Blinder, Trictrac CEO.'
p9632
aS'"They\xe2\x80\x99re able to see aggregated, anonymised utilisation trends".'
p9633
aS'The largest UK investment this year was in the domestically focused insurer Gryphon, which is awaiting regulatory approval to offer tailored life, critical illness and income protection insurance via financial advisers using cloud-based technology.'
p9634
aS'Telematics - black boxes in cars which enable insurers to check customers\xe2\x80\x99 driving and reward safer habits - have been in use for a while.'
p9635
aS'Anton Ossip, CEO of Discovery Insure, owned by Johannesburg-based financial services firm Discovery Ltd, said accident claims had dropped more than 11 percent since it began using customers\xe2\x80\x99 driving information in pricing in 2011.'
p9636
aS'Kenny Leitch, global connected insurance director at UK insurer RSA said it had paid nearly 2 million pounds in cash rewards to young drivers for safe driving using telematics.'
p9637
aS'Insurtech firms are now looking at how to use telematics in real time to prevent accidents.'
p9638
aS'For example, said Tottman, an app may suggest a coffee at a service station at the insurer\xe2\x80\x99s expense if it detects tiredness in a driver\xe2\x80\x99s voice.'
p9639
aS'Consultancy EY, data security firm Guardtime, Microsoft and ship operator Maersk are building the first blockchain-based marine insurance platform.'
p9640
aS'"The shared ledger can alert a ship in Somali waters that it\xe2\x80\x99s approaching an area where pirates have just hijacked another ship," said Shaun Crawford, global insurance leader at EY.'
p9641
aS'AXA also has a strategic fund investing in insurtech startups and investments by Allianz\xe2\x80\x99s 430 million euro ($513 million) fund include U.S. firm Lemonade, a digital peer-to-peer insurer that uses artificial intelligence and behavioural economics.'
p9642
aS'The U.S. pulled in $4.4 billion in insurtech investment between 2010 and 2016, compared with $1.3 billion in the Asia-Pacific region and $300 million in Europe, according to Accenture\xe2\x80\x99s analysis of CB Insights data.'
p9643
aS'More than half the 100-plus insurers surveyed by  consultants Capgemini said they wanted to partner with insurtech firms, according to its annual World Insurance Report published last week with trade body Efma.'
p9644
aS'Murray Raisbeck, global co-head of fintech at consultants KPMG said some inroads by insurers into technology were still largely a public relations exercise, but insurtech was becoming a "permanent feature" of the market.'
