aS'The Trump administration is unflinching in its misbegotten campaign to protect the coal industry from what has become an obvious and inevitable decline.'
p9662
aS'Eight months in, the administration has already killed, or is in the process of killing, rules that would prevent the dumping of coal mining wastes in streams, impose a temporary moratorium on new mine leases in the West, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions from coal-fired power plants \xe2\x80\x94 one of President Barack Obama\xe2\x80\x99s most important efforts to resist climate change.'
p9663
aS'All of this to prop up an industry whose workers would be best served not by false promises of new mining jobs, but by aggressive programs to retrain them for a changing economy.'
p9664
aS'The latest ritualistic bow from Scott Pruitt, the administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency who has presented himself as an industry savior, was to order last week   of the Obama administration\xe2\x80\x99s tighter controls on lead, mercury, arsenic and other coal plant wastes that threaten human health.'
p9665
aS'Delaying the rule\xe2\x80\x99s effective date to November 2020, Mr. Pruitt said, merely "resets the clock".'
p9666
aS'What it does, rather, is to try to twist the clock back to the day when coal was essentially a monopoly fuel, a day that practical-minded utility executives know is long gone.'
p9667
aS'In fact, these executives are busily shutting down coal-fired plants in favor of more affordable energy sources like natural gas and wind and solar power.'
p9668
aS'"We\xe2\x80\x99re not going to build any more coal plants; that\xe2\x80\x99s not going to happen," Chris Beam, head of Appalachian Power, West Virginia\xe2\x80\x99s largest utility, bluntly told the state last April, despite President Trump\xe2\x80\x99s phantasmagorical campaign promise to resurrect lost jobs for coal miners.'
p9669
aS'No less candid, Lynn Good, the head of Duke Energy, America\xe2\x80\x99s largest utility, defended the closing of 12 coal plants across five years, with more to come, in order to cut the company\xe2\x80\x99s coal-fired energy output by a third: "Our strategy will continue to be to drive carbon out of our business".'
p9670
aS'In February, one of the nation\xe2\x80\x99s biggest coal-fired plants, the Navajo Generating Station in Arizona, set plans to shut down by the end of 2019 \xe2\x80\x94 more than two decades earlier than expected \xe2\x80\x94 in order to turn to alternatives, cut consumer prices and shed the notoriety of being the third-worst carbon polluter in the nation, according to the ratings of the (pre-Trump) E.P.A. While environmental rules have played some role in the closing of coal-fired plants, the main driver is cheaper and abundant natural gas.'
p9671
aS'Coal\xe2\x80\x99s use in power generation has been declining since 2007, and by 2016 coal-fired plants produced only 30 percent of the nation\xe2\x80\x99s total generation, compared with 50 percent in 2003.'
p9672
aS'The trend will continue; an estimated 46-plus coal-fired units will close at 25 electricity plants in 16 states over the next five years,   Institute for Energy Economics and Financial Analysis.'
p9673
aS'In its outlook for 2017, the institute skewered Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s campaign vows, saying, "Promises to create more coal jobs will not be kept \xe2\x80\x94 indeed the industry will continue to cut payrolls".'
p9674
aS'About 60,000 coal industry jobs have been lost since 2011, and three of the four major mining companies have gone bankrupt, according to a new study by Columbia University\xe2\x80\x99s  .'
p9675
aS'Even so, Mr. Trump remains obstinate in his "war on coal" statements and steadfast to his bloated campaign promises to laid-off miners, despite expert opinion, expressed in the study, that lifting vital environmental controls "will not materially improve" the coal industry\xe2\x80\x99s prospects.'
p9676
aS'It is shocking that an administration led and staffed by supposedly shrewd business executives deliberately overlooks the blossoming of profitable and cleaner energy products simply because of Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s hollow showmanship before his campaign base.'
p9677
aS'Until now, the E.P.A. and the environmental safeguards Congress has ordered it to enforce have been crucial to the development of new technologies.'
p9678
aS'To have Mr. Pruitt sully that history with false promises to a fading industry is irresponsible.'
