p9704
aS'\xe2\x80\x94 Senator Mitch McConnell and his minions wasted some $10 million \xe2\x80\x94 and President Trump squandered more of his shrinking political capital \xe2\x80\x94 trying to tell Alabama Republicans whom to choose as their nominee for the Senate.'
p9705
aS'When their placeman, the temporary incumbent Luther Strange, lost by more than nine percentage points on Tuesday to Roy Moore, a former chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court, their ham-handed interventions were exposed as flagrant political malpractice.'
p9706
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a familiar pattern.'
p9707
aS'When Republican Party committees or groups backed by Mitch McConnell tried to dictate choices to Republican voters in Florida in 2010, they got Marco Rubio instead; in Texas in 2012, it was Ted Cruz; in Nebraska in 2014, it was Ben Sasse.'
p9708
aS'Voters in Alabama, like their predecessors, told the Washington bully-boys to stuff it.'
p9709
aS'State parties can choose their own nominees, thank you very much, without orders from a Republican politburo.'
p9710
aS'Mr. Strange was never the front-runner.'
p9711
aS'Smart Alabama analysts had rated Mr. Moore the likely winner from the day qualifying for this special election closed.'
p9712
aS'Local considerations and reputations, not Washington\xe2\x80\x99s feuds, set the parameters.'
p9713
aS'But the McConnell gang\xe2\x80\x99s activities, especially their mendacious and noxious substance and character, made it more likely rather than less that Mr. Moore would emerge as the nominee.'
p9714
aS'The more they polluted the airwaves and local mailboxes with nasty, ludicrous attacks on Mr. Moore (my house received nearly 20 glossy, redundant and tone-deaf mailers in a single week), the more Alabamians were both disgusted by their vile tenor and reminded that Mr. Strange was the choice of the Washington insiders they despise.'
p9715
aS'Alabamians found it insulting to be told by Washingtonians that they should vote for Mr. Strange over Mr. Moore because the latter was "a career politician".'
p9716
aS'Note to Washington: Southerners don\xe2\x80\x99t see judges as politicians, especially when the judge in question twice relinquished his seat not for money but for what many cultural conservatives call principle.'
p9717
aS'Further note: Voters damn sure think that the "career politician" gibe is hypocritical when it is employed on behalf of a longtime Washington lobbyist who was running his fourth political race since 2006.'
p9718
aS'Granted, the Washington gang was particularly worried that the controversial Mr. Moore was more likely than any other Republican to lose to Doug Jones, the Democratic nominee (he is more likely, but not by much), and terrified that he might embarrass them if elected (right again).'
p9719
aS'The last thing they want is a senator who says that the First Amendment doesn\xe2\x80\x99t apply to Muslims because Islam isn\xe2\x80\x99t a real religion, or that homosexuality itself (not just gay marriage) should be "illegal".'
p9720
aS'But if they wanted a nominee other than Mr. Moore, they should have stayed out entirely.'
p9721
aS'Instead, they threatened severe political reprisals to any candidate who would dare challenge Mr. Strange (thus keeping out others more likely to defeat Mr. Moore) and to any consultant who dared work for such challengers.'
p9722
aS'When Representative Mo Brooks, a hard-liner who might have been a formidable opponent for Mr. Moore in a primary runoff, ran anyway, they smeared him by running ads suggesting that Mr. Brooks was soft on the Islamic State.'
p9723
aS'Soft on the Islamic State!'
p9724
aS'No wonder Mr. Brooks provided a key endorsement for Mr. Moore.'
p9725
aS'Mr. Moore always was overwhelmingly likely to beat Mr. Strange head-to-head, for three reasons.'
p9726
aS'First, he was seen as uniquely noble, having twice forfeited his power as chief justice in stands against what was seen (rightly or wrongly) as federal judicial overreach.'
p9727
aS'Second, Mr. Strange was seen as bearing an ineradicable ethical stain, having secured his Senate appointment from the very governor, the disgraced Robert Bentley, who was supposed to be under criminal investigation by Mr. Strange\xe2\x80\x99s office when he was the state\xe2\x80\x99s attorney general.'
p9728
aS'The conflict of interest was blatant, but somehow most national analysts still don\xe2\x80\x99t understand how huge a political factor this was.'
p9729
aS'I know people who have been friendly with Mr. Strange for decades, and who were decidedly unenamored of Mr. Moore, who nonetheless told me they would vote for Mr. Moore out of sheer disgust at Mr. Strange\xe2\x80\x99s machinations.'
p9730
aS'Third, it is axiomatic that in a low-turnout election (such as an off-year, September special election), the candidate with the most enthusiastic followers and best existing organization has an edge over a candidate with appeal that, even if it is theoretically broader, is less intense or personal.'
p9731
aS'Operating through local churches and social media, Mr. Moore\xe2\x80\x99s network of dedicated volunteers and supporters was more formidable than anything Mr. McConnell\xe2\x80\x99s money could buy.'
p9732
aS'Mr. McConnell\xe2\x80\x99s team piled onto Mr. Strange\xe2\x80\x99s back the fourth disadvantage \xe2\x80\x94 the obnoxiously counterproductive campaign tactics I\xe2\x80\x99ve already mentioned \xe2\x80\x94 with the result that Mr. Strange never had a chance.'
p9733
aS'Despite all that, national commentators seemed surprised that even though Mr. McConnell was a detriment to Mr. Strange, Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s repeated expressions of enthusiastic support for the incumbent did not carry the day in this wildly pro-Trump state.'
p9734
aS'The truth is that Mr. Trump was irrelevant.'
p9735
aS'As much as it might appall the political class to admit it, this race was about Alabama, not about Washington.'
p9736
aS'Still, Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s very irrelevance here is instructive.'
p9737
aS'It continues a string of instances in which his endorsement was either useless or even harmful.'
p9738
aS'Last year he endorsed incumbent Representative Renee Ellmers in an intraparty match in North Carolina; she lost.'
p9739
aS'Earlier this year, Republicans just managed to survive scares in supposedly safe Republican seats in Montana, Kansas, South Carolina and Georgia.'
p9740
aS'The lesson here is that when it comes to political clout outside of himself, President Trump is an impotent loser.'
