aS'This longtime but informal Senate practice allows a senator to block the nomination of a judge from his or her home state by refusing to sign off on a blue-colored form.'
p11193
aS'The idea was to give senators, who are presumed to be more familiar with the lawyers and judges in their own states, a meaningful say in the choosing of those judges.'
p11194
aS'It also works as an incentive for moderation in staffing the federal judiciary, which, as the only unelected branch of government, depends on the public trust for its legitimacy.'
p11195
aS'But with Democratic senators now refusing to agree to hearings for two of President Trump\xe2\x80\x99s nominees to the federal appeals courts, Mr. McConnell   that the blue slip "ought to simply be a notification of how you\xe2\x80\x99re going to vote, not the opportunity to blackball".'
p11196
aS'What a difference a few years make.'
p11197
aS'Back in 2009, Mr. McConnell and the entire Republican Senate caucus \xe2\x80\x94 then in the minority \xe2\x80\x94   President Barack Obama to honor all blue slips.'
p11198
aS'The appointment of federal judges is a "shared constitutional responsibility," the Republicans said, warning Mr. Obama that "if we are not consulted on, and approve of, a nominee from our states," the senators intended to prevent that nominee from getting a hearing.'
