aS'They expected the blue-slip policy "to be observed, even-handedly and regardless of party affiliation".'
p11200
aS'Lucky for them, it was.'
p11201
aS'Senator Patrick Leahy, the veteran Vermont Democrat and chairman of the Judiciary Committee at the time, applied the policy without exception, meaning that a single withheld blue slip would torpedo a judicial nomination.'
p11202
aS'Republican senators exploited their blue slips with abandon, and with little or no explanation.'
p11203
aS'One senator blocked a nominee because   the Constitution did not protect an individual right to bear arms \xe2\x80\x94 an accurate description of the uncertainty about the law at the time.'
p11204
aS'Other senators blocked nominees they had previously approved for other courts, or even recommended to the White House themselves.'
p11205
aS'In all, 18 of Mr. Obama\xe2\x80\x99s judicial nominees were scuttled, including six to the Courts of Appeals.'
p11206
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s not counting dozens more vacancies that languished for years without a nominee because senators made it clear they would object to anyone.'
p11207
aS'This abuse of blue slips led many,  , to call for an end to the practice, but Mr. Leahy continued it \xe2\x80\x94 as did Senator Charles Grassley of Iowa, who became chairman of the Judiciary Committee after Republicans won the Senate in 2014.'
p11208
aS'President Trump now has 144 vacancies to fill on the federal bench, many as a direct result of Republican intransigence during the Obama era.'
p11209
aS'So it\xe2\x80\x99s particularly rich, if not surprising, for Republicans to urge its demise.'
p11210
aS'What led them to this?'
