aS'Exactly 230 years ago, on Sept. 17, 1787, a group of men in Philadelphia concluded a summer of sophisticated, impassioned debates about the fate of their fledgling nation.'
p11467
aS'The document that emerged, our Constitution, is often thought of as part of an aristocratic counterrevolution that stands in contrast to the democratic revolution of 1776.'
p11468
aS'But our Constitution has at least one radical feature: It isn\xe2\x80\x99t designed for a society with economic inequality.'
p11469
aS'There are other things the Constitution wasn\xe2\x80\x99t written for, of course.'
p11470
aS'The founders didn\xe2\x80\x99t foresee America becoming a global superpower.'
p11471
aS'They didn\xe2\x80\x99t plan for the internet or nuclear weapons.'
p11472
aS'And they certainly couldn\xe2\x80\x99t have imagined a former reality television star president.'
p11473
aS'Commentators wring their hands over all of these transformations \xe2\x80\x94 though these days, they tend to focus on whether this country\xe2\x80\x99s founding document can survive the current president.'
p11474
aS'But there is a different, and far more stubborn, risk that our country faces \xe2\x80\x94 and which, arguably, led to the TV star turned president in the first place.'
p11475
aS'Our Constitution was not built for a country with so much wealth concentrated at the very top nor for the threats that invariably accompany it: oligarchs and populist demagogues.'
p11476
aS'From the ancient Greeks to the American founders, statesmen and political philosophers were obsessed with the problem of economic inequality.'
p11477
aS'Unequal societies were subject to constant strife \xe2\x80\x94 even revolution.'
p11478
aS'The rich would tyrannize the poor, and the poor would revolt against the rich.'
p11479
aS'The solution was to build economic class right into the structure of government.'
p11480
aS'In England, for example, the structure of government balanced lords and commoners.'
p11481
aS'In ancient Rome, there was the patrician Senate for the wealthy, and the Tribune of the Plebeians for everyone else.'
p11482
aS'We can think of these as class-warfare constitutions: Each class has a share in governing, and a check on the other.'
p11483
aS'Those checks prevent oligarchy on the one hand and a tyranny founded on populist demagogy on the other.'
p11484
aS'What is surprising about the design of our Constitution is that it isn\xe2\x80\x99t a class warfare constitution.'
p11485
aS'Our Constitution doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mandate that only the wealthy can become senators, and we don\xe2\x80\x99t have a tribune of the plebs.'
p11486
aS'Our founding charter doesn\xe2\x80\x99t have structural checks and balances between economic classes: not between rich and poor, and certainly not between corporate interests and ordinary workers.'
p11487
aS'This was a radical change in the history of constitutional government.'
p11488
aS'And it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t an oversight.'
p11489
aS'The founding generation knew how to write class-warfare constitutions \xe2\x80\x94 they even debated such proposals during the summer of 1787.'
p11490
aS'But they ultimately chose a framework for government that didn\xe2\x80\x99t pit class against class.'
p11491
aS'Part of the reason was practical.'
p11492
aS'from the secret debates at the Philadelphia Convention show that the delegates had a hard time agreeing on how they would design such a class-based system.'
p11493
aS'But part of the reason was political: They knew the American people wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t agree to that kind of government.'
p11494
aS'At the time, many Americans believed the new nation would not be afflicted by the problems that accompanied economic inequality because there simply wasn\xe2\x80\x99t much inequality within the political community of white men.'
p11495
aS'Today we tend to emphasize how undemocratic the founding era was when judged by our values \xe2\x80\x94 its exclusion of women, enslavement of African-Americans, violence against Native Americans.'
p11496
aS'But in doing so, we risk missing something important: Many in the founding generation believed America was exceptional because of the extraordinary degree of economic equality within the political community as they defined it.'
p11497
aS'Unlike Europe, America wasn\xe2\x80\x99t bogged down by the legacy of feudalism, nor did it have a hereditary aristocracy.'
p11498
aS'Noah Webster, best known for his dictionary, commented that there were "small inequalities of property," a fact that distinguished America from Europe and the rest of the world.'
p11499
aS'Equality of property, he believed, was crucial for sustaining a republic.'
p11500
aS'During the Constitutional Convention, South Carolinan Charles Pinckney said America had "a greater equality than is to be found among the people of any other country".'
p11501
aS'As long as the new nation could expand west, he thought, it would be possible to have a citizenry of independent yeoman farmers.'
p11502
aS'In a community with economic equality, there was simply no need for constitutional structures to manage the clash between the wealthy and everyone else.'
p11503
aS'The problem, of course, is that economic inequality has been on the rise for at least the last generation.'
p11504
aS'In 1976 the richest 1 percent of Americans took home about 8.5 percent of our national income.'
p11505
aS'Today they take home more than 20 percent.'
p11506
aS'In major sectors of the economy \xe2\x80\x94 banking, airlines, agriculture, pharmaceuticals, telecommunications \xe2\x80\x94 economic power is increasingly concentrated in a small number of companies.'
p11507
aS'While much of the debate has been on the moral or economic consequences of economic inequality, the more fundamental problem is that our constitutional system might not survive in an unequal economy.'
p11508
aS'Campaign contributions, lobbying, the revolving door of industry insiders working in government, interest group influence over regulators and even think tanks \xe2\x80\x94 all of these features of our current political system skew policy making to favor the wealthy and entrenched economic interests.'
p11509
aS'"The rich will strive to establish their dominion and enslave the rest," Gouverneur Morris observed in 1787.'
p11510
aS'"They always did. They always will".'
p11511
aS'An oligarchy \xe2\x80\x94 not a republic \xe2\x80\x94 is the inevitable result.'
p11512
aS'As a republic descends into an oligarchy, the people revolt.'
p11513
aS'Populist revolts are rarely anarchic; they require leadership.'
p11514
aS'Morris predicted that the rich would take advantage of the people\xe2\x80\x99s "passions" and "make these the instruments for oppressing them".'
p11515
aS'The future Broadway sensation Alexander Hamilton put it more clearly: "Of those men who have overturned the liberties of republics, the greatest number have begun their career by paying an obsequious court to the people: commencing demagogues, and ending tyrants".'
p11516
aS'Starting more than a century ago, amid the first Gilded Age, Americans confronted rising inequality, rapid industrial change, a communications and transportation revolution and the emergence of monopolies.'
p11517
aS'Populists and progressives responded by pushing for reforms that would tame the great concentrations of wealth and power that were corrupting government.'
p11518
aS'On the economic side, they invented antitrust laws and public utilities regulation, established an income tax, and fought for minimum wages.'
p11519
aS'On the political side, they passed campaign finance regulations and amended the Constitution so the people would get to elect senators directly.'
p11520
aS'They did these things because they knew that our republican form of government could not survive in an economically unequal society.'
p11521
aS'As Theodore Roosevelt wrote, "There can be no real political democracy unless there is something approaching an economic democracy".'
p11522
aS'For all its resilience and longevity, our Constitution doesn\xe2\x80\x99t have structural checks built into it to prevent oligarchy or populist demagogues.'
p11523
aS'It was written on the assumption that America would remain relatively equal economically.'
p11524
aS'Even the father of the Constitution understood this.'
p11525
aS'Toward the end of his life, Madison worried that the number of Americans who had only the "bare necessities of life" would one day increase.'
p11526
aS'When it did, he , the institutions and laws of the country would need to be adapted, and that task would require "all the wisdom of the wisest patriots".'
p11527
aS'With economic inequality rising and the middle class collapsing, the deep question we must ask today is whether our generation has wise patriots who, like the progressives a century ago, will adapt the institutions and laws of our country \xe2\x80\x94 and save our republic.'
p11528
aS'If you look closely at Brown v.'
p11529
aS'Board of Education, the landmark 1954 school desegregation decision, you\xe2\x80\x99ll see that Brown wasn\xe2\x80\x99t a single case.'
p11530
aS'It was five cases consolidated into one.'
p11531
aS'Briggs v.'
p11532
aS'Elliott, the first of them, took place in my home state, South Carolina.'
p11533
aS'Briggs came about after the Rev.'
p11534
aS'Joseph De Laine organized a group of black parents in Clarendon County to petition for equal educational facilities.'
p11535
aS'The man who stood fast against that request \xe2\x80\x94 the Elliott of Briggs v.'
p11536
aS'Elliott \xe2\x80\x94 was the chairman of the school board, Roderick Miles Elliott.'
p11537
aS'Or as he was known in my family, Uncle Roddy.'
p11538
aS'Although I grew up in South Carolina in the 1960s and \xe2\x80\x9970s, I didn\xe2\x80\x99t learn about Briggs v.'
p11539
aS'Elliott until I was an adult.'
p11540
aS'My father, Uncle Roddy\xe2\x80\x99s nephew, often talked about how shamefully black people were treated in Clarendon County, but he was deeply uncomfortable with the part our family had played.'
p11541
aS'Like most Southerners, he was skilled at avoiding unpleasant conversations, and in the case of Briggs, events conspired to help him.'
p11542
aS'For reasons that remain murky, the Supreme Court case came to be called Brown rather than Briggs, even though Briggs preceded Brown both alphabetically and temporally.'
p11543
aS'So it was Brown v.'
p11544
aS'Board of Education that was memorialized in the history textbooks, and our family name was spared association in the public mind with a racist cause.'
p11545
aS'I won\xe2\x80\x99t pretend I\xe2\x80\x99m not grateful.'
p11546
aS'But the fact that Brown has overshadowed Briggs has also meant that Mr. De Laine, the man who did more than anyone else to bring about school desegregation in South Carolina, has been too often forgotten.'
p11547
aS'This month, with the blessing of his surviving children, Joseph De Laine Jr. and Ophelia De Laine Gona, my cousin Joe Elliott \xe2\x80\x94 Uncle Roddy\xe2\x80\x99s grandson \xe2\x80\x94 submitted a   to the South Carolina legislature on behalf of 21 descendants and relatives of Roderick Miles Elliott (including me), asking the legislature to honor Mr. De Laine with a statue on the grounds of the State House in Columbia.'
p11548
aS'In a just world, the name of Joseph De Laine would already be familiar to South Carolinians.'
p11549
aS'Mr. De Laine was a minister in the African Methodist Episcopal Church and a teacher in the Clarendon County public schools, where his wife, Mattie, also taught.'
p11550
aS'Black schools in Clarendon County in the 1940s were in abysmal condition \xe2\x80\x94 dilapidated, poorly heated and woefully understaffed.'
p11551
aS'Children had to walk miles to attend school, because the school board, led by Uncle Roddy, refused to provide a bus.'
p11552
aS'It provided 30 buses for white children.'
p11553
aS'Mr. De Laine began organizing the parents of Clarendon County in 1947 and kept at it for the next seven years.'
p11554
aS'When the Supreme Court finally vindicated his cause in 1954, it used the dissenting opinion in Briggs as the legal backbone for its decision.'
p11555
aS'In South Carolina, however, Mr. De Laine\xe2\x80\x99s courage and tenacity were punished.'
p11556
aS'Both he and his wife lost their teaching jobs.'
p11557
aS'When an arsonist set fire to the De Laine home, which stood 60 feet outside the city limits of Summerton, S.C., the all-white firefighting squad in Summerton stood by and watched it burn to the ground.'
p11558
aS'Later, Mr. De Laine\xe2\x80\x99s church in Lake City was burned to the ground as well.'
p11559
aS'He was eventually forced to leave the state in 1955 after defending his home against a group of armed attackers.'
p11560
aS'Mr. De Laine died in Charlotte, N.C, in 1974.'
p11561
aS'Congress awarded Mr. De Laine a Gold Medal in 2004 (along with the Briggs petitioners Levi Pearson and Harry and Eliza Briggs), but a comparable gesture of recognition has never been made in South Carolina.'
p11562
aS'The state has no monuments to Mr. De Laine, and apart from a small interstate interchange near Summerton, no roads, bridges or public buildings bear his name.'
p11563
aS'Asking South Carolina to honor Mr. De Laine might seem quixotic.'
p11564
aS'It took decades of protest and the 2015 mass murder at Emanuel A.M.E. Church in Charleston before the Confederate flag came down from the South Carolina State House.'
p11565
aS'Sixty-three years after Brown, schools in Summerton remain de facto segregated, thanks in part to a private academy favored by many white families.'
p11566
aS'Change never comes easily in South Carolina, a state populated by stubborn iconoclasts who can be single-minded in the pursuit of hopeless causes.'
p11567
aS'To which I say: This is exactly why we should honor Mr. De Laine.'
p11568
aS'He showed us how to put that single-mindedness to work for the cause of righteousness.'
p11569
aS'School desegregation is often seen as a tool for justice, and rightly so.'
p11570
aS'But it is an equally powerful tool for friendship, love and solidarity.'
p11571
aS'Most of my generation of South Carolinians had the privilege of attending the integrated schools that Uncle Roddy fought against.'
p11572
aS'As a result, many of us have formed lasting relationships across racial lines in ways that would have been unimaginable to our Southern grandparents, both black and white.'
p11573
aS'If we can somehow make our way together through these dark times, it will be in no small part because of the vision of Joseph De Laine.'
p11574
aS'San Francisco \xe2\x80\x94 Just five years ago, I sued Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers, the venture capital firm in Silicon Valley where I had worked since 2005, for bias and gender discrimination.'
p11575
aS'The lawsuit, which I lost, led to the venture capital world closing ranks against me.'
p11576
aS'I had trouble finding work.'
p11577
aS'People were afraid to support me publicly.'
p11578
aS'I was called a fraud, and greedy, and was accused of being in a fake marriage.'
p11579
aS'Now, over the past year, at least a dozen women have publicly shared their stories of being discriminated against and harassed in tech by their managers, by investors or by board members.'
p11580
aS'Privately, I have heard dozens more.'
p11581
aS'What I also hear, over and over again, is the question, "Has anything changed"?'
p11582
aS'The huge change is that people now acknowledge the problem.'
p11583
