aS'Turkey and Iran both appear eager to enforce that demand and Iraqi troops are already taking part in maneuvers on the Turkish side of the border.'
p12769
aS'These measures will pressure the Kurdish leadership to agree to some of Baghdad\xe2\x80\x99s terms, including the withdrawal of Kurdish forces to within official regional borders and returning to Baghdad oil fields seized starting in 2003.'
p12770
aS'Such measures would satisfy pressure on the Iraqi federal government from its Arab and non-Kurdish communities to check Kurdish expansionism and also help pacify Turkish and Iranian worries about instability.'
p12771
aS'But they will not answer the longer-term questions about Iraqi Kurdish aspirations for independence or the fate of Kirkuk.'
p12772
aS'These questions will need to be answered through tough negotiations between Baghdad and the Kurdish government and the solutions carried out in a way that has a legal basis in Iraq\xe2\x80\x99s Constitution.'
p12773
aS'Before then, the partnership between Baghdad and Erbil, backed by the international coalition, which has led to the near complete defeat of the Islamic State in Iraq, should continue to be the focus for both sides.'
p12774
aS'Other countries, in particular the United States, can also play a positive role.'
p12775
aS'By supporting Baghdad\xe2\x80\x99s efforts to prevent conflict and by encouraging the Kurdish government to be more flexible in its dealing with the federal government, the United States and others can bring the two sides together.'
p12776
aS'This would avoid giving too great a role for Turkey and Iran, who are more concerned about their own interests than Iraq\xe2\x80\x99s future.'
p12777
aS'This may be the only way to reach a peaceful resolution to a tense situation in a region that is not short on violence.'
p12778
aS'JARABULUS, Syria \xe2\x80\x94 Since 2011, the civil war in Syria has killed more than 470,000 people, mostly civilians.'
p12779
aS'Millions of people have been displaced, and nearly five million Syrians have fled, creating the biggest refugee crisis since World War II.'
p12780
aS'By far the greatest burden of receiving Syria\xe2\x80\x99s refugees has fallen not on the United States or on Europe, but on Syria\xe2\x80\x99s neighbors: Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan.'
p12781
aS'Together, these countries are hosting most of the five million Syrians.'
p12782
aS'Each is coping with huge challenges, with different degrees of success.'
p12783
aS'In my visits to those three countries, I\xe2\x80\x98ve been struck by how much more dignity has been accorded to Syrian refugees in Turkey than in Jordan, and especially in Lebanon.'
p12784
aS'Lebanon, with a population of six million, has long given refuge to Palestinians.'
p12785
aS'According to the United Nations Relief and Works Agency, some 450,000 Palestinian refugees are registered in Lebanon, most of them in camps.'
p12786
aS'Even third-generation Palestinians born in Lebanon retain refugee status and live in refugee camps without a pathway to citizenship \xe2\x80\x94 almost 70 years after their ancestors arrived.'
p12787
aS'Lebanese law even excludes refugees from most jobs.'
p12788
aS'To this refugee population, Lebanon has now added an estimated 1.5 million Syrians.'
p12789
aS'Many live in plastic tents in crowded camps with scarce access to clean water, surviving on aid from nongovernmental organizations.'
p12790
aS'Because the Lebanese government doesn\xe2\x80\x99t want the Syrians to become permanent residents as the Palestinians have, the camps are not officially recognized or managed by the United Nations.'
p12791
aS'Resentment toward Syrian refugees has reached alarming levels.'
p12792
aS'With elections next year, some Lebanese politicians are promising to deport the refugees once the war in Syria has been fought to a standstill.'
p12793
aS'For the time being, Syrians receive charity, not dignity.'
p12794
aS'Over the last 10 months, I visited several of these camps.'
p12795
aS'In a camp in the Bekaa Valley, I met 12-year-old Nour and her sister, Aya, outside a bakery.'
p12796
aS'As I stopped to buy sweets to celebrate the end of Ramadan, I asked Nour about her family.'
p12797
aS'She told me that she and Aya had lost everyone.'
p12798
aS'She now lives with her only remaining relative \xe2\x80\x94 an impoverished elderly aunt who has five children of her own.'
p12799
aS'Nour hasn\xe2\x80\x99t been to school since the outbreak of the war.'
p12800
aS'In Lebanon, she spends her days in the street with her sister, begging.'
p12801
aS'Nour and Aya are among thousands of Syrian children who have to roam the streets selling napkins, candies and bottled water.'
p12802
aS'Others work on farms to support themselves and what is left of their families.'
p12803
aS'At the Tal Sarhoun refugee camp, also in the Bekaa Valley, by government decree Syrian and Palestinian children go to United Nations schools only in the afternoon.'
p12804
aS'This policy is a deliberate attempt to segregate refugees from Lebanese children.'
p12805
aS'I saw many boys who, instead of going to school, were playing in the street with toy guns.'
p12806
aS'What future is there for these young people?'
p12807
aS'Jordan has shown a more welcoming attitude toward its 1.3 million Syrian refugees.'
p12808
aS'The largest camp, Zaatari, sits close to the northern border, where it is managed by the Jordanian Ministry of Interior and the office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, and financed by a consortium of international aid agencies.'
p12809
aS'Still, up to 60,000 people are trapped at the Syria-Jordan border.'
p12810
aS'After Jordanian security officials were killed by an Islamic State car bomb in 2016, the government closed down access to another camp, Rukban, and banned border entry to Syrians.'
p12811
aS'That has left Syrians camping in the desert in a no man\xe2\x80\x99s land, an area called "the berm".'
p12812
aS'There, thousands are vulnerable to airstrikes, living in desperate conditions and subsisting on scarce rations.'
p12813
aS'Disease is rife, but the Jordanian authorities have blocked access to aid and medical treatment, designating the area a closed military zone.'
p12814
aS'Amid this suffocating humanitarian crisis, the Trump administration has threatened to cut funding to international aid agencies that are assisting Syrian refugees.'
p12815
aS'As the United States slouches away from its global leadership role, regional powers like Turkey are stepping in to fill the vacuum.'
p12816
aS'Turkey and its 80 million people have welcomed more than three million Syrian refugees.'
p12817
aS'"Syrian refugees are not a problem to solve," the head of the Turkish emergency relief effort told me.'
p12818
aS'"They are a reality to manage".'
p12819
aS'The Turkish city of Gaziantep sets an example in treating refugees humanely.'
p12820
aS'A beautiful city on the Syrian-Turkish border, Gaziantep is said to house 600,000 Syrians, approximately 40,000 of which live in the city\xe2\x80\x99s five camps, which are administered by Turkey\xe2\x80\x99s Disaster and Emergency Management Presidency.'
p12821
aS'The rest \xe2\x80\x94 the vast majority of them \xe2\x80\x94 live in the city itself.'
p12822
aS'Refugees are allowed to work and have access to free health care and schools, and the government has repeatedly committed to creating a pathway to Turkish citizenship.'
p12823
aS'Gaziantep\xe2\x80\x99s mayor since 2014, Fatma Sahin, has made the safeguarding of refugee rights a signature policy.'
p12824
aS'Her city has become a global model on how to embrace the survivors of a war.'
p12825
aS'I accompanied Ms. Sahin to see some makeshift homes in the city\xe2\x80\x99s camps, where the Syrian refugees greeted us as though we were long-lost relatives.'
p12826
aS'It was inspiring to see hope alive for an otherwise humiliated people.'
p12827
aS'Turkey\xe2\x80\x99s refugee policy does not stop at its border.'
p12828
aS'I visited Jarabulus in Syria, a town liberated from Islamic State control last year by the Turkish military.'
p12829
aS'While Ankara\xe2\x80\x99s motives are many, one concrete result is a reduction in the flow of refugees across the border and the possibility that many refugees can return to their homes.'
p12830
aS'In place of the Islamic State\xe2\x80\x99s summary justice and public beheadings, there is now a hospital with a maternity ward.'
p12831
aS'The schools are being rebuilt, and the city has formed a new local council.'
p12832
aS'Though facing difficulties of its own \xe2\x80\x94 the attempted military coup was little more than a year ago \xe2\x80\x94 Turkey has managed to pursue a far more humane refugee policy than its neighbors.'
p12833
aS'Europe has been happy to let Turkey play this leading role in refugee relief.'
p12834
aS'President Recep Tayyip Erdogan\xe2\x80\x99s government struck a deal with the European Union in which Europe is funding Turkey\xe2\x80\x99s refugee program in exchange for preventing migrants from reaching European shores.'
p12835
aS'Turkey\xe2\x80\x99s response to the refugee crisis has considerably enhanced the regional prestige and power of its president.'
p12836
aS'Mr. Erdogan has long cherished a dream of building a new Ottoman Empire, with Ankara as its capital.'
p12837
aS'Turkey\xe2\x80\x99s robust refugee policy has materially advanced that ambition.'
p12838
aS'Meanwhile, the war in Syria is winding down and Syrians are starting to go home.'
p12839
aS'The International Organization for Migration   that 600,000 Syrians have returned home this year.'
p12840
aS'But this process remains reversible.'
p12841
aS'President Bashar al-Assad\xe2\x80\x99s merciless violence may yet produce another wave of refugees, since he plans to retake, among other contested areas, the city of Idlib.'
p12842
aS'Last April, he again used sarin gas on civilians there; his next assault could be just as deadly.'
p12843
aS'Even if some form of interim agreement is reached, no one yet has proposed a satisfactory plan for the safety of Syrian refugees \xe2\x80\x94 including those who return and those who cannot.'
p12844
aS'With the aid of his foreign allies, Iran and Russia, Mr. Assad will be   of this grisly conflict, and he plans to stay in power.'
p12845
aS'For many refugees, even after the war concludes, a return to Assad-controlled Syria is a death sentence.'
p12846
aS'Given the regime\xe2\x80\x99s atrocities, it seems certain that Syria\xe2\x80\x99s neighbors will host large refugee populations for years, and possibly generations, to come.'
p12847
aS'Most Syrians I spoke to during my travels in the refugee camps told me of a common culture of abuse by their host country\xe2\x80\x99s military and police.'
p12848
aS'In Lebanon especially, generations of Syrians \xe2\x80\x94 broken women, men and children \xe2\x80\x94 may be forced to live under a state with little means or patience to deal with the long-term reality of their presence.'
p12849
aS'People forced to flee from their homes and then rejected will be ripe for radicalization unless the world turns its attention to helping them rebuild their lives, with real homes, some honor and at least a little hope.'
