aS'The first time I forayed into online dating, I let my wheelchair show just a little in my photos.'
p12851
aS'The good guys, I hoped, would be so taken by my clever profile and witty banter that they\xe2\x80\x99d be able to look beyond my disability, if they even noticed it at all.'
p12852
aS'I eagerly began swiping, quickly matching with an attractive man whose profile picture showed him sporting an enormous iguana on his shoulder.'
p12853
aS'Thinking that would make for an easy conversation starter, I messaged him.'
p12854
aS'A few minutes later, he replied, but instead of responding to my reptilian inquiry, he asked, "Are you in a wheelchair"?'
p12855
aS'I kept my answer simple and told him that yes, I do use a wheelchair, but I was much more interested in the back story of the iguana.'
p12856
aS'Unfortunately, he wasn\xe2\x80\x99t interested at all, messaging back only to say: "Sorry. The wheelchair\xe2\x80\x99s a deal-breaker for me".'
p12857
aS'His blunt reply stung, but the feeling was nothing new.'
p12858
aS'Because I was born with my disability \xe2\x80\x94 Larsen syndrome, a genetic joint and muscle disorder \xe2\x80\x94 I\xe2\x80\x99d already gathered a pile of romantic rejections seemingly big enough to fill an Olympic swimming pool by the time I downloaded Tinder.'
p12859
aS'This particular rejection, however, unleashed a wave of panic within me.'
p12860
aS'A few months before my initial swipes, I\xe2\x80\x99d gone through a messy breakup with a man I dated for over two years.'
p12861
aS'I truly believed he was the person I\xe2\x80\x99d marry, and that I\xe2\x80\x99d never have to worry about rejection again.'
p12862
aS'When I found myself newly single, I turned to online dating in the hopes of easing my fears that no one else would ever accept me as I am, that lightning doesn\xe2\x80\x99t strike twice.'
p12863
aS'Not one to be deterred, I persevered, downloading every possible dating app and creating accounts on various dating sites.'
p12864
aS'But I became skittish about revealing my disability, because in an already shallow dating culture, I believed my wheelchair would cause most men to write me off without a second thought.'
p12865
aS'So I decided to hide my disability completely.'
p12866
aS'I cropped my wheelchair out of my photos.'
p12867
aS'I eliminated any mention of it in my profiles.'
p12868
aS'In this virtual world, I could pretend my disability didn\xe2\x80\x99t exist.'
p12869
aS'I kept up with this facade for a while, messaging matches who were none the wiser.'
p12870
aS'Once I thought I\xe2\x80\x99d spoken with a guy long enough to establish his interest, I\xe2\x80\x99d choose a moment to strike, telling him about my disability.'
p12871
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99d send a long-winded explanation divulging my wheelchair use, reminding him that it didn\xe2\x80\x99t make me any less of person and ending with reassurance that he could ask me questions, should he have any.'
p12872
aS'After dropping the "wheelchair bomb," I\xe2\x80\x99d have to brace myself for their reactions, which were always a mixed bag, often ranging from indifference to ghosting.'
p12873
aS'Occasionally, I\xe2\x80\x99d receive an accepting response.'
p12874
aS'One man that I connected with on Coffee Meets Bagel was incredibly apologetic when I first told him about my wheelchair, as though it was the most tragic thing he\xe2\x80\x99d ever heard.'
p12875
aS'I shut that down by explaining that my disability is part of who I am and it\xe2\x80\x99s nothing to be sorry for.'
p12876
aS'I ended up going on one date with him, and then another.'
p12877
aS'For the second date, my bagel suggested a painting night (a social event that involves paintbrushes, canvases, acrylics and, usually, wine) since I\xe2\x80\x99d told him how much I enjoy them.'
p12878
aS'He found a Groupon and I researched a location, picking out a restaurant in New York City that was supposed to be wheelchair accessible.'
p12879
aS'As it turned out, the restaurant was accessible, but the painting class was happening in a room upstairs.'
p12880
aS'So, we spent our entire date sitting directly below the painters, eating dinner and making strained conversation with wine-fueled laughter and painting instruction in the background.'
p12881
aS'I was mortified.'
p12882
aS'Following that disaster, I promised my date I\xe2\x80\x99d get his money back.'
p12883
aS'As soon as the company refunded our tickets, I never heard from him again.'
p12884
aS'It was painful to realize that the hard part isn\xe2\x80\x99t over once someone learns that I\xe2\x80\x99m disabled.'
p12885
aS'Going on dates with me can be a crash course on disability, and I recognize that\xe2\x80\x99s not always easy for non-disabled people to process.'
p12886
aS'But I wasn\xe2\x80\x99t helping the situation by keeping the existence of my disability concealed, springing it upon people only when I thought it felt right.'
p12887
aS'In retrospect, this served only to contribute to the stigma I usually work so hard to fight.'
p12888
aS'I felt like a hypocrite.'
p12889
aS'In every other area of my life, my disability is front and center.'
p12890
aS'I write and speak endlessly about being a proud, unapologetic disabled woman.'
p12891
aS'It is part of my identity, shaping everything I do and everything I value.'
p12892
aS'But in the online dating world, my disability was my secret shame.'
p12893
aS'So I decided it was time for a change.'
p12894
aS'I started gradually, making references to my disability throughout my profile, then adding photos in which my wheelchair is clearly visible.'
p12895
aS'I tried to keep things light and humorous.'
p12896
aS'For instance, OKCupid asks users to list six things they can\xe2\x80\x99t live without; one of mine is "the invention of the wheel".'
p12897
aS'Still, I found myself having to make sure that potential matches had actually picked up on the trail of clues I\xe2\x80\x99d left.'
p12898
aS'I grew tired of feeling like I needed to deceive men into being interested because society instilled in me that my disability makes me undesirable.'
p12899
aS'Finally, I took the leap I\xe2\x80\x99d been so afraid to make, opening up about disability to strangers whom I hoped would appreciate my honesty and perhaps send me a message.'
p12900
aS'My disability is part of my identity and I\xe2\x80\x99m a loud, proud disability rights activist, but there is so much more that defines me (you know, like the stuff I\xe2\x80\x99ve got in my profile).'
p12901
aS'I realize some people are hesitant to date a human who experiences the world sitting down.'
p12902
aS'But I\xe2\x80\x99d like to think you\xe2\x80\x99ll keep reading and dive a little deeper.'
p12903
aS'Prominently in my profile, I wrote: "I\xe2\x80\x99d like to be very upfront about the fact that I use a wheelchair. And you\xe2\x80\x99re welcome to ask questions, should you have any".'
p12904
aS'Once I added that paragraph, I felt liberated, relieved that anyone I spoke to would have a clearer picture of me.'
p12905
aS'There have been plenty of matches that haven\xe2\x80\x99t worked out, and whether that\xe2\x80\x99s actually because of my disability, I\xe2\x80\x99ll never know.'
p12906
aS'But I had a nearly yearlong relationship with a man I met through OKCupid, so I know it\xe2\x80\x99s possible for lightning to strike again.'
p12907
aS'My dating life remains a comedy of errors, and I still struggle every day with the feeling that my disability means I won\xe2\x80\x99t find love, but at least I\xe2\x80\x99m being true to myself.'
p12908
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m putting myself out there \xe2\x80\x94 my whole self \xe2\x80\x94 and it feels good to be proud of who I am.'
p12909
aS'Ten years on from the financial crisis, it\xe2\x80\x99s hard not to have a sense of d\xc3\xa9j\xc3\xa0 vu.'
p12910
aS'Financial scandal and wrangles over financial rule-making still dominate the headlines.'
p12911
aS'The cyberhacking at Equifax compromised personal records for half of the adult population of the United States.'
p12912
aS'At SoFi, a one-time fintech darling that offers student loans and other types of credit, the chief executive was forced to resign after revelations of sexual harassment and risky lending practices (the company misled investors about its finances and put inexperienced customer service representatives in charge of credit evaluations).'
p12913
aS'The White House and Republicans in Congress in the meantime are trying to roll back hard-won banking regulations in the Dodd-Frank financial oversight law.'
p12914
aS'All of it brings to mind an acronym familiar to financial writers like myself \xe2\x80\x94 BOB, or "bored of banking".'
p12915
aS'Even some of us that cover the markets for a living can find ourselves BOB.'
p12916
aS'Over the last 10 years, there has been so much financial scandal, so many battles between regulators and financiers, and so much complexity (more liquidity and less leverage with your tier one capital, anyone?'
p12917
aS') that a large swath of the public has become numb to the debate about how to make our financial system safer.'
p12918
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s a dangerous problem, because despite all of the wrangling and rule making, there\xe2\x80\x99s a core truth about our financial system that we have yet to comprehend fully: It isn\xe2\x80\x99t serving us, we\xe2\x80\x99re serving it.'
p12919
aS'Adam Smith, the father of modern capitalism, envisioned financial services (and I stress the word "service") as an industry that didn\xe2\x80\x99t exist as an end in itself, but rather as a helpmeet to other types of business.'
p12920
aS'Yet lending to Main Street is now a minority of what the largest banks in the country do.'
p12921
aS'In the 1970s, most of their financial flows, which of course come directly from our savings, would have been funneled into new business investment.'
p12922
aS'Today, only about 15 percent of the money coming out of the largest financial institutions goes to that purpose.'
p12923
aS'The rest exists in a closed loop of trading; institutions facilitate and engage in the buying and selling of stocks, bonds, real estate and other assets that mainly enriches the 20 percent of the population that owns 80 percent of that asset base.'
p12924
aS'This doesn\xe2\x80\x99t help growth, but it does fuel the wealth gap.'
p12925
aS'This fundamental shift in the business model of finance is what we should really be talking about \xe2\x80\x94 rather than the technocratic details of liquidity ratios or capital levels or even how to punish specific banking misdeeds.'
p12926
aS'The big problem is that our banking system would no longer be recognizable to Adam Smith, who believed that for markets to work, all players must have equal access to information, transparent prices and a shared moral framework.'
p12927
aS'Good luck with that today.'
p12928
aS'While the largest banks can correctly claim that they have offloaded risky assets and bolstered the amount of cash on their balance sheets over the last decade, their business model has become fundamentally disconnected from the very people and entities it was designed to serve.'
p12929
aS'Small community banks, which make up only 13 percent of all banking assets, do nearly half of all lending to small businesses.'
p12930
aS'Big banks are about deal making.'
p12931
aS'They serve mostly themselves, existing as the middle of the hourglass that is our economy, charging whatever rent they like for others to pass through.'
p12932
aS'(Finance is one of the few industries in which fees have gone up as the sector as a whole has grown.'
p12933
aS') The financial industry, dominated by the biggest banks, provides only 4 percent of all jobs in the country, yet takes about a quarter of the corporate profit pie.'
p12934
aS'Perhaps that\xe2\x80\x99s why companies of all stripes try to copy its model.'
p12935
aS'Nonfinancial firms as a whole now get five times the revenue from purely financial activities as they did in the 1980s.'
p12936
aS'Stock buybacks artificially drive up the price of corporate shares, enriching the C-suite.'
p12937
aS'Airlines can make more hedging oil prices than selling coach seats.'
p12938
aS'Drug companies spend as much time tax optimizing as they do worrying about which new compound to research.'
p12939
aS'The largest Silicon Valley firms now use a good chunk of their spare cash to underwrite bond offerings the same way Goldman Sachs might.'
p12940
aS'The blending of technology and finance has reached an apex with the creation of firms like SoFi, which put the same old models on big data steroids.'
p12941
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s an area we\xe2\x80\x99ll likely hear much more about.'
p12942
aS'A couple of weeks ago, at the Senate Banking Committee hearings on fintech, lawmakers once again struggled with how to think about these latest lending crises.'
p12943
aS'But it\xe2\x80\x99s not data or privacy or algorithms that are the fundamental issue with our financial system.'
p12944
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s the fact that the system itself has lost its core purpose.'
p12945
aS'Finance has become the tail that wags the dog.'
p12946
aS'Until we start talking about how to create a financial system that really serves society, rather than just trying to stay ahead of the misdeeds of one that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t, we\xe2\x80\x99ll struggle in vain to bridge the gap between Wall Street and Main Street.'
p12947
aS'The former C.I.A. officer Valerie Plame Wilson made news with her Twitter account last week when, on the first day of Rosh Hashana, she shared an article that said, "America\xe2\x80\x99s Jews are driving America\xe2\x80\x99s wars: Shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t they recuse themselves when dealing with the Middle East"?'
p12948
aS'The article, which appeared on a fringe website, said that Jewish neoconservatives were pushing for a war with Iran.'
p12949
aS'Ms. Wilson, whose identity as a covert operative was leaked in 2003 by members of the George W. Bush administration nettled by the opposition of her husband, Ambassador Joseph Wilson, to the Iraq war, repeated the well-worn narrative that Jewish neoconservatives promoted the invasion of Iraq \xe2\x80\x94 and are beating the drum for a conflict with Iran.'
p12950
aS'Of course, most Jews are not neoconservatives, and most neoconservatives are not Jewish.'
p12951
aS'In any case, it was two influential non-Jews, Vice President Dick Cheney and Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, who played the central role with President Bush in deciding to invade Iraq in 2003.'
p12952
aS'Ignoring the old saying about when you are in a hole you should stop digging, Ms. Wilson made some excuses and then mentioned that she is of Jewish descent.'
p12953
aS'Finally, she apologized.'
p12954
aS'I have little interest in piling on Ms. Wilson.'
p12955
aS'But the whole affair brought back some memories about how Jews were perceived within the national security apparatus for a long time.'
p12956
aS'When I began working in the Pentagon during President Jimmy Carter\xe2\x80\x99s administration, there was an unspoken but unmistakable assumption: If you were Jewish, you could not work on the Middle East because you would be biased.'
p12957
aS'However, if you knew about the Middle East because you came from a missionary family or from the oil industry, you were an expert.'
p12958
aS'Never mind that having such a background might shape a particular view of the region, the United States\xe2\x80\x99 interests in it, or Israel.'
p12959
aS'People with these backgrounds were perceived to be unbiased, while Jews could not be objective and would be partial to Israel to the exclusion of American interests.'
p12960
aS'Sometimes, I would find this view expressed subtly.'
p12961
aS'Other times it would be overt, including well after Secretary of State George Shultz tried to change the culture of the State Department during the early years of the Reagan\xe2\x80\x99 administration.'
p12962
aS'For Mr. Shultz, being Jewish was no longer a disqualification from working on Arab-Israeli issues.'
p12963
aS'He was more interested in your knowledge than your identity.'
p12964
aS'He made me, someone who is Jewish and was working on the National Security Council staff at the time, a member of the small team working with him on Arab-Israeli diplomacy.'
p12965
aS'( , who is also Jewish and a career Foreign Service Officer, was on that team as well.'
p12966
aS') When James Baker became secretary of state in 1989, he continued to help remove suspicions about Jews from the national security establishment.'
p12967
aS'And yet, I remember well the time in 1990, when I was the head of the State Department\xe2\x80\x99s policy planning staff, I was visited by a diplomatic security investigator who was doing a background check on someone who had listed me as a reference.'
p12968
aS'This person was being considered for a senior position in the George H. W. Bush administration, not one directly involved with the Middle East.'
p12969
aS'At one point, the investigator asked me a question that is routine in these background checks: Was this person loyal to the United States?'
p12970
aS'I answered yes, without a doubt.'
p12971
