aS'This week the F.B.I. released its   of crime in the United States, and the picture it paints is troubling.'
p13252
aS'In 2016, there were 17,250 homicides, an increase of more than 8.5 percent from the previous year.'
p13253
aS'This comes on the heels of a 12 percent rise in 2015, bringing the total increase over two years to nearly 22 percent \xe2\x80\x94 the largest two-year increase in homicide in 25 years.'
p13254
aS'Violent crime \xe2\x80\x94 which includes rapes, robberies and assaults, in addition to homicides \xe2\x80\x94 is also up, but less so, rising 4 percent, after a 4 percent increase in 2015.'
p13255
aS'What to make of this two-year spike in death and violence is unclear, but you can be certain of this: Partisans on all sides will seek to spin this situation to their advantage.'
p13256
aS'And that\xe2\x80\x99s a problem that stunts productive conversation about solutions.'
p13257
aS'Criminal justice reformers will worry that fear of violent crime could slow the momentum of their movement.'
p13258
aS'As a result, they\xe2\x80\x99ll play down the data that says it\xe2\x80\x99s increasing.'
p13259
aS'They\xe2\x80\x99ll say that it\xe2\x80\x99s too soon to call this a trend, that a few neighborhoods in a few cities are driving the numbers, and remind us that overall rates of violence remain near historical lows.'
p13260
aS'Opponents of true reform, including President Trump and Attorney General Jeff Sessions, will do far worse.'
p13261
aS'They will likely use the latest numbers to push the culture-war-fueling narrative about "American carnage" that Mr. Trump described in his Inaugural Address.'
p13262
aS'And then nothing will change.'
p13263
aS'When it comes to how the country deals with crime, impasse and stalemate will win the day.'
p13264
aS'This is not new: Progressives consistently argue that crime is simply the result of socioeconomic root causes such as poverty, unemployment, and poor education.'
p13265
aS'But the fact that crime rates declined during the Great Depression and remained low during the Great Recession indicate that\xe2\x80\x99s not the case \xe2\x80\x94 in reality, crime rates often rise and fall independently of such measures.'
p13266
aS'Conservatives often assert that crime is a matter of values, even though   that most people living in dangerous neighborhoods despise the violence they see in their communities.'
p13267
aS'For years, some scholars claimed that mass incarceration was caused by the war on drugs, but  , not drugs, that pushed our incarceration rates sky high.'
p13268
aS'Law-and-order relics link drug use and violence.'
p13269
aS'But today\xe2\x80\x99s drug epidemic, the opioid crisis, took hold years before the rise in violent crime and has few proven connections with violence to date.'
p13270
aS'Many argue that guns are the crux of that problem, so they push for legal restrictions on them.'
p13271
aS'Most gun crimes, however, are perpetrated with weapons that are   under the laws on the books today.'
p13272
aS'Others insist that guns are the solution, as they could allow law-abiding people to protect themselves from crime \xe2\x80\x94 even though  , and that households with guns are more, not less, likely to suffer gun injuries.'
p13273
aS'We need a new national dialogue on crime, one that is less about ideology and more about evidence.'
p13274
aS'The current conversation oversimplifies complex issues, emphasizes blame over responsibility, and encourages deadlock instead of progress.'
p13275
aS'We need to move from argument winning to problem solving, recognizing that all these issues are related to one another, and especially to the violence that needlessly claims so many lives.'
p13276
aS'The conventional wisdom tells us if we want to reduce violent crime, we should look elsewhere: to poverty, culture, drugs or guns.'
p13277
aS'Decades of data says otherwise: When a colleague and I  , we learned that to control violence, one must account for it directly by focusing on the small numbers of places, people and behaviors that disproportionately drive the problem.'
p13278
aS'The best approach is to tackle the hardest cases with a combination of empathy and resolve, offering assistance if it will be accepted but also accountability for brutal behavior.'
p13279
aS'Here\xe2\x80\x99s a proven approach that deserves more support: Mr. Kennedy\xe2\x80\x99s   supports local efforts to reduce violence, minimize incarceration, and improve police-community relationships.'
p13280
aS'They\xe2\x80\x99ll double down on outdated tough-on-crime strategies like aggressive prosecutions, mandatory minimum sentencing and drug education and follow a strategy that my colleague David Kennedy, a criminal justice researcher and director of the National Network for Safe Communities, recently called a " . Civic, community and criminal justice leaders confront criminals with a simple message: "The killing must end now.'
