aS'In October 2007, New York University announced an ambitious plan to open a "portal" campus in Abu Dhabi, in the United Arab Emirates.'
p13288
aS'John Sexton, N.Y.U.\xe2\x80\x99s president at the time and the project\xe2\x80\x99s champion, promised that the new branch would adhere to the same practices as the main campus in New York, "including our standards of academic freedom".'
p13289
aS'Ten years later, Mr. Sexton\xe2\x80\x99s promise of academic freedom has proved to be largely worthless.'
p13290
aS'I am an American citizen and a tenured professor at N.Y.U.\xe2\x80\x99s main campus, and I was scheduled to teach a journalism class this fall in Abu Dhabi.'
p13291
aS'But a few weeks before the semester started, an N.Y.U. administrator told me that the United Arab Emirates government had denied me the security clearance necessary for anyone teaching there to get a work visa.'
p13292
aS'The university appealed; the Emirati security officials rejected the appeal.'
p13293
aS'Emirati officials did not give N.Y.U. a reason for denying my application.'
p13294
aS'They rarely do.'
p13295
aS'It is usually easy for American citizens to get a work visa for the U.A.E. Why was I denied?'
p13296
aS'I am also a Shiite Muslim born in Lebanon.'
p13297
aS'The U.A.E., like Saudi Arabia and other Sunni Arab states, are worried about Iran\xe2\x80\x99s regional ascendance and its influence over Syria, Iraq, Lebanon and Yemen.'
p13298
aS'This anxiety fuels a fear that virtually any Shiite in the region could pose a security threat \xe2\x80\x94 and could be linked to Iran or its allies.'
p13299
aS'The U.A.E.\xe2\x80\x99s security clearance forms require applicants to list religion and sect, and N.Y.U.\xe2\x80\x99s own written instructions specify that its employees cannot leave those fields blank.'
p13300
aS'University officials recently told me that they\xe2\x80\x99re still working to reverse my security clearance denial.'
p13301
aS'But based on my past experience with the Abu Dhabi project, I have little hope.'
p13302
aS'The signs of religious discrimination were already there in 2012 and 2013, when I taught a monthlong journalism class at the Abu Dhabi campus.'
p13303
aS'N.Y.U. administrators had told me they were worried that I would be denied a security clearance because of my Shiite origins, and they twice held back on submitting my application.'
p13304
aS'They found a way around it by sending me on a tourist visa and describing me as a "consultant".'
p13305
aS'My name was not listed as an instructor on the public course material; I taught the class with my then wife, who, as an American citizen of European ancestry, didn\xe2\x80\x99t have any problems.'
p13306
aS'For two years, various university administrators promised to resolve my case.'
p13307
aS'But the process always stalled, and I was told it was out of their hands.'
p13308
aS'I will probably never know exactly what happened, but I suspect that N.Y.U. administrators in Abu Dhabi did not want to expend limited political capital with their Emirati partners on my case, or the "Shiite problem" in general.'
p13309
aS'The government of Abu Dhabi, whose security apparatus denied my security clearance most likely for sectarian reasons, has funded the planning and construction of the N.Y.U. campus and its operational expenses.'
p13310
aS'At least one other tenured N.Y.U. professor, also a United States citizen of Shiite origin, was recently denied a security clearance to teach at the Abu Dhabi campus.'
p13311
aS'This is precisely what the university\xe2\x80\x99s leadership promised would not happen when it made the deal to open a branch in the capital of an authoritarian state.'
p13312
aS'The university started its partnership with Abu Dhabi at a time when \xe2\x80\x94 awash in record oil revenues in the mid-2000s \xe2\x80\x94 the emirate\xe2\x80\x99s leaders, especially the crown prince and de facto ruler, Mohammed bin Zayed, had set out to buy social and cultural legitimacy.'
p13313
aS'Abu Dhabi funded literary festivals and prizes, translation projects and branches of pre-eminent museums and universities.'
p13314
aS'But the Arab Spring uprisings rattled the U.A.E. leaders\xe2\x80\x99 confidence in their own ability to stay in power, and a repressive turn prioritizing security over cultural capital followed.'
p13315
aS'In March 2011, as the popular revolts spread through the region, more than 100 activists in the U.A.E. signed a   calling for direct elections and reform of the country\xe2\x80\x99s toothless Parliament.'
p13316
aS'Many of those who signed the document were prosecuted, stripped of their citizenship or subsequently deported.'
p13317
aS'Academics also came under assault.'
p13318
aS'In the summer of 2012, Matt Duffy, a journalism professor at Zayed University in Abu Dhabi, was abruptly   and forced to leave the U.A.E. after he criticized media restrictions in the country.'
p13319
aS'In March 2015, Andrew Ross, an N.Y.U. professor who specializes in labor issues, was   from traveling to Abu Dhabi for unspecified security reasons.'
p13320
aS'Mr. Ross, who was an outspoken critic of the university\xe2\x80\x99s Abu Dhabi project and especially the abuse of migrant laborers in the emirates, had planned to spend his spring break researching labor conditions.'
p13321
aS'The university\xe2\x80\x99s response was tepid and cowardly.'
p13322
aS'A spokesman argued that "it is the government that controls visa and immigration policy, and not the university".'
p13323
aS'The university and other Western intellectual and cultural institutions, including the Sorbonne and the Louvre and Guggenheim museums, that made deals to open branches in Abu Dhabi have failed to adjust to the new reality: A more repressive security apparatus was shaping the priorities of their local partner and benefactor.'
p13324
aS'It is ironic that I supported the Abu Dhabi project when it started, and I wanted it to succeed, despite the limitations.'
p13325
aS'I still think the project has merits: The students being recruited to the campus \xe2\x80\x94 representing over 100 nationalities, and many receiving full scholarships underwritten by Abu Dhabi \xe2\x80\x94 are exceptional.'
p13326
aS'When N.Y.U.\xe2\x80\x99s leadership first announced the project, some students, faculty and trustees were worried that the U.A.E. would deny entry to Jews, gays and other groups that the Gulf leadership might find objectionable.'
p13327
aS'But those apprehensions were based on an outdated understanding of the Gulf states and their fears.'
p13328
aS'By the time the project was underway, Abu Dhabi considered Iran\xe2\x80\x99s regional influence to be the greatest threat to its security.'
p13329
aS'In the view of Gulf leaders, the Iran danger lurks everywhere, and Arab and Persian Shiites alike (even American citizens) are potential fifth columnists, who can infiltrate their societies to advance Iran\xe2\x80\x99s interests.'
p13330
aS'N.Y.U. officials have provided very few details on their deal with Abu Dhabi, admitting only that the emirate   the university an initial $50 million grant \xe2\x80\x94 a good-will gift negotiated by Mr. Sexton.'
p13331
aS'N.Y.U. administrators provided data to a faculty committee showing that from 2009 to 2016, the Abu Dhabi authorities approved 97 percent of visa applications by faculty, students and staff.'
p13332
aS'The data show that 10 faculty applications, out of 863, were rejected.'
p13333
aS'If N.Y.U. continues to accept Abu Dhabi\xe2\x80\x99s largess, it needs to acknowledge the limitations that the emirate\xe2\x80\x99s security and foreign policies impose on academic freedom.'
p13334
aS'At the very least, the university should admit that it has bought into a political system that actively discriminates against members of a religious minority because of an overwhelming fear of Iran and hatred of Shiites.'
p13335
aS'This is far from the free movement of people and ideas to which N.Y.U.\xe2\x80\x99s leaders claim to aspire.'
