aS'One spring afternoon, Samantha Coleman\xe2\x80\x99s two daughters ran across the family\xe2\x80\x99s yard, chasing dozens of newly hatched chicks.'
p13337
aS'Coleman, 28, ran after them.'
p13338
aS'"Whoa! Child down," she called, reaching to pick up her 2-year-old, who had managed to fall into a bush.'
p13339
aS'"This is my life," Coleman said, laughing.'
p13340
aS'"Gummy bears in my pockets, half-naked kids, spills everywhere".'
p13341
aS'She paused.'
p13342
aS'"But I\xe2\x80\x99m good".'
p13343
aS'Sometimes this still surprises her.'
p13344
aS'Four years ago, things looked very different: Coleman was using heroin, was in a violent relationship and risked losing her older daughter to foster care.'
p13345
aS'In most places, a parent in Coleman\xe2\x80\x99s position would be required to complete a treatment program ordered by a traditional Family Court as a condition of regaining custody.'
p13346
aS'But the likelihood of losing one\xe2\x80\x99s child is high: there\xe2\x80\x99s little support for parents trying to finish treatment, and many drop out.'
p13347
aS'Federal data indicate that substance abuse accounts for nearly 40 percent of all cases in which a child is removed from home, though some experts believe that the number is as high as 80 percent.'
p13348
aS'Coleman\xe2\x80\x99s case was handled very differently.'
p13349
aS'Chautauqua County, N.Y., where she lives, had an innovative intervention program called Family Treatment Court, which gives parents access to a wide range of coordinated services.'
p13350
aS'Treatment programs are tailored to each participant\xe2\x80\x99s needs, and caseworkers and a presiding judge closely track their progress.'
p13351
aS'The first Family Treatment Court opened in Reno, Nevada in 1994, and there are now about 370 across the country.'
p13352
aS'The program helps parents complete drug and alcohol treatment, keeping them out of the criminal justice system and keeping their children out of foster care.'
p13353
aS'National statistics are not yet available to measure the effectiveness of the programs, because studies of Family Treatment Courts have generally been limited to assessments of individual programs, which vary in their methods.'
p13354
aS'One thing that is clear is that the innovation can save governments money.'
p13355
aS'A 2010 report on a Family Treatment Court in Oregon found that over a two-year period, the program reduced average criminal justice and child welfare costs by $13,000 a participant, whether or not they graduated.'
p13356
aS'But those courts serve only an estimated 5 to 10 percent of families who could benefit from them.'
p13357
aS'The need is growing across the country: opioid addiction is at epidemic levels and with it has come a flood of child welfare cases.'
p13358
aS'In Indiana, the number of children interacting with Child Protective Services jumped nearly 40 percent between 2013 and 2015; in 2016, the number of Massachusetts children placed in foster care reached 15,892, which Maria Mossaides, the state\xe2\x80\x99s child advocate, believes is a record high.'
p13359
aS'Before entering Family Treatment Court, Coleman struggled with addiction for years.'
p13360
aS'She had been prescribed opiates while recovering from an accident in which she had been severely burned and soon became addicted.'
p13361
aS'Sometimes she left her firstborn daughter alone with a physically abusive boyfriend so she could get high.'
p13362
aS'It was a pattern she had experienced herself, growing up in Dunkirk, in the western hills of New York State.'
p13363
aS'"All I\xe2\x80\x99d seen was domestic violence and chemical dependency from my mom and my whole family," she said.'
p13364
aS'"I didn\xe2\x80\x99t know any other way to live".'
p13365
aS'But when Coleman lost custody of her daughter in 2013, it was an alarm.'
p13366
aS'Ever since she was young, she\xe2\x80\x99d dreamed of being a mother.'
p13367
aS'Now, she realized that if she "didn\xe2\x80\x99t stop what I was doing I was going to destroy my daughter, and she was going to be doing the same thing I was in 10 years".'
p13368
aS'When Coleman began Family Treatment Court, she was nervous.'
p13369
