aS'This has happened at least three times before, and conditions are ripe for it to happen again.'
p14588
aS'As someone who has had malaria four times, I know the awful power of this disease.'
p14589
aS'I remember how grim the situation was in Africa in the 1990s when two of the most used medicines then, chloroquine and sulfadoxine/pyrimethamine, were failing.'
p14590
aS'A sense of hopelessness was felt by the people living with malaria and those of us working to stop the disease.'
p14591
aS'We had to accept a daily disaster \xe2\x80\x94 as a colleague of mine has put it, a 747 full of African children crashing into a mountain every three hours, day and night, for years on end.'
p14592
aS'With an enormous amount of work, we managed to reduce this carnage to something less horrible.'
p14593
aS'But I don\xe2\x80\x99t ever want to go back to those days.'
p14594
aS'Malaria is transmitted to humans (and other animals) by infected mosquitoes, who inject malaria parasites into the bloodstream.'
p14595
aS'The parasites spread throughout the body and multiply exponentially, causing chills, fever, headache, nausea and intense fatigue.'
p14596
aS'Over the last century, researchers have developed effective medicines for malaria, including quinine, chloroquine, sulfadoxine/pyrimethamine, mefloquine, and artemisinin.'
p14597
aS'When taken promptly, those drugs killed the parasites before they killed their host.'
p14598
aS'Unfortunately, as usually happens in the battle between microbe and human, the malaria bug has evolved and developed resistance to our medicines.'
p14599
aS'As a result, malaria has been beaten back in several places over the last 75 years, only to spread again, more lethal than before because the drugs no longer work.'
p14600
aS'Frequently, drug-resistant strains have originated in the Mekong region of Asia, an area that includes Myanmar, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam and the Yunnan Province of China.'
p14601
aS'We are not sure why it starts there; it is likely a combination of factors.'
p14602
aS'The parasites that circulate in the region may be able to mutate especially quickly.'
p14603
aS'The region draws tens of thousands of migrants, who come for work on rubber plantations and in other industries, and who are particularly susceptible to malaria since they have lower levels of natural immunity.'
p14604
aS'Because of widespread poverty, as well as lack of health care and education, those who get sick often use less medicine than they should, or use counterfeit drugs; both practices spur drug resistance.'
p14605
aS'Once drug resistance appears in the Mekong region, it spreads, often with ghastly results.'
p14606
aS'In the 1950s, chloroquine-resistant malaria jumped to India and Africa, killing millions.'
p14607
aS'Researchers, drug companies and public health officials came up with a replacement by combining two existing drugs, but then in the 1970s, parasites resistant to the sulfadoxine/pyrimethamine combination appeared in the Mekong and spread globally, rendering the treatment useless.'
p14608
aS'Since the late 1990s, we have relied on a drug called artemisinin, which is the best treatment we have ever had for malaria.'
p14609
aS'Much of our recent success against this disease reflects the power of this medicine.'
p14610
aS'It kills the parasite quickly, with few side effects, and it has saved millions of lives.'
p14611
aS'We have tried to forestall resistance by combining artemisinin with other drugs, much as we do when treating H.I.V. and tuberculosis, but the day of reckoning appears to be at hand.'
p14612
aS'Over the past decade, several studies have found widespread resistance to the artemisinin-piperaquine combination throughout Southeast Asia.'
p14613
aS'At some spots in western Cambodia, more than 40 percent of people who received artemisinin drug combinations failed to clear the parasites from their blood, or got sick again soon after treatment ended.'
p14614
aS'This is a clear and ominous sign that the parasites are becoming more resistant.'
p14615
aS'So now we stand once again on the edge of the precipice.'
p14616
aS'This time the risk of untreatable malaria is even greater than in the past, because no new drugs are likely to be available in the next few years.'
p14617
aS'It takes a long time for drugs to go through the development pipeline, and most of the leading candidates are close relatives of artemisinin, so the malaria-causing parasites will likely be resistant to those drugs as well.'
p14618
aS'The first response of the public health community was to try to contain drug-resistant malaria in the Mekong region where it originated, preventing its wider spread.'
p14619
aS'But past experience shows that this is not easy to do, and we now have clear evidence that multidrug resistant strains have spread across hundreds of miles, crossing national borders.'
p14620
aS'Even worse, new resistant strains are popping up repeatedly and spreading, in a lethal version of Whac-a-Mole.'
p14621
aS'Instead, we should focus on a more ambitious strategy: to eliminate malaria from the Mekong region.'
p14622
aS'This will be difficult, because the areas with the highest rates of malaria tend to be poor, rural and underdeveloped.'
p14623
aS'But with coordination, hard work and proper funding, we can achieve our goal.'
p14624
aS'Malaria has been eliminated from many regions where it was once common: the Southern United States, Russia, southern Europe, the Middle East and, most recently, Sri Lanka.'
p14625
aS'There is no reason we can\xe2\x80\x99t do the same in the Mekong region.'
p14626
aS'A broad consensus has emerged that elimination is the best strategy.'
p14627
aS'The World Health Organization; the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria; the President\xe2\x80\x99s Malaria Initiative; the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and others, have all expressed their commitment to this approach, as have the countries in the region.'
p14628
aS'Elimination will require a coordinated attack using all the weapons at our disposal.'
p14629
aS'We know we can eventually eliminate malaria from the region by using the currently available anti-mosquito and anti-parasite measures, including insecticides and bed nets, plus medicines and diagnostic tests.'
p14630
aS'Eliminating multidrug resistant malaria from the Mekong before it spreads to Africa will require so-called elimination accelerators, including highly sensitive new tests to identify symptom-free carriers of malaria infection, and mass drug treatment of infected groups or populations.'
p14631
aS'We also need closer cooperation from American and European health officials, international health agencies and financers, local nongovernmental organizations and especially from the inhabitants and governments of the Mekong region.'
p14632
aS'We must ramp up quickly; drug resistance is spreading; if it spins out of control, we run the risk of a huge resurgence of malaria in other parts of Asia and especially in Africa.'
