aS'President Donald Trump and Republican leaders inched closer to releasing their tax framework this week, as details leaked to lobbyists suggested it would dramatically cut taxes for corporations and the wealthy, provide a measure of middle-class tax relief and punish some households in Democratic-leaning states like New York and New Jersey.'
p15121
aS'The White House said Trump will travel to Indiana Wednesday for a late-afternoon speech that will focus on the tax-overhaul effort.'
p15122
aS'Early Monday morning, he tweeted that he has "important meetings taking place today. Big tax cuts & reform".'
p15123
aS'The only meetings listed on his schedule were a lunch with Vice President Mike Pence and dinner with "grassroots leaders" -- a group that will include several conservative organizations.'
p15124
aS'Certain details of the tax framework have been finalized, according to White House press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders.'
p15125
aS'She didn\xe2\x80\x99t specify which ones, and said conversations with members of the president\xe2\x80\x99s team, including Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin and National Economic Council Director Gary Cohn, will continue.'
p15126
aS'While some details of the framework may be in flux, a list of specifics that\xe2\x80\x99s circulating among Washington lobbyists breaks from the president\xe2\x80\x99s recent rhetoric against tax cuts for the rich.'
p15127
aS'It sets the stage for a battle with Democrats and faces a litany of obstacles, including intra-party disputes about whether to pay for the tax breaks upfront or increase the deficit.'
p15128
aS'The emerging framework includes a proposal to cut the corporate tax rate to 20 percent from 35 percent -- a costly move in revenue terms that Trump and Republicans say is necessary to create job growth.'
p15129
aS'But its provisions for individual taxes may hit closer to home for many Americans.'
p15130
aS'Three tax lobbyists familiar with those changes said they include cutting the top individual tax rate to 35 percent and creating a 25 percent rate for certain "pass-through" business owners -- both down from the current top rate of 39.6 percent.'
p15131
