aS'Growing up in Toronto in the 1980s, I had a connection to Holocaust history that was direct, visceral and human.'
p15884
aS'Each year, Holocaust survivors came to my school to talk about what they had experienced during the war.'
p15885
aS'It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t unusual for these survivors to be the grandparents of a classmate.'
p15886
aS'Some of them had just begun telling their stories for the first time.'
p15887
aS'I thought of my own grandparents, survivors from Poland who eventually immigrated to Montreal.'
p15888
aS'They hardly ever spoke to me about what happened to them and the family members they lost.'
p15889
aS'It was too painful for them to tell, and I was too afraid to ask.'
p15890
aS'Today, the Holocaust survivor population is diminishing quickly.'
p15891
aS'Most survivors are now in their 80s or 90s.'
p15892
aS'A few years ago, I started to think about a film about the last remaining Holocaust speakers, the people who have devoted their lives to describing a painful past, and what it might mean for that to come to an end \xe2\x80\x94 for them personally, and for us.'
p15893
aS'Then I read about the project   The University of Southern California Shoah Foundation, known for its work preserving genocide survivor testimonies, had embarked on a new project: interactive three-dimensional recordings of Holocaust survivors, to allow people to continue speaking to them long after they are gone.'
p15894
aS'I wanted to know more.'
p15895
aS'How did survivors feel about this new technology?'
p15896
aS'Could it really keep these interactions going?'
p15897
aS'What would it feel like to have a conversation with a digital survivor?'
p15898
aS'Filming Eva Schloss as she participated in the project and told her story to the surrounding cameras, I didn\xe2\x80\x99t find clear answers.'
p15899
aS'I heard a woman painfully aware of the injustice lived by so many around the world today, still determined to share her story in case it might help someone, somewhere.'
p15900
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m grateful to have had the chance to get to know Schloss in person.'
p15901
aS'Nothing can replace her.'
p15902
aS'But one day soon, I will take my kids to visit "New Dimensions in Testimony": They will see an interactive, digital version of Schloss and they will ask her questions about her life.'
p15903
aS'They will listen to her reflect on war, loss and social justice.'
p15904
aS'And I hope a conversation will begin, and continue, as it did for me over 30 years ago.'
