aS'S\xc3\x83O PAULO, Brazil \xe2\x80\x94 A woman weeps while sitting in a corporate board room, surrounded by a couple of frowning businessmen and floor-to-ceiling glass windows showcasing the S\xc3\xa3o Paulo skyline.'
p16247
aS'She\xe2\x80\x99s sorry, she says, but she should have the right to make mistakes.'
p16248
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s her first time on a reality TV show!'
p16249
aS'And besides, all she did was mess up someone\xe2\x80\x99s coffee order.'
p16250
aS'Jo\xc3\xa3o Doria, a media mogul, is unsympathetic.'
p16251
aS'"Our world is the real world," he says to the weeping woman from across the table.'
p16252
aS'"It\xe2\x80\x99s your world that is unreal".'
p16253
aS'Since January, a new season of reality has begun for many of us.'
p16254
aS'In the United States, Donald Trump became president.'
p16255
aS'Here in S\xc3\xa3o Paulo, Jo\xc3\xa3o Doria Jr. became mayor.'
p16256
aS'The two men have much in common: They are conservative populists with big egos.'
p16257
aS'They like to use social media to get their message out.'
p16258
aS'They have both written self-help business books with uninspired titles ("The Art of the Deal" by Mr. Trump, "Lessons in Winning" by Mr. Doria).'
p16259
aS'They are also both former hosts of the reality TV show "The Apprentice".'
p16260
aS'I wanted to get a better sense of my new mayor and what he\xe2\x80\x99ll do to my city.'
p16261
aS'But instead of looking at his electoral platform, his speeches or his academic record, I decided to go right to the primary source.'
p16262
aS'Following in   I set myself to the task of watching 31 episodes from two seasons of Mr. Doria\xe2\x80\x99s "O Aprendiz," the Brazilian franchise of Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s original show, to search for lessons on the nature of reality.'
p16263
aS'"O Aprendiz" is a game show that tests the business skills of a dozen candidates competing to earn a position at one of the host\xe2\x80\x99s corporations.'
p16264
aS'In each episode, they are assigned to teams and given a business-related task, usually sponsored by a certain company (a bank, a retail chain, an automobile manufacturer).'
p16265
aS'The task often consists in selling products or creating new advertising strategies.'
p16266
aS'The average episode goes something like this: The contestants \xe2\x80\x94 a majority of them white and privileged \xe2\x80\x94 receive about $5,000 to build a small kiosk in a mall.'
p16267
aS'They spend a couple of arduous days on the telephone, persuading other businesspeople to do favors such as donating products or attending marketing events.'
p16268
aS'They negotiate cutthroat rates with desperate freelancers.'
p16269
aS'Suddenly, they have some kind of brilliant idea \xe2\x80\x94 for example, dressing someone in a fluffy heart costume to promote coffee \xe2\x80\x94 and this stroke of genius produces a winner.'
p16270
aS'The winning team gets a luxury trip to Switzerland as a reward.'
p16271
aS'How many people we attended to?'
p16272
aS'Walking in the streets of Zurich, one of the participants recalls her whole excruciating day of serving coffee at a marketing event and says: "Remember how many coffee cups we served? We deserve this, don\xe2\x80\x99t we"?'
p16273
aS'(I imagine a real-life waiter who works for minimum-wage salary watching this and collapsing in sobs into a fetal position.'
p16274
aS') After the first few episodes, I noticed something peculiar: The participants were reaching out to the same companies that had already sponsored the previous challenges of the season.'
p16275
aS'(Let\xe2\x80\x99s call it the power of networking.'
p16276
aS') They\xe2\x80\x99ve also made outrageously improbable deals, like selling six bananas for $15 and earning 50 euros to wash a few dishes in an Italian hotel.'
p16277
aS'What does any of this have to do with Mr. Doria\xe2\x80\x99s way of doing politics?'
p16278
aS'A lot, actually.'
p16279
aS'Sometimes, as the mayor has proudly admitted, he calls one of his executive friends and asks for generous donations to the city.'
p16280
aS'It doesn\xe2\x80\x99t seem to matter if the company he\xe2\x80\x99s requesting money from is being sued by the city or has huge debts to it.'
p16281
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s the same kind of dubious, personalized style of doing business for which contestants on "O Aprendiz" are rewarded.'
p16282
aS'Look at the case of Cyrela, one of the biggest real estate companies in Brazil.'
p16283
aS'Cyrela agreed to renovate the restrooms in a S\xc3\xa3o Paulo park at "no cost" to the public, even though the renovation should cost about $140,000.'
p16284
aS'At the time, the company was involved in a legal dispute with the city over some separate building projects.'
p16285
aS'(That dispute was later settled.'
p16286
aS') Meanwhile, Cyrela also has vested interests in the forthcoming urban plan of S\xc3\xa3o Paulo, which will include laws about the maximum height of new buildings.'
p16287
aS'As if it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t enough, Mr. Doria has recently appointed Cyrela\xe2\x80\x99s former vice president as head of a new department called the Special Secretariat for Social Investment.'
p16288
aS'His first duty was to preside over the inauguration ceremony of the new toilets donated by his own former company.'
p16289
aS'It was like the scene from the last episode of Season 7, when a competitor manages to persuade Saulo, the singer who won the reality show "\xc3\x8ddolos," which is, of course, on the same channel as "O Aprendiz," to perform at a marketing event.'
p16290
aS'Mr. Doria doesn\xe2\x80\x99t see any conflicts of interest \xe2\x80\x94 though he once threatened to end an interview as soon as the issue came up.'
p16291
aS'On that occasion, the journalist was questioning the mayor on his links to one of his many private-sector pals: the owner of a drugstore chain called Ultrafarma, who happens to be a member of Lide, an events company founded by Mr. Doria and now run by his son.'
p16292
aS'The group often promotes business events with the participation of politicians.'
p16293
aS'According to news reports, Ultrafarma made a $190,000 donation to S\xc3\xa3o Paulo\xe2\x80\x99s public drug dispensaries last February.'
p16294
aS'(The mayor\xe2\x80\x99s press office denies this.'
p16295
aS') A day later, the mayor posted a video in which he personally advertised Ultrafarma\xe2\x80\x99s vitamin brand before a meeting of his cabinet.'
p16296
aS'The following month, Ultrafarma made an official donation to the municipality, this time in the form of prime-time TV advertisements for Mr. Doria\xe2\x80\x99s controversial cleanup program "Cidade Linda" (Beautiful City), which has been criticized by many citizens as a boondoggle.'
p16297
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s unclear how the city itself should have benefited from this donation.'
p16298
aS'What\xe2\x80\x99s even more worrying is that this "Aprendiz"-like behavior may not be confined to S\xc3\xa3o Paulo.'
p16299
aS'Mr. Doria is considered a possible candidate for the 2018 presidential elections.'
p16300
aS'From a business perspective, a timely donation to the city may pay off more than making a contribution to a political campaign.'
p16301
aS'In fact, this ethical minefield in Mr. Doria\xe2\x80\x99s administration has emerged soon after the Supreme Court decided to ban corporate donations to political campaigns.'
p16302
aS'The goal was precisely to weaken the ties between the government and business interests that could lead to bribery and other forms of corruption.'
p16303
aS'But Mr. Doria remains unperturbed in his polo shirt while managing ethically questionable decisions.'
p16304
aS'The mayor had already restricted the autonomy of the Office of the Municipal Comptroller General, the city\xe2\x80\x99s recently created anticorruption agency, and last month he fired the acting comptroller general "for administrative and operational reasons".'
p16305
aS'As a protest, three officials at the agency resigned, including the head of the integrity department.'
p16306
aS'Curiously, in the fifth episode of Season 8 of "O Aprendiz," Mr. Doria fired a contestant for using his connections with a business executive to get ahead in one of the challenges.'
p16307
aS'"This country will change only when it has ethics, principles," Mr. Doria declared vehemently while brandishing a silver pen.'
