aS'Sunday was a dark day for Germany.'
p16310
aS'For the first time in its postwar history, a far-right party won enough votes to enter the Bundestag.'
p16311
aS'And not by a hair, either \xe2\x80\x94 the Alternative for Germany, or AfD, won 12.6 percent, ahead of stalwart parties like the Greens and the pro-business Free Democrats, making it the third-largest caucus among the seven represented in the Parliament.'
p16312
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s shocking.'
p16313
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a catastrophe.'
p16314
aS'And yet Sunday was also a great day for Germany.'
p16315
aS'It was a demonstration of the stability and health of the country\xe2\x80\x99s postwar democracy.'
p16316
aS'It was proof that its system is resilient in a crisis.'
p16317
aS'It was a demonstration of Germany\xe2\x80\x99s serenity and maturity.'
p16318
aS'I will try to explain why both can be true at the same time.'
p16319
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a sad day because some 5.8 million Germans cast their vote for the AfD.'
p16320
aS'Founded in 2013 by a m\xc3\xa9lange of ultra-conservatives, right-wing economists and assorted fringe groups who were concerned about Chancellor Angela Merkel\xe2\x80\x99s adamant commitment to the euro, the party adopted an anti-immigrant stance, galvanized by the 2015-16 refugee crisis.'
p16321
aS'In both its platform and the public statements by AfD representatives, the party increasingly used racist language.'
p16322
aS'The AfD regards the German people as a coherent biological body under threat to be "destroyed" by immigration.'
p16323
aS'It strives to protect Germany\xe2\x80\x99s "endemic" culture against immigrant cultures, which it regards as inferior.'
p16324
aS'Alexander Gauland, one of the party\xe2\x80\x99s two front-runners, recently demanded that Aydan Ozogus, a policy maker of Turkish descent, be "disposed of" in Turkey.'
p16325
aS'He also said that Germany could be proud of "the achievements of German soldiers in two world wars".'
p16326
aS'In a statement after the election results, Mr. Gauland said "We will take back our country and our people".'
p16327
aS'The AfD will receive about 94 out of approximately 709 seats in the new parliament, meaning many even more obscure figures than Mr. Gauland will sweep into the Bundestag, people sympathizing with extremist groups and conspiracy theorists.'
p16328
aS'But there\xe2\x80\x99s another way to look at these results.'
p16329
aS'Only two years after 890,000 immigrants entered Germany almost at the same time, nearly overloading the system; only one year and nine months after gangs of young men, many of whom were immigrants from northern Africa, sexually harassed hundreds of women on New Year\xe2\x80\x99s Eve in Cologne; only months after a series of terrorist attacks in Germany, one in the very capital of the country, left 12 dead \xe2\x80\x94 after all this, 87 percent of German voters still cast their ballot for parties   than the anti-immigration, far-right AfD.'
p16330
aS'No matter what the AfD tried to argue during the closing weeks of the race, the past year and a half tells a story of national unity rather than of national agony.'
p16331
aS'Given the relatively staid nature of German politics, it may be hard for outsiders to grasp just how contentious the past two years have been.'
p16332
aS'In January 2016, just after the Cologne attacks, the atmosphere in Germany was close to ignition.'
p16333
aS'Trust in the government sharply dropped, and so did Mrs. Merkel\xe2\x80\x99s poll numbers.'
p16334
aS'Some polls put the AfD as high as 15 percent.'
p16335
aS'But then the governing coalition of center-left Social Democrats and center-right Christian Democrats changed its policy.'
p16336
aS'The Bundestag passed a series of laws restricting immigration, and it gave enhanced powers to police and intelligence services.'
p16337
aS'Mrs. Merkel, a Christian Democrat, pushed an agreement with Turkey to hold back refugees in exchange for financial support.'
p16338
aS'Not all these policies are smart.'
p16339
aS'Some will hinder the integration of refugees and other immigrants who are in Germany to stay.'
p16340
aS'But many are reasonable and necessary, and none undermine the coalition government\xe2\x80\x99s basic commitment to help refugees.'
p16341
aS'And they shored up public support for Mrs. Merkel, for the government and for the country\xe2\x80\x99s refugee policy.'
p16342
aS'If you look at democracy as a marketplace of ideas and positions, Germany\xe2\x80\x99s political economy has actually worked extremely well over the past year.'
p16343
aS'The AfD surged because of a market gap for stricter immigration laws \xe2\x80\x94 and when the established parties adopted policies to fill this gap, the extremists were robbed of their fuel.'
p16344
aS'Today, according to one poll, only 50 percent of Germans consider refugees an "important problem".'
p16345
aS'In this week\xe2\x80\x99s election, people cared deeply about education, about elderly care, about North Korea.'
p16346
aS'Refugee policy was one important topic, but not the dominant one.'
p16347
aS'Sixty percent said they voted for the AfD because they were dissatisfied with the established parties.'
p16348
aS'But even that response is a good sign; it shows that we do not necessarily have five million racists living among us.'
p16349
aS'This was a belated act of protest, not a shift in the country\xe2\x80\x99s ideological landscape.'
p16350
aS'Many Germans have nagged their way through this campaign \xe2\x80\x94 too dull, they said, too boring, not confrontational enough.'
p16351
aS'I found that annoying: What sort of election did they want?'
p16352
aS'The kind that features a candidate who calls his opponent "crooked"?'
p16353
aS'On Sunday, Germans had the option of two capable and experienced major candidates, and many more in a variety of smaller parties, representing pretty much every political viewpoint.'
p16354
aS'For the most part, these are people who really care about the country, and have a deep knowledge of the most important issues.'
p16355
aS'Two thirds of all eligible voters actually went to vote.'
p16356
aS'Most of them voted for liberal democracy.'
p16357
aS'The headlines on Monday were ominous.'
p16358
aS'But we should not forget what a lucky bunch we are.'
