aS'BEIJING \xe2\x80\x94 My grandmother likes to tell stories from her career as a journalist in the early decades of the People\xe2\x80\x99s Republic of China.'
p16360
aS'She recalls scrawling down Chairman Mao\xe2\x80\x99s latest pronouncements as they came through loudspeakers and talking with joyous peasants from the newly collectivized countryside.'
p16361
aS'In what was her career highlight, she turned an anonymous candy salesman into a national labor hero with glowing praises for his service to the people.'
p16362
aS'She had grown up in the central province of Hunan, where her father was a landlord.'
p16363
aS'She talks about her mother as a glum housewife who resented her husband for taking a concubine after she had failed to give birth to a boy.'
p16364
aS'"The Communists did many terrible things," my grandmother always says at the end of her reminiscences.'
p16365
aS'"But they made women\xe2\x80\x99s lives much better".'
p16366
aS'That often-repeated dictum sums up the popular perception of Mao Zedong\xe2\x80\x99s legacy regarding women in China.'
p16367
aS'As every Chinese schoolchild learns in history class, the Communists rescued peasant daughters from urban brothels and ushered cloistered wives into factories, liberating them from the oppression of Confucian patriarchy and imperialist threat.'
p16368
aS'But the narrative of an across-the-board elevation of women\xe2\x80\x99s status under Mao contains crucial caveats.'
p16369
aS'While the Communist revolution brought women more job opportunities, it also made their interests subordinate to collective goals.'
p16370
aS'Stopping at the household doorstep, Mao\xe2\x80\x99s words and policies did little to alleviate women\xe2\x80\x99s domestic burdens like housework and child care.'
p16371
aS'And by inundating society with rhetoric blithely celebrating its achievements, the revolution deprived women of the private language with which they might understand and articulate their personal experiences.'
p16372
aS'When historians researched the collectivization of the Chinese countryside in the 1950s, an event believed to have empowered rural women by offering them employment, they discovered a complicated picture.'
p16373
aS'While women indeed contributed enormously to collective farming, they rarely rose to positions of responsibility; they remained outsiders in communes organized around their husbands\xe2\x80\x99 family and village relationships.'
p16374
aS'Studies also showed that women routinely performed physically demanding jobs but earned less than men, since the lighter, most valued tasks involving large animals or machinery were usually reserved for men.'
p16375
aS'The urban workplace was hardly more inspiring.'
p16376
aS'Women were shunted to collective neighborhood workshops with meager pay and dismal working conditions, while men were more commonly employed in comfortable big-industry and state-enterprise jobs.'
p16377
aS'Party cadres\xe2\x80\x99 explanations for this reflected deeply entrenched gender prejudices: Women have a weaker constitution and gentler temper, rendering them unfit for the strenuous tasks of operating heavy equipment or manning factory floors.'
p16378
aS'The party at times paid lip service to the equal sharing of domestic labor, but in practice it condoned women\xe2\x80\x99s continuing subordination in the home.'
p16379
aS'In posters and speeches, female socialist icons were portrayed as "iron women" who labored heroically in front of steel furnaces while maintaining a harmonious family.'
p16380
aS'But it was a cherry-picking approach that focused exclusively on bringing women into the work force and neglected their experiences in other realms.'
p16381
aS'Visitors to rural areas saw peasant wives toiling around the clock: cooking, mending clothes and feeding livestock after finishing a day of work in the fields.'
p16382
aS'Their plight shocked the urban youth who were sent down to the countryside during the Cultural Revolution, such that Naihua Zhang, a sociology professor at Florida Atlantic University who spent time in the countryside as a young woman in that era, equated rural marriage with a total erasure of women\xe2\x80\x99s identity.'
p16383
aS'Researchers also observed that after marriage factory women often experienced slower career advancement than men as they became saddled with domestic responsibilities that left them with little time to learn new skills and take on extra work, both prerequisites for promotion.'
p16384
aS'State services that promised to ease their burden, like public child care centers, were in reality few and far between.'
p16385
aS'Unlike their counterparts in developed countries, Chinese women didn\xe2\x80\x99t have labor-saving household appliances, since Mao\xe2\x80\x99s economic policies prioritized heavy industry over the production of consumer products like washing machines and dishwashers.'
p16386
aS'Some Western scholars have said these realities amounted to a "revolution postponed".'
p16387
aS'Yet the conclusions of researchers were contradicted by none other than Chinese women themselves.'
p16388
aS'During her field study in China in 1970s, Margery Wolf, who was an anthropology professor at University of Iowa, was surprised by how effusive Chinese women were about the miracle of female emancipation in the very presence of their continued oppression.'
p16389
aS'"It was easy to take gender equality \xe2\x80\x94 an ideal that was widely promoted \xe2\x80\x94 as the reality and regard problems as reminiscent of old systems and ideology that would erode with time," said Professor Zhang, the sociologist.'
p16390
aS'The state rolled out propaganda campaigns aimed at not only enlisting women in the work force but also shaping their self-perception.'
p16391
aS'Posters, textbooks and newspapers propagated images and narratives that, devoid of any particularities of personal experiences, depicted women as men\xe2\x80\x99s equal in outlook, value and achievement.'
p16392
aS'For women in the workplace to adhere to this narrowly defined acceptable female image meant to see, understand and speak about their life not as it was, but as what it ought to be according to the party ideal.'
p16393
aS'It is a measure of the campaign\xe2\x80\x99s success that women who publicly described their experiences in the Mao era did so exclusively in official rhetoric.'
p16394
aS'Elisabeth Croll, an anthropologist specializing in Chinese women, observed that all published accounts of Chinese women\xe2\x80\x99s lives during the early decades of the People\xe2\x80\x99s Republic followed the standard narrative of their rise from mistreated wives and daughters to independent, socialist workers; it had become the story of practically every woman.'
p16395
aS'Forty years after Mao\xe2\x80\x99s death, this aspect of his legacy is still understood through his famous pronouncement on gender equality, "Women hold up half the sky".'
p16396
aS'It is a slogan my grandmother utters in the same breath as the chairman\xe2\x80\x99s other sins and deeds.'
p16397
aS'She does not mention the arduous work of managing a household and raising three children amid tumultuous revolutionary campaigns.'
p16398
aS'Nor does she complain about how she couldn\xe2\x80\x99t join the party because of her husband\xe2\x80\x99s unpopular political affiliations.'
p16399
aS'She gives only a chuckle when she recalls the exhortations she once received from party superiors to marry just as her career was taking off.'
p16400
aS'For all its flaws, the Communist revolution taught Chinese women to dream big.'
p16401
aS'When it came to advice for my mother, my grandmother applauded her daughter\xe2\x80\x99s decision to go to graduate school and urged her to find a husband who would be supportive of her career.'
p16402
aS'She still seems to think that the new market economy \xe2\x80\x94 with its meritocracy and freedom of choice \xe2\x80\x94 will finally allow women to be masters of their minds and actions.'
p16403
aS'After all, she has always said to my mother, "you have more opportunities".'
