aS'Ren\xc3\xa9 Descartes has long been credited with the near-single-handed creation of modern philosophy.'
p16405
aS'Generations of students have read, and continue to read, his famous "Meditations" as the rejection of medieval ways of thinking and the invention of the modern self.'
p16406
aS'They learned that he doubted all traditional ways of knowing before pivoting to the modern subjective individual.'
p16407
aS'Tumbling into a "deep whirlpool," the doubter of the "Meditations" has no secure footing until he hits upon a single firm and indubitable truth: He is most essentially "a thinking thing".'
p16408
aS'The modern individual is born, with the rejection of the past as its midwife.'
p16409
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s a dramatic story.'
p16410
aS'But it\xe2\x80\x99s false.'
p16411
aS'Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s contemporaries in the 17th century would have been stunned to hear these accomplishments credited to him.'
p16412
aS'Although he was rightly famous in his time for some of his scientific and mathematical ideas, many considered his philosophical proposals about the radical difference between mind and body implausible and unoriginal.'
p16413
aS'Even his scientific ideas were often ranked on par with others.'
p16414
aS'For example, the English philosopher   considered Hobbes\xe2\x80\x99s and Spinoza\xe2\x80\x99s account of corporeal nature to be equally influential, and similarly mistaken.'
p16415
aS'Another contemporary, the German Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, agreed, sometimes comparing Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s proposals to those of long-forgotten thinkers like  .'
p16416
aS'Others noted his debt to past thinkers.'
p16417
aS'In his "Dictionary," Pierre Bayle writes of complaints about Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s "pirating" of ideas from earlier sources.'
p16418
aS'Fast forward a century or so to Kant, who does not consider the author of the "Meditations" to be worth much attention.'
p16419
aS'So if Descartes did not invent modern philosophy, how was this false narrative created and sustained?'
p16420
aS'The longstanding story about Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s creation of a "new philosophy" that broke radically with medieval "ways of thinking" and that marked "the dawn of modern times" was promoted by philosophers who came after Kant and who, oddly enough, turned Descartes into the originator of "Germanic" thought.'
p16421
aS'In his 1820s lectures on the history of philosophy, Hegel asserts that "Germanic, i. e., modern philosophy begins with Descartes".'
p16422
aS'By 1847, Schopenhauer insists "our excellent Descartes" is "the instigator of subjective investigation and in this the father of modern philosophy".'
p16423
aS'A prominent German professor, Kuno Fischer (1824 -1907), published a gripping (and multivolume) story in the 1870s about Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s groundbreaking ideas and their impact on subsequent thought.'
p16424
aS'In a revealing passage from his extended discussion of Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s life and innovations, Fischer writes: "In the whole range of philosophical literature, there is no work in which the struggle for truth is portrayed in a more animated, personal, captivating manner and, at the same time, more simply and clearly, than in Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s essay on method and his first \xe2\x80\x98Meditation. \xe2\x80\x99 " This 19th-century invention of the "modern era" excised 17th- and 18th-century philosophy of its theological and religious underpinnings \xe2\x80\x94 and its women, whether they were overtly theological or not.'
p16425
aS'Even influential Enlightenment figures like the natural philosopher,  , were ignored, not to mention the contributions of significant 17th-century radical thinkers like   and Anne Conway, a favorite of Leibniz.'
p16426
aS'The adulation continued into the early 20th century, when Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s heroism was codified by prominent thinkers like the German Ernst Cassirer (1874-1945) and the French \xc3\x89tienne Gilson (1884-1978).'
p16427
aS'In Cassirer\xe2\x80\x99s dramatic telling, Descartes single-handedly created the "spiritual essence" of a new epoch, which would "permeate all fields of knowledge," to which 18th-century philosophers responded, and out of which Kant and other German thinkers would arise as liberating angels.'
p16428
aS'Based on his interpretation of the 17th century as a period of "great metaphysical systems" developed in response to Descartes, Cassirer advised historians to "string its various intellectual formulations along the thread of time and study them chronologically".'
p16429
aS'That is, in order to understand "the sum total" of the period\xe2\x80\x99s "philosophical content," it was sufficient to track its systems "lengthwise".'
p16430
aS'And so people did.'
p16431
aS'One of the most influential treatments of the history of philosophy in the English speaking world is the hugely ambitious and admirably clear study by Frederick Copleston, an Oxford trained classicist who converted to Catholicism, became a Jesuit priest, and famously debated his friend A. J. Ayer as well as Bertrand Russell on philosophical and theological matters.'
p16432
aS'In elegant concise prose, Copleston kept to the lengthwise approach, displaying the whole history of philosophy in nine volumes, published between 1946\xe2\x80\x9375 and widely read in the English-speaking world.'
p16433
aS'Although Copleston includes mystics like   (1260-1328) and prominent Jesuit scholastics like Francisco   (1548\xe2\x80\x931617), he entirely ignores the richly philosophical spiritual writings of even the most prominent late medieval women, reducing the entirety of philosophy to a series of great men, each responding to the ones who went before.'
p16434
aS'Analytically trained historians working in the mid-20th century were satisfied to rummage through the "great systems" of the canonical great men to find their philosophical gems.'
p16435
aS'And who can blame them?'
p16436
aS'From Bertrand Russell\xe2\x80\x99s book on Leibniz (1900) to Peter Strawson\xe2\x80\x99s study of Kant (1966), prominent philosophers could grind their own philosophical axes using historical texts.'
p16437
aS'They felt justified in restricting themselves to the standard story about modern philosophy and its limited range of problems, to which they could apply their philosophical tools with the hope of producing innovative ideas and arguments for themselves and their colleagues.'
p16438
aS'One did not need to worry one\xe2\x80\x99s head with the social and political complications of early modern Europe, much less dirty one\xe2\x80\x99s hands with the messiness of its theology.'
p16439
aS'One could focus on what   to properly educated philosophers.'
p16440
aS'This approach was doomed to fail.'
p16441
aS'The richness and diversity of early modern philosophy were bound to become evident, engendering a growing awareness of the inadequacy of the standard story.'
p16442
aS'The engendering of that inadequacy was itself gendered.'
p16443
aS'When feminist scholars in the 1980s began to explore early modern women writers, they discovered both the richness of the period\xe2\x80\x99s philosophy and the inadequacy of the lengthwise approach.'
p16444
aS'Scholars like Eileen O\xe2\x80\x99Neill dared historians to widen their scope and include long-forgotten figures, foreseeing how women\xe2\x80\x99s philosophies would offer significant insights into the period\xe2\x80\x99s central debates.'
p16445
aS'This strategy has produced significant results and begun to influence the way historians of philosophy think about the period.'
p16446
aS'Most relevant to the reconsideration of Descartes and the subjective individual that he was supposed to have invented is the recent recognition that late medieval spiritual meditations \xe2\x80\x94 especially those written by women like Julian of Norwich, Hadewijch of Brabant, Catherine of Siena and Teresa of \xc3\x81vila \xe2\x80\x94 involved the need to focus on the meditator\xe2\x80\x99s subjectivity as a means to rethink everything the meditator has previously learned about the world.'
p16447
aS'The point was to learn not to   about the external matters so as to develop new habits and beliefs.'
p16448
aS'For most meditators, the only proper means to do this was through subjective exploration.'
p16449
aS'Longstanding prejudice against women, their capacities to reason, and their right to teach had left women out of philosophy for centuries.'
p16450
aS'But the 12th century witnessed the beginning of a shift to meditative practices emphasizing introspection and feelings.'
p16451
aS'Although created by men, the new forms of spiritual practice gave women the right, for the first time in centuries to write and be read.'
p16452
aS'Because women were considered naturally predisposed to emotive introspection, their spiritual writings began to be taken seriously.'
p16453
aS'In constant fear of overstepping their bounds, these authors had to find imaginative ways to share their insights while seeming suitably humble.'
p16454
aS'For example, Julian of Norwich writes in late 14th-century England, "Just because I am a woman, must I \xe2\x80\xa6 not tell you about the goodness of God, when I saw \xe2\x80\xa6 his wish that it should be known"?'
p16455
aS'Women like Julian had to admit their "natural" inferiority and practice their philosophy within the confines of this emotive spiritual genre.'
p16456
aS'And so they did, brilliantly, writing carefully in their meditations about the subjective individual who doubts everything she was previously taught before progressing to self-knowledge and eventually to truth.'
p16457
aS'It is here in the spiritual writings of late medieval women that we find many of the features that Hegel and Schopenhauer considered new and "Germanic".'
p16458
aS'To be sure, the steps in Descartes\xe2\x80\x99s "Meditations" are rendered in more explicitly epistemological terms than those of his predecessors, but his strategy and pivot to self-knowledge were already at the time centuries old.'
p16459
aS'It is no wonder his contemporaries were not very impressed.'
p16460
aS'Our understanding of history evolves.'
p16461
aS'We can now see Descartes as the benefactor of a long tradition, to which women significantly contributed.'
p16462
aS'The time seems right to rethink the role of women and other noncanonical figures in the history of philosophy and begin to create a more accurate story about philosophy\xe2\x80\x99s rich and diverse past.'
