aS'\xe2\x80\x94 In December 1953, the inaugural issue of Playboy magazine hit newsstands without a date.'
p16888
aS'Hugh Hefner, its creator, was unsure whether it would be a success and have a future, so by withholding the date he hoped he could continue to sell that issue until he sold out of that first run.'
p16889
aS'Mr. Hefner, who  , had nothing to worry about.'
p16890
aS'In its prime, the magazine ranked among America\xe2\x80\x99s top-selling publications, alongside Life and Time, sometimes beating their subscription rates.'
p16891
aS'The magazine, intended for men, quickly transcended Mr. Hefner\xe2\x80\x99s target audience, with a subscriber base that cut across gender, race, class and ideology.'
p16892
aS'Today it\xe2\x80\x99s easy to write off Playboy, and Mr. Hefner, as the last remnants of a more sexist age.'
p16893
aS'But seen from the perspective of the 1950s and \xe2\x80\x9960s, they were progressive icons \xe2\x80\x94 not just in the libertine styles they promoted, but in the causes that they featured.'
p16894
aS'The magazine became central to what it meant to be a modern man.'
p16895
aS'The masculine ideal of the era was narrowly defined: aloof, outdoorsy, a breadwinner, "manly".'
p16896
aS'Showing too much of an interest in culture, fine food or travel was anathema.'
p16897
aS'Mr. Hefner felt trapped by conformity and designed a magazine that promoted a very different idea of what made an individual a "man" through its features and advice on clothing, food, alcohol selections, art, music and literature.'
p16898
aS'Though it quickly became a clich\xc3\xa9, many male readers really did "read it for the articles," telling surveys that they enjoyed features on the ideal bachelor pad even more than the centerfold.'
p16899
aS'Of course, Playboy was never just about the articles.'
p16900
aS'From the beginning, its goal was to combine and appeal to men\xe2\x80\x99s entire range of interests \xe2\x80\x94 the intellectual, the entertaining and the erotic.'
p16901
aS'Hence the Playboy Playmate, which Mr. Hefner modeled after Esquire\xe2\x80\x99s Vargas Girls, popular among servicemen during World War II.'
p16902
aS'Women in the magazine, he said, were intended more as the girl next door than as sex objects.'
p16903
aS'Still, the fact that they were often topless (full nudity didn\xe2\x80\x99t appear until 1972) brought criticism that Mr. Hefner objectified women; promoted an unrealistic standard of female beauty; and promulgated the idea that women should be subservient playmates for the modern man.'
p16904
aS'To Mr. Hefner, women were simply one of the interests of most heterosexual men.'
p16905
aS'The magazine featured discussions of equal rights, contraception and reproductive choice.'
p16906
aS'Mr. Hefner never saw that as a contradiction.'
p16907
aS'As the magazine\xe2\x80\x99s editorial style evolved, Mr. Hefner and his editors delved more into politics and current events.'
p16908
aS'By the 1960s, he was writing a frequent installment, "The Playboy Philosophy," in which he addressed topics like the First Amendment and sexual mores.'
p16909
aS'He advocated gay rights.'
p16910
aS'He pushed for women\xe2\x80\x99s access to birth control and abortion.'
p16911
aS'He discussed censorship as well as what constituted "obscene" in the United States, and he promoted the free exchange of thoughts and ideas.'
p16912
aS'And readers responded.'
p16913
aS'So many wrote in that the magazine created "The Playboy Forum," where it published readers\xe2\x80\x99 letters discussing the content of the "Philosophy".'
p16914
aS'Playboy became more than just a magazine, but a place that facilitated dialogue among a wide variety of readers: Men, women, veterans, draft dodgers, congressmen and clergy all wrote into the Forum.'
p16915
aS'Mr. Hefner went beyond the pages of Playboy to spread his message.'
p16916
aS'He created the Playboy Club franchise to bring the atmosphere of the magazine to life for its readers.'
p16917
aS'They could buy good food, good liquor and good entertainment.'
p16918
aS'He integrated his staff and membership; he hired men and women of all races, and often provided black comedians and musicians their first chances to perform in front of white audiences.'
p16919
aS'When a New Orleans and Miami club owner segregated the membership, Mr. Hefner bought those franchises back.'
p16920
aS'The clubs provided female employees with tuition reimbursement and encouraged them to attend college.'
p16921
aS'Mr. Hefner also set up the Playboy Foundation, which supported First Amendment rights, often contributing to defendants in free-speech cases.'
p16922
aS'The foundation went on to support other works, including research on post-traumatic stress disorder, commissions on Agent Orange and programs and organizations for veterans.'
p16923
aS'Those latter causes were no coincidence: Playboy played a major role in the American war in Vietnam.'
p16924
aS'For hundreds of thousands of young men "in country" \xe2\x80\x94 their average age was 19 \xe2\x80\x94 the magazine made them feel as if they were back home.'
p16925
aS'The centerfold pages hung on tent flaps and office walls, and could be found stashed in pockets, helmets and packs.'
p16926
aS'The interest went beyond the women: Young soldiers eagerly perused the glossy advertisements for the latest stereos, cars and fashion, which they could buy at one of the mall-like PXs on the military\xe2\x80\x99s sprawling bases (yes, even cars, which the government would ship home).'
p16927
aS'It acted as a how-to guide for consumption and consumerism for many young men who had never had disposable income before.'
p16928
aS'Articles and interviews in the magazine were some of their only sources of real news about the growing antiwar and counterculture movements stateside.'
p16929
aS'They went beyond the headlines, too, discussing and critiquing strategy, the draft and the politicians who moved the chess pieces.'
p16930
aS'But the magazine also remained supportive of the men fighting the war.'
p16931
aS'Countless letters from servicemen to the magazine, now stored in the Playboy archives, reveal how much the magazine lifted morale, how it brought a welcome respite from the boredom, terror and chaos they endured on a daily basis.'
p16932
aS'While the magazine deserved criticism, its evolution reflected changing norms and values in American society.'
p16933
aS'In August 1967, a soldier named Donald Iasillo wrote to Playboy thanking the magazine for literally saving his life.'
p16934
aS'An issue folded in his chest pocket had prevented a bullet from entering his heart.'
p16935
aS'"Usually for reasons other than its value as armor plate, Playboy is by far the biggest morale booster in Vietnam," he wrote.'
p16936
aS'"For this, we  thank you".'
