aS'That enormous sum excludes the $1 million the administration expected to spend this week on Milo Yiannopoulos\xe2\x80\x99s chaotic and disorganized "Free Speech Week".'
p16940
aS'Free Speech Week was supposed to be a four-day rally that brought in big-name provocateurs like Ann Coulter and Steve Bannon.'
p16941
aS'But although Mr. Yiannopoulos spent lots of energy  , he appears to have spent very little planning it.'
p16942
aS'He and the Berkeley Patriot, the student group hosting his event, failed to confirm most of their speakers, including Ms. Coulter and Mr. Bannon, and they never filed the paperwork necessary to book campus venues.'
p16943
aS'On Friday, the Berkeley Patriot pulled its support for the event entirely.'
p16944
aS'Predictably, Mr. Yiannopoulos declared at a   on Saturday that the Berkeley administration did "everything in its power to crush its own students\xe2\x80\x99 aspirations" to host his event, and vowed nevertheless to speak on Berkeley\xe2\x80\x99s Sproul Plaza "come hell or high water".'
p16945
aS'The school still expects to spend a handsome sum to secure the unsponsored event.'
p16946
aS'If that seems unwarranted, consider that Berkeley has had to essentially soldier up for unexpectedly violent rallies in their public plaza many times this year.'
p16947
aS'This is a huge distraction for a university already struggling to reduce a crippling budget deficit of $150 million.'
p16948
aS'And it raises a thorny question for those who believe that free speech should trump all else: Should public institutions be spending taxpayer money allocated for higher education on speakers who aren\xe2\x80\x99t there for teaching and learning?'
p16949
aS'I\xe2\x80\x99m intimately familiar with the right-wing tactic of framing anything less than free speech absolutism as "against free speech," in part because I   this tactic as a conservative college student.'
p16950
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s easy to declare that if low-value speakers like Mr. Yiannopoulos want a campus platform, it\xe2\x80\x99s censorship if a school doesn\xe2\x80\x99t give them one.'
p16951
aS'But as we are seeing with Berkeley, the reality is that "free speech on campus" is not resource-neutral.'
p16952
aS'Indeed, in an effort to make sure Free Speech Week could go on, Janet Napolitano, the president of University of California, even offered to chip in at least $300,000 to help with security.'
p16953
aS'"It\xe2\x80\x99s a cost that the university is bearing to protect the speakers but also to protect the value of free speech," she said.'
p16954
aS'That\xe2\x80\x99s a bold statement from Ms. Napolitano, as security concerns about Mr. Yiannopoulos\xe2\x80\x99s event resulted in the postponement of a previously scheduled talk by Anna Tsing, a leading anthropologist.'
p16955
aS'I doubt Ms. Tsing\xe2\x80\x99s anthropology lecture would have cost Berkeley and the University of California system anywhere near $1 million.'
p16956
aS'And I suspect that if Ms. Tsing were sharing the campus with a conservative like Yuval Levin or Walter Williams on the same day, neither speech would have to be canceled.'
p16957
aS'Which is why spending seven figures\xe2\x80\x99 worth of student fees and taxpayer money to host Mr. Yiannopoulos is less about defending free speech than it is about supporting provocation for its own sake.'
p16958
aS'Undoubtedly, left-wing "antifa" groups have contributed to the security risks and costs at Berkeley, taking the bait that speakers like Mr. Yiannopoulos lay out and   far-right militia groups who  .'
p16959
aS'But we should keep in mind, as the historian Mark Bray  , that antifa groups form specifically to counter white supremacist and Nazi violence, having done so from the days of Hitler and Mussolini.'
p16960
aS'Antifa groups are a symptom, not a cause, of the threat of white supremacist violence.'
p16961
aS'For the most part, both sides have little to do with college students who are, by and large, angry to see their campus overrun by outsiders.'
p16962
aS'Universities have a duty to keep campuses safe, not in the service of paternalism, but in the service of providing a suitable learning environment for students.'
p16963
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s easy to claim that denying a speaker \xe2\x80\x94 even one like Mr. Yiannopoulos or Richard Spencer \xe2\x80\x94 is a kind of epistemological harm that makes students worse off.'
p16964
aS'But so too are the acts of shutting down popular facilities for security purposes, and bringing in less-experienced security personnel who   violence with students, and transforming the campus into a microcosm of a police state.'
p16965
aS'The question of which campus speakers warrant security funding is real and challenging \xe2\x80\x94 especially considering that a speech by Ben Shapiro, a mainstream conservative who used to speak at Berkeley with barely a mention, recently cost the school $600,000 in security expenses.'
p16966
aS'But the escalation of security costs isn\xe2\x80\x99t a response to conservative thought.'
p16967
aS'It is the only way schools can respond to a deliberate right-wing strategy, driven by outside groups, to inflict disruptive and deliberately offensive speakers on campuses, and thus bait the left into outrage.'
p16968
aS'The audience for right-wing speakers like Mr. Yiannopoulos is not college students themselves, but rather the culture warriors on either side of the aisle who respond to seeing campus communities in distress.'
p16969
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s true that we\xe2\x80\x99re hearing fewer cries of campus censorship since   universities denied Mr. Spencer a speaking engagement after his "Unite the Right" rally in Charlottesville, Va., in August turned violent and deadly.'
p16970
aS'But we shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be fooled into thinking that the only problem with a speaker like Mr. Spencer is the offensiveness of his views.'
p16971
aS'It may feel easier to draw the line at Nazis and overt white supremacists, but that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t excuse us from thinking seriously \xe2\x80\x94 as we should have a long time ago \xe2\x80\x94 about educational standards for who deserves a college platform and financial resources.'
p16972
aS'Whereas conservatives politicians have traditionally warned against reckless public spending, in some cases by attempting to   entire academic divisions and programs, they\xe2\x80\x99re suddenly urging public institutions to hand over their wallets to bring a person to campus who\xe2\x80\x99s known for   to publicly mock them during his talks.'
p16973
aS'Mr. Yiannopoulos has already   two Berkeley students he disagrees with, posting their photos and identifying information on social media, which puts these students in direct danger of being harassed and threatened.'
p16974
aS'When speakers like these cost hundreds of thousands of dollars but add scant academic value, the issue is more complicated than the radical or offensive nature of their views.'
p16975
aS'We do need more conservative voices on campus.'
p16976
aS'But a free speech movement that has elevated expensive provocateurs over conservative intellectuals has only undermined the cause of campus intellectual diversity.'
