aS'Jann Wenner, the founder of Rolling Stone magazine, announced a few days ago that he was putting his company\xe2\x80\x99s controlling stake in the longtime music publication up for sale.'
p16996
aS'For many, it feels like the end of an era, but especially for me.'
p16997
aS'I worked there in the early 1990s, as an intern and then as an editorial assistant.'
p16998
aS'It\xe2\x80\x99s where I learned how to be a journalist \xe2\x80\x94 and, to a greater extent than I realized at the time, it\xe2\x80\x99s where I learned how to be an American.'
p16999
aS'In the summer of 1992, as part of the requirements for my journalism degree at the University of Maryland, College Park, I applied for an internship at a few publications, including Rolling Stone.'
p17000
aS'At the time, the magazine was widely regarded as the leading cultural magazine in America.'
p17001
aS'The coolest thing I could imagine was to work there \xe2\x80\x94 even if I wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t get paid.'
p17002
aS'When I got the internship, I packed my bags and moved to New York without a moment\xe2\x80\x99s thought, leaving my boyfriend behind.'
p17003
aS'I grew up in Lebanon and moved to the United States as a teenager, and when I arrived in New York my understanding of the country was still taking shape; I was still grappling with the complicated set of rules that governed American culture, so different from what I had imagined as a child, gorging on American film, TV shows and music in the embattled Beirut of the 1970s and \xe2\x80\x9980s.'
p17004
aS'The road to success, I quickly realized, was not a straight shot but a windy, often hard to see or follow thruway.'
p17005
aS'And another thing: America had yet to become the feminist Eden I was so eager to inhabit.'
p17006
aS'These, and many others, aren\xe2\x80\x99t the sorts of things I picked up on overnight.'
p17007
aS'But I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t have chosen a better place to begin unpacking them than Rolling Stone in the early 1990s.'
p17008
aS'I felt instantly at home.'
p17009
aS'I thought at the time that I was not learning much, sifting through daily newspapers for articles the editors might want to read, but it provided me with a front view of American culture \xe2\x80\x94 both the day-to-day culture of a professional American work environment, and the unfolding of the culture at large through the production of one of its most famous magazines.'
p17010
aS'The internship\xe2\x80\x99s three months went by fast, and I was soon back at school.'
p17011
aS'But a few days after I graduated the following December, I was in New York again, desperately hoping to be hired at Rolling Stone.'
p17012
aS'Three agonizing months later, an editorial assistant position opened up at the magazine.'
p17013
aS'I applied and got it.'
p17014
aS'By then, Rolling Stone was no longer the subversive publication it started out as back in 1967, but it was still far from a regular working environment.'
p17015
aS'On any given day, Eddie Vedder, Anthony Kiedis, Mick Jagger, Tom Cruise or John F. Kennedy Jr. might drop by.'
p17016
aS'My cubicle was the closest to Mr. Wenner\xe2\x80\x99s office, so I had a front-row seat to the comings and goings.'
p17017
aS'Whenever a celebrity visited, I would suddenly become the most popular person in the office, with everyone rushing to my desk to "chat" as they ogled the latest high-profile guest.'
p17018
aS'In between short bouts of actual work, I would huddle with a group of fellow employees to discuss the latest movie or book or concert that we had attended the previous night, with free tickets thanks to the generosity (and busyness) of David Fricke, the legendary Ramones-look-alike music editor; Anthony DeCurtis, the editor of the music review section; and Sid Holt, the de facto head editor of the magazine and my immediate boss.'
p17019
aS'I would often saunter to the office of my other immediate boss, Peter Travers, Rolling Stone\xe2\x80\x99s widely quoted film reviewer, hoping to talk movies.'
p17020
aS'I still cringe at my dismissal of the 1995 Todd Haynes film, "Safe," starring Julianne Moore, proclaiming it tedious and pointless in front of Mr. Travers, who, for good reasons defended it \xe2\x80\x94 and, I am sure, thought the less of me for not being able to understand its cinematic and philosophical intentions.'
p17021
aS'But I have no residue of shame for panning the insufferable "Happy Gilmore" \xe2\x80\x94 this was before Adam Sandler redeemed himself by starring in Paul Thomas Anderson\xe2\x80\x99s "Punch-Drunk Love" \xe2\x80\x94 which represented to me the most inane aspects of American culture.'
p17022
aS'Along with my secretarial responsibilities I ran the letters page and the table of contents, which meant it was my blessed duty to read everything we published.'
p17023
aS'The magazine had published the works of some of the best-known journalists of the 20th century, such as Greil Marcus, Hunter S. Thompson, Lester Bangs and Cameron Crowe, and many were still contributing \xe2\x80\x94 sometimes, on my lucky days, they visited, too.'
p17024
aS'It had also brought on many new writers, some of whom, such as Chris Mundy, Jancee Dunn and Kim Neely, became my own writing icons.'
p17025
aS'All three sat near me, and I would watch with great envy as they headed out of the office, sometimes for a few hours, often for days, to interview the person who would soon grace our cover.'
p17026
aS'Mr. Holt oversaw my editorial duties, and we often sat together to devise the table of contents.'
p17027
aS'It was during these sessions that I learned the power of the em dash in American writing, a device I now use \xe2\x80\x94 and abuse \xe2\x80\x94 in my own writing.'
p17028
aS'Though negligible by then, my Lebanese accent sometimes poked its head, often when pronouncing a word that I hadn\xe2\x80\x99t practiced enough.'
p17029
aS'At the time, Rolling Stone was trying to shift with the times.'
p17030
aS'It embraced shows like "Friends," provocatively running a photo of a naked Jennifer Aniston on its cover, and began championing the grunge phenomenon.'
p17031
aS'I still clearly remember the day news reached us that Kurt Cobain was dead, and the gloom that pervaded our offices.'
p17032
aS'We received the news the way many Americans reacted to the death of John F. Kennedy: with utter shock and a sense of despondency.'
p17033
aS'Still, the 1990s were, to a large extent, hopeful times.'
p17034
aS'America was moving forward, with Bill Clinton in the lead.'
p17035
